<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0147EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GasolineTax     12-16 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gasoline Tax,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highway Lobby Opposes Gas Tax Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers, insurance companies, contractors
and the oil industry are trying to make a pre-emptive strike against
raising the gasoline tax to cut the federal budget deficit.
   The highway lobby presented its arguments at a news conference
Thursday, saying such a tax increase would be unfair to the poor and
to residents of rural areas. It also claimed that an increase would
soak up money needed to repair the nation's highways and bridges.
   The news conference was sponsored by The Road Information
Project, which is financed by companies with a vested interest in
highways. It presented four former Federal Highway Administration
chiefs to argue against reducing the deficit by raising the gas tax.
   Ray Barnhart, Frank C. Turner, Norbert Tiemann and John Hassell
all said any gas-tax increase needs to be earmarked to repair roads
and bridges. They cited estimates that 60 percent of the nation's
paved roads and 42 percent of its bridges are substandard.
   Some members of the National Economic Commission, which was
created to recommend ways to reduce the $155-billion budget deficit,
have urged an increase of up to 50 cents in the gas tax. Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, has said he could support an increase of 10 or 15 cents _
if President-elect Bush should propose it.
   But Bush has said repeatedly he opposes any tax increase to cut
the deficit, and he specifically rejects boosting the gas tax.
   Virtually all the tax, now 9.1 cents a gallon, is earmarked for
highways, bridges and mass transit; none goes into the fund that
pays for general government services.
   Each one-cent increase in the gasoline tax would raise about $1
billion, although economists say a major boost in the tax likely
would produce a smaller per-gallon payoff because people would drive
less.
</TEXT>
