<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-16 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agriculture Department Resolves To Cure Ham Processing Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has resolved that
the new year will bring an end to a five-year rule-making snag
involving food safety and the processing of old-fashioned country
ham.
   The deadline for ham producers to comply with new federal
regulations was supposed to be Dec. 31, but it has been pushed back
to the final day of 1989. The deadline once was Dec. 31, 1987. And
before that it was Dec. 31, 1986. There also was one on Aug. 6, 1985.
   Now, the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service says it
will stick to a deadline of Dec. 31, 1989 _ or whenever the agency
finally approves the new rules, spokeswoman Irene Goins said
Thursday.
   The lengthy rule-making procedure involves those hams often seen
on grocery shelves in cloth bags or hanging from rafters in country
stores. They must be scrubbed to remove mold and then soaked or
boiled a couple of times to reduce the salt content.
   They're the kind of hams for which someone had to invent red-eye
gravy and, in some parts of the country, grits.
   As the USDA defines them, they're ``uncooked, cured, dried,
smoked or unsmoked pork products made from solid meat.''
   Typically, country or dry-cured hams are treated with salt and
then put in a smokehouse to cure and age, a total process that can
take months or even years.
   Most hams sold in supermarkets are wet-cured quickly in brine
solutions and cooked before sale to consumers.
   In March 1983, the USDA proposed rules intended to help prevent
trichinosis, a disease caused by microscopic parasitic worms, or
trichinae, that can occur in improperly cooked pork. The proposed
rules were directed at ready-to-eat pork products and dry-cured
country hams.
   Shortly after the original proposal was adopted Feb. 6, 1985, the
agency learned that some federally inspected ham producers were
using old-fashioned methods that didn't meet the new USDA
requirements and were ordered to show by Aug. 6, 1985, that their
curing procedures were safe.
   The country ham industry protested, so the USDA allowed more
time. One compelling reason for the extensions of time for
compliance was that no trichina problems had been associated with
the dry-cured hams.
   ``These traditional processing methods have been permitted
because they are decades-old methods believed to be effective in
destroying trichinae,'' says Ronald J. Prucha, acting administrator
of the USDA agency.
   ``We are researching the safety of traditional trichina control
methods and developing a proposed rule for issuance in early 1989,''
he said. ``After we receive public comments on that proposal, we
will develop new regulations.''
   But just in case the USDA's rule-making machine is slower than
officials hope, the compliance deadline was extended another full
year.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17 percent increase in the amount of raw
sugar that can be imported from 39 foreign countries in 1989 has
been announced by the Agriculture Department.
   Deputy Secretary Peter Meyers said Thursday that next year's
quota was set at about 1.24 million short tons of 2,000 pounds each,
up from about 1.06 million tons in calendar 1988.
   In metric tons, which have about 2,205 pounds each, the 1989
quota will be almost 1.13 million tons. Metric units were used to
establish next year's quota to meet the terms of a new U.S. tariff
system, which will take effect Jan. 1.
   The Dominican Republic led the list with a 1989 allocation of
185,328 metric tons, followed by the Philippines, 166,374, and
Brazil, 152,685.
   Reduced production because of this year's drought and rising
demand were the main reasons for boosting the quota so sharply,
officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peanut farmers will be allowed a bigger
government quota for their 1989 crop.
   The Agriculture Department said Thursday that the national peanut
marketing quota for 1989 will be 1.44 million tons, up 37,800 tons
from this year's quota.
   The national quota is required by law to be equal to the
estimated quantity of peanuts that will be needed for domestic
edible, seed and related uses in the 1989-90 marketing year, which
will begin Aug. 1, 1989. The quota cannot be less than 1.1 million
tons.
   Officials said the 1989 poundage quota will be allocated to each
producing state based on the state's share of the 1988 quota.
Increases in a state's quota will be allocated among qualifying
peanut farms.
   Peanut farmers voted in a referendum in January 1986 to continue
quota for crops through 1990.
</TEXT>
