<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     12-16 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Overturns President's Order To Halt Trial In Beating Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South-West African Supreme
Court has overturned an order by South African President P.W. Botha
to halt the trial of four soldiers accused of fatally beating a
black man, according to news reports.
   The Supreme Court in Windhoek, capital of the South
African-controlled territory also known as Namibia, ruled Botha's
1986 order halting the trial was invalid, newspapers reported
Thursday.
   Botha had relied on a law that said if he determined members of
the security forces were acting in good faith to combat terrorism,
they could not be tried for acts they committed.
   But the court ruled Wednesday that Botha could not legally make
such a decision because he did not receive the proper report about
the case. The court said the report, signed by Defense Minister
Magnus Malan, was ``most misleading,'' and that the investigator
failed to talk to witnesses.
   Mweunhanga Uapota, wife of the dead man, brought the appeal. In
her affidavit she said she, her husband Frans, and some friends were
gathered at a shop in Onengali, in northern Namibia, when soldiers
appeared, forced them to lie down, kicked them, blindfolded and
assaulted her husband.
   The court noted the defendants did not deny the allegations.
   It also noted the post-mortem report, detailing Uapota's
injuries, was not submitted to the president, and he also was not
given information showing Uapota was never involved in terrorism.
   The autopsy report said Uapota died from massive bleeding on the
brain, caused by head injury. It also said he had serious injuries
to the upper abdomen and chest, a broken neck and injuries
``consistent with a rope having been tied around the deceased's
neck.''
   Under an agreement this week among South Africa, Cuba and Angola,
Cuba is to withdraw its troops from Angola, and South-West Africa is
to become independent.
   In other developments:
   _ Piet Rudolph, a leading member of two right-wing pro-apartheid
organizations, was freed on $42 bail Thursday after being charged in
connection with a shooting in downtown Pretoria.
   _ Two limpet mines exploded Thursday in Randfontein, a mining and
commercial center west of Johannesburg, causing slight damage and no
casualties, police reported.
   _ Botha demanded that Free Weekly, a new Afrikaans-language
paper, pay him $42,000 and publish an apology for a story saying he
had dined with an ``infamous Mafia boss.'' The paper refused on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
