<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Press     12-16 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Press,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Change Rules On Talking With Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush is fed up with being
peppered with questions while posing for pictures, and says he won't
let that happen during photo-taking sessions after his inauguration.
   ``Talking at photo ops will continue until Jan. 20 and after that
there will be absolutely none,'' Bush admonished reporters Thursday.
   He told the journalists his new press policy was for their own
good because shouting questions during photo opportunities was
``demeaning to your profession.''
   There was no shouting during the session that sparked Bush's
edict, just a reprise of the usual questions the vice president gets
these days about when he will finish naming his Cabinet.
   Earlier, Bush was asked about Yasser Arafat while he posed for
posterity with Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita.
   While Bush held few news conferences during the campaign, he has
faced reporters for extensive questioning repeatedly since the
election, turning each of his Cabinet announcements into news
conferences.
   He also has been responding to questions at the picture-taking
sessions in the White House with visiting dignitaries, politicians
or guests, where a pool of 10 or 15 reporters, photographers and
camera crews are ushered in for the opening minute.
   The photo opportunity at times has been the White House press
corps' main avenue of communication with President Reagan, who has
held fewer news conferences than any modern president and who often
seemed to enjoy firing off one-liners during these brief encounters
with the press.
   The Reagan administration made an attempt to muzzle reporters
during photo-opportunity sessions, but backed off when the
television networks refused to send in their camera crews without
their correspondents.
   Mary Martin, deputy Washington bureau chief for CBS News, said
Thursday night, ``When information is needed, we're going to ask
questions.''
   But she added, ``If the vice president makes himself available to
answer questions at other times, it becomes less necessary to pursue
your questions at photo opportunities.''
   That may be what Bush has in mind. ``I hope that we can work out
something that's satisfactory to all,'' he said.
   Top aides have said they expect Bush to have frequent, short
contacts with the news media, possibly several times a week.
   ``I'll have other ways of communicating that will be much more
pleasant for you and much more pleasant for me and much more
respectful of our guests like foreign visitors,'' Bush told
reporters.
   Asked if he would hold regular news conferences, Bush said, ``Oh,
sure there'll be news conferences.'' He said they would not be
``regular'' _ ``That idea went out years ago'' _ but ``frequent
ones.''
   ``But not shouted questions,'' he reiterated. ``It's demeaning to
your profession. You shouldn't have to yell at me to get an answer.''
   He said he would permit the shouted questions to continue during
the transition ``because there's a certain fun. I like the give and
take of it. It's humility.''
   But he predicted that ending such situations ``will be a great
relief to the photographers and ... to the serious reporters that
would like answers and not have to yell over a helicopter
someplace.''
</TEXT>
