<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Cyprus     12-16 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Cyprus,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Extends Cyprus Peacekeeping Six Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council has extended the U.N.
peacekeeping mission on Cyprus for six months and expressed hope
rival Turkish and Greek Cypriot communities will resolve their
conflict by June.
   After the council voted 15-0 on Thursday to extend the mandate of
the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus, representatives of Greece,
Turkey, and the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities debated anew
who began the conflict.
   Turkish Cypriot Representative Ozer Koray accused Greece and the
Greek Cypriot community of ``importing arms from Greece and also
setting up weaponry plants.''
   Cypriot Ambassador Constantine Moushoutas, speaking for Greek
Cypriots, blamed the crisis on ``the Turkish invasion and
occupation.'' He noted past Security Council resolutions call for
withdrawing all foreign troops and settlers from the island.
   In 1974, a coup by Greece's ruling military junta failed on the
island. Turkey invaded the northern part of Cyprus, saying it was
protecting the minority Turkish Cypriot community, and sent
thousands of Turks to settle in the north.
   Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in 1975 proclaimed the
northern part of the island an independent Turkish state but the
only diplomatic recognition it has won is from Turkey.
   Cypriot President George Vassiliou, who leads the Greek
community, and Denktash have held a series of talks aimed at setting
up a republic containing both communities.
   The talks have been deadlocked. Another round is scheduled to
begin Monday.
   The U.N. peacekeepers on Cyprus are funded by voluntary
contributions from U.N. member states, but a report to the council
by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said donations have not
been coming in.
</TEXT>
