<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pentagon-HealthFees     12-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon-Health Fees,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Kills Plan To Charge For Military Medical Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has killed
a White House proposal to charge military dependents and retirees a
fee for health care, sources said.
   The sources, who spoke Thursday on condition they not be
identified, said Carlucci had intervened personally with officials
at the Office of Management and Budget to scuttle the idea.
   ``OMB is backing down,'' one ranking Pentagon official said.
``This plan will be scrapped.''
   The Pentagon's chief spokesman, Dan Howard, declined to say
Thursday whether OMB had agreed to discard the plan. But Howard made
it clear that Carlucci had fought the budget office over the matter.
   ``The secretary understands that the military member and his
family count medical care in the system as one of their most
important fundamental benefits,'' Howard said.
   ``An increase and change in charging fees to our service
personnel would constitute a decrease in their net pay and benefits
package. And changing this benefit would be a breach of faith with
our military service members, their families and our retirees, and
have a negative effect on attracting and retaining quality
personnel.''
   Earlier this week, defense officials disclosed that OMB was
pressing the Pentagon to begin levying user fees starting next Oct.
1. The sources, who claimed Pentagon officials were going
``bananas'' over the prospect of the user fees, said the plan was
advanced by OMB for inclusion in the Defense Department's fiscal
1990 budget proposal. The budget is scheduled to be submitted to
Congress on Jan. 9.
   Under the plan, military dependents and retirees would have been
charged $10 for every outpatient doctor visit up to an annual
ceiling of $100; $3 to have prescriptions filled; and $50 for
admission to a military hospital.
   Men and women on active duty would not have been affected, nor
would the dependents of enlisted personnel in the bottom four
enlisted ranks.
   In addition, the plan called for a doubling of the annual
insurance deductible for dependents and retirees who turn to private
physicians instead of using military facilities. The so-called
CHAMPUS insurance deductibles would have increased from $50 to $100
for individuals and $100 to $200 for families.
   Currently, military dependents and retirees are allowed to use
military hospitals on a ``space available'' basis, with active-duty
personnel always having priority. But when a dependent or retiree is
admitted to a hospital or uses other services, the only fee he or
she pays is a nominal subsistence fee for food while hospitalized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
