<HEAD>$53 Billion Budget For 1989 Adopted By EEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Plumb, president of the European
Parliament, signed the European Economic Community's 1989 budget
into law.
   The budget, signed Thursday, amounts to $52.8 billion, with
farm-spending set at $31.5 billion, or 56 percent of the total.
   It was the first time agriculture payments were kept to under 60
percent of the budget since the EEC, or Common Market, was founded
31 years ago. The lower agriculture figure was the result of a deal
hammered out by the 12 EEC leaders in Brussels in February to
strictly control farm payments.
   The cut was made possible by higher-than-forecast world cereal
prices and a cheaper U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
