<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Military     12-16 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Military,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Gets New Chief of General Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union announced that Col. Gen. Mikhail
A. Moiseyev will be the new military chief of staff, an appointment
that appears to signal Mikhail S. Gorbachev's desire to bring new
faces into the Red Army leadership.
   Moiseyev, 49, was appointed over several more senior officers and
is the first military leader too young to have taken part in the
Soviet victory over Nazi Germany in World War II.
   His appointment to replace Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev was
announced Thursday in the Defense Ministry newspaper Red Star.
   Akhromeyev's retirement was announced by Soviet officials in New
York Dec. 7, the day Gorbachev told the United Nations he would
unilaterally cut the Soviet military.
   That caused speculation the 65-year-old Akhromeyev was resigning
in protest. Soviet officials denied this.
   Thursday's Red Star story was the first public announcement in
the Soviet Union of Akhromeyev's retirement.
   Moiseyev's previous post was as Red Army commander in the Far
East.
   Western diplomatic sources in Moscow said little is known about
Moiseyev, who now becomes a first deputy defense minister and the
No. 2 leader under Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov.
   One source said Moiseyev was promoted to his present rank in
November 1987. ``It may suggest to some of the old-timers that it's
time to hang it up,'' said the source, who spoke on condition he not
be identified.
   Moiseyev's areas of military expertise were not known, and the
diplomatic source said it was likely that since he has been serving
in the Far East, ``the people on the general staff who will work for
him don't know him either.''
   It was not known whether Moiseyev was a protege of Yazov, but
Yazov also served as commander of the heavily fortified Far East
district before being named defense minister in May 1987.
   Yazov is known as a strong proponent of reforms in the Soviet
military in line with Gorbachev's effort to restructure Soviet
society. Akhromeyev was one of the officials Gorbachev passed over
when Yazov was named defense minister.
   Red Star said Akhromeyev was being transferred to another job. In
his announcement of Akhromeyev's retirement last week, the Foreign
Ministry spokesman, Gennady I. Gerasimov, said he would remain an
adviser to Gorbachev.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Viktor Karpov said at a news conference
Thursday that Akhromeyev's retirement ``is in no way connected with
the Soviet troop reductions announced by Mikhail Gorbachev at the
United Nations.''
   Born into a working class family in 1939, Moiseyev joined the
Soviet army in 1958 and graduated from the Frunze Military Academy
and the military academy of the armed forces' general staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
