<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalEarthquake     12-16 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Earthquake,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Earthquake Jars Weather-beaten Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp earthquake that may have been
an aftershock to a quake two years ago jolted Southern California,
shattering windows and knocking pictures askew but causing no
serious damage or injury.
   The quake, centered about 13 miles northwest of here, struck at
9:53 p.m. Thursday and was felt in at least five Southern California
counties from Palm Springs to Los Angeles 110 miles to the west, and
San Diego 135 miles to the southeast, authorities said.
   ``It was sort of like riding a hobby horse,'' said Georgia
Duncan, a San Bernardino County sheriff's dispatcher in Victorville,
60 miles northwest of Palm Springs. ``The windows rattled and stuff
on the cabinet sort of bounced around.''
   The temblor measured 4.8 on the Richter scale of ground motion,
said Hall Daily, spokesman for Pasadena's California Institute of
Technology, which studies earthquake activity.
   ``I think it was the strongest one we had since the big one in
'86,'' said Palm Springs police Sgt. Ron Starrs, referring to a
5.6-magnitude quake that rocked Palm Springs on July 8, 1986,
causing $5.3 million in property damage.
   The latest quake, which jolted a state still suffering from the
effects of high winds, fires and snowstorms in the last week, might
have been an aftershock of the 1986 temblor, Daily said.
   ``The seismologists are looking into that possibility,'' he said.
   The quake knocked over liquor bottles and glasses at Pompeii
Nightclub here, where a few patrons headed for the door, said
manager Johnny Boreta.
   ``It was a little shaker,'' said Diana Perri, manager of Bono's,
a restaurant owned by Palm Springs' celebrity mayor, Sonny Bono.
``Mr. and Mrs. Bono did give us a call to make sure we were all OK.''
   About 15 moviegoers fled a theater at the Palm Desert Town
Center, but most of the 200 people in the audience chose to sit it
out.
   Plate glass windows bowed at the Palm Springs police station and
rims around ceiling sprinkler heads fell to the floor, but few other
problems were reported, Starrs said.
   Local hospitals reported no quake-related injuries.
   ``The most we had were some broken store windows downtown,'' said
police Lt. Mike McCabe in Palm Springs.
   In nearby Palm Desert, Mary Jo Lyon said the mirror on her
bedroom wall shook and she ran from the room to check on her
Christmas tree, which listed to one side after the jolt.
   ``It shook me up,'' she said.
   Donna Smiler, an employee of a 7-Eleven store in Palm Springs,
said the temblor was brief.
   ``I just sat here and watched everything move. All of our signs
shook. You could hear it, it was a definite rumble,'' she said.
   In Los Angeles, Chris Harris of Hollywood said his typewriter
fell off his desk, and pictures were knocked askew.
   The earthquake was the second substantial tremor this month in
Southern California.
   On Dec. 3, a 5.0-magnitude quake struck beneath downtown
Pasadena. That quake was felt in seven counties, but damage was
mostly limited to the contents of store shelves and windows.
   The most recent quake to cause extensive damage in metropolitan
Los Angeles was a 5.9-magnitude temblor that caused damage estimated
at $358 million. Eight deaths and more than 200 injuries were
attributed to that quake and its 5.3-magnitude aftershock on Oct. 4,
1987.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage and 6
severe damage.
</TEXT>
