<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Arafat-US     12-16 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arafat-US,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Changed Stand On PLO After Arafat Threat, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. administration decided to talk with the
Palestine Liberation Organization after chairman Yasser Arafat
threatened to resign, according to a published report today.
   The Al-Qabas daily newspaper, quoting an unnamed senior Arab
official, said Arafat was going to announce his resignation at a
news conference Wednesday in Geneva only hours before President
Reagan said U.S. officials would open a dialogue with the
long-shunned PLO.
   There was no immediate independent confirmation of the report.
   Al-Qabas said Swedish Foreign Minister Sten Andersson, who acted
as a mediator between the PLO and Washington, asked Arafat to
postpone the decision or at least refrain from announcing it until
Andersson had contacted Washington.
   The daily said Arafat postponed his news conference for several
hours until Wednesday evening while Andersson contacted U.S.
Secretary of State George Shultz ``about Arafat's plan to resign.''
   The paper quoted Arafat as saying: ``If the moderate Palestinian
leadership does not suit the Americans, then let them reach
understanding with another leadership.''
   The inference appeared to be that if Arafat quit, more militant
and less flexible figures could take over.
   The paper said that following a telephone call by Andersson, the
Reagan administration advised him they would announce their decision
to open a dialogue with the PLO.
   The Americans cited Arafat's explicit recognition of Israel's
right to exist and renunciation of terrorism as the reason they
decided to talk with the PLO.
</TEXT>
