<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0540EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--Syphilis     12-16 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--Syphilis,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Real Change' In Syphilis: More Prostitutes, Drug Users</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While syphilis is occuring less frequently among
homosexuals, cases of the disease have sharply increased among
prostitutes and drug abusers who may be trading sex for drugs,
federal health officials say.
   Studies in Philadelphia and Connecticut have noted significant
rises in the last three years in the numbers of syphilis patients
from the latter two groups, the national Centers for Disease Control
said Thursday.
   ``The magnitude of the increase ... suggests that the trends
observed in Connecticut and Philadelphia reflect real changes,'' the
CDC said. ``The emergence of syphilis among prostitutes, drug users
and their sexual contacts may be a widespread national phenomenon.''
   ``Obviously, biologically, there's no interaction that we know of
between drug use and syphilis,'' said Dr. Jonathan Zenilman, a CDC
specialist in sexually transmitted diseases. ``Certainly, what this
looks like is that it may be a sex-for-drugs type of phenomenon.''
   For example, the CDC reported that in Connecticut, the percentage
of female syphilis patients reporting that they were prostitutes
rose from 7 percent in 1985 to 21 percent in 1987; the percentage of
females with syphilis reporting drug use rose from zero to 14
percent.
   Among heterosexual males in Philadelphia, the percentage of
syphilis patients reporting contact with prostitutes rose from 2
percent to 21 percent, while the percentage reporting drug use rose
from 5 to 13.
   As syphilis skyrockets among prostitutes and drug users, it's
dropping among homosexuals, the CDC noted. In the 1985-87 studies,
the percentage of male syphilis patients reporting that they were
homosexual or bisexual dropped sharply _ from 38 percent to 11
percent in Connecticut; from 53 percent to 18 percent in
Philadelphia.
   In the wake of AIDS, which strikes most often among homosexual
men and drug abusers, ``the gay community has had substantial
(safe-sex) education efforts,'' Zenilman said. ``The gay community
itself is one that may be more responsive to behavior modification.
   ``The drug abusing community has always been more difficult to
reach. Somebody looking for a fix is not always interested in the
long term.''
   Through last week, 37,985 civilian syphilis cases had been
reported in the United States this year, up 14 percent from the same
time a year ago and up 45 percent compared to the median for the
past five years.
   ``That's almost exclusively among heterosexual men,'' Zenilman
said, noting that the national total is increasing while the
proportion in homosexual men in decreasing.
   The CDC's report, prepared by Dr. Robert Rolfs of the
Atlanta-based agency, said that limiting the spread of syphilis may
require new tactics ``to better identify and treat syphilis-infected
prostitutes, drug users and their sexual contacts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
