<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0472,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide Says Shamir Planning New Peace Initiative, Denies Autonomy
Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 16 beginning: But the ... in Washington to restore
dropped first name. Picks up graf 17 pvs, `The first ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, seeking to
counter the new U.S.-PLO dialogue, plans to launch a new peace
initiative once a coalition government has been formed, a top aide
said today.
   ``Mr. Shamir is considering new moves after he forms the
government,'' said Shamir spokesman Avi Pazner. ``He is seriously
considering options on how to act in the diplomatic field.''
   Pazner would not elaborate, but he denied a report in the Haaretz
daily newspaper that Shamir considered granting autonomy to the 1.7
million Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Mr. Shamir believes that unilateral moves have no value,''
Pazner told The Associated Press. ``He believes only an agreement
resulting from negotiations is viable.''
   Haaretz quoted officials close to Shamir as saying the prime
minister, who heads the right-wing Likud bloc, wanted to form a
coalition with the left-leaning Labor Party as quickly as possible
and then launch a peace initiative focusing on autonomy.
   The newspaper also said Shamir was deeply hurt by President
Reagan's decision Wednesday to open talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which Israel considers a terrorist
organization.
   In a meeting with U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering on Thursday,
Shamir said the U.S. decision was a ``terrible mistake,'' and he
criticized Washington for not informing Israel about it sooner,
Haaretz said.
   ``This behavior is unacceptable between two allies,'' Haaretz
quoted Shamir as telling Pickering.
   Washington's announcement that it would meet with the PLO came
after PLO chairman Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism and said he
recognized Israel's right to exist.
   Pazner predicted the talks would fail.
   ``We believe that the United States will discover very soon the
true face of the PLO and will realize that it can not be a partner
for negotiations and peace,'' he said.
   Israel wants to see the U.S. initiative fail quickly, or it will
face mounting international pressure for a favorable response to the
PLO, analysts said.
   A delay in the response could endanger relations with Washington,
Israel's main ally and the source of $3 billion in annual aid.
   But Ariel Merari of the Tel Aviv University's Jaffee Center for
Strategic Studies predicted U.S.-PLO contacts would last for
``months or even a year without any dramatic developments'' as they
focus on questions of procedure.
   An agreement on a U.N.-sponsored peace conference would be the
likely outcome of successful U.S.-PLO talks. Many Israelis view it
as a forum for demanding far-reaching land concessions from the
Jewish state.
   But the first item on the agenda of U.S.-PLO contacts will be the
question of terrorism, Secretary of State George P. Shultz told
Israeli reporters in Washington.
   ``The first point we will make in that dialogue is to emphasize
our total rejection of terrorism anywhere, outside Israel, inside
Israel,'' Shultz said in remarks broadcast on Israel television.
   Merari, an expert on terrorism, said Arafat may order his Fatah
faction to refrain from terror attacks abroad or attempts to
infiltrate Israel on hostage-taking missions. But he said terror
linked to the Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories will
continue.
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Palestinians called the U.S.
move a victory of their yearlong revolt, which has left at least 326
Palestinians and 13 Israelis dead.
   Dozens of Jewish settlers from the territories began a hunger
strike and pitched tents in front of Shamir's office.
   ``The U.S. policy of recognizing the PLO is the seed of the next
war,'' said Ron Nachman, a settler leader. ``Israel cannot reach
agreement with the PLO. There's no common ground and the result will
be an explosion.''
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, a political rival of Shamir, said
the Jewish state had to come up ``with a new political initiative as
an answer to this situation.''
   Peres proposed elections in the occupied territories to choose
Palestinian leaders for peace negotiations, saying Israel ``will not
negotiate with an armed delegation instead of an elected one.''
   Within Peres' left-leaning Labor party, a group of 30 doves
called on the leadership to change the party platform and allow
contacts with the PLO.
   Ezer Weizman, a Labor Cabinet minister without portfolio, said
Arafat's statements made the PLO a satisfactory partner.
   ``I think a new era has opened,'' he said. ``Now our political
platform must be reconsidered.''
</TEXT>
