<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stubborn Storm Belts Southern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stubborn storm lingered off the southern coast of California
today, pelting the area with rain, up to 6 inches of wet snow and
stiff winds gusting as high as 60 mph.
   Snow fell on much of San Luis Obispo County, bringing highway
traffic to a near standstill. Six inches of snow fell at Santa
Margarita and Cuesta Ridge; 1 to 4 inches blanketed Paso Robles
City; and 4 inches of snow hit Atascadero.
   The storm remaining off California's southern coast brought the
strong winds and rain, with the rain changing to snow in higher
elevations. The storm was not expected to move much today.
   Heavier rainfall by early this morning included almost 2 inches
at Mount Wilson, Calif.
   The storm was to produce as much as 2 feet of snow in the higher
elevations by Sunday morning and winds gusting as high as 60 mph.
   In the East, a snow squall warning was posted early today over
north, central New York and along the eastern shores of Lake
Ontario, where up to 6 inches of snow was forecast to fall this
morning.
   Wind chills remained in the bitter cold range over northern New
York. By midnight, Massina reached 3 degrees above zero and the 15
to 20 mph winds brought a wind chill of 30 below zero.
   By midnight snowfall extended from western New York across
northwest Pennsylvania, Michigan, North Dakota and southeast
Colorado. Also, rain reached from the Florida panhandle across
southern Alabama and central Georgia into central South Carolina.
   Today's forecast called for snow from eastern North Dakota across
Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and upper Michigan, as well as through
the southern Rockies; and rain from central California across
southwest California, becoming snow in the mountains of Southern
California.
   High temperatures were forecast in the single digits and the
teens from northern New England across the Great Lakes, Minnesota
and eastern North Dakota; in the 20s and 30s from central New
England through North Carolina, over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,
from Iowa across Arkansas, the rest of the northern half of the
Plains, the Rockies and the northern half of the Plateau; in the 40s
and 50s from South Carolina across northern Florida, from the
central Gulf of Mexico states across Louisiana and New Mexico; in
the 50s over much of California and the 60s over the inland
Southwest and in the 70s over southern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at Wausau, Wis., to 82 degrees at Homestead, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 40 cloudy; Boston 20 windy; Buffalo 18 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 53 rain; Cincinnati 18 fair; Cleveland 21 snow;
Detroit 12 fair; Miami 67 partly cloudy; New York 23 windy;
Philadelphia 25 windy; Pittsburgh 14 fair; Portland, Maine 16 fair;
Washington 26 windy.
   _Central: Bismarck 26 windy; Chicago fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 35
partly cloudy; Denver fair; Des Moines fair; Indianapolis 13 fair;
Kansas City fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul cloudy; Nashville 24 fair;
New Orleans 46 drizzle; St. Louis 14 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 23 fair; Anchorage 33 rain; Las Vegas 40 fair;
Los Angeles 55 showery; Phoenix 53 fair; Salt Lake City 22 fair; San
Diego 56 rain; San Francisco 51 partly cloudy; Seattle 35 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal fair; Toronto 12 partly cloudy.
