<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial     12-16 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summations Expected To End Today In `Bess Mess' Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Summations expected to resume at 8:30 a.m.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bess Myerson's lawyer, saying prosecutors were
driven by desperation in their attempts to convict the former Miss
America of conspiracy, told jurors in his summation, ``You will
never see anything as low.''
   Attorney Frederick Hafetz on Thursday said the case against Miss
Myerson, who is accused of trying to influence a judge, was based
primarily on circumstantial evidence and lambasted the government
for its use of an unreliable star witness.
   He noted that Assistant U.S. Attorney Stuart Abrams, in his
summation, made much of the fact that during the spring and summer
of 1983, Miss Myerson was calling the judge on her private line
while using an assumed name.
   ``You only do something like that when you know you're doing
something wrong,'' Abrams told the jury earlier this week.
   Hafetz conceded that evidence about the mysterious phone calls
``sounds suspicious'' and ``sexy.'' But, he countered, ``there is
not one whit of evidence the government needs to sustain a criminal
conspiracy.''
   Meantime, U.S. District Judge John F. Keenan, who plans to give
the 11-week-old case to jurors on Monday, ordered an early start for
today's session and said lawyers for both sides would have only
until day's end to finish arguing their case.
   He said it would be unfair for government lawyers to have all
weekend to work on a rebuttal.
   Miss Myerson, Miss America 1945 and once New York City's cultural
affairs commissioner, is accused of trying to influence a judge's
rulings in the divorce of her lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, by
giving a city job to the judge's daughter, Sukhreet Gabel.
   Miss Myerson, Capasso and the former judge are all on trial.
   According to prosecutors, former state Supreme Court Justice
Hortense Gabel slashed Capasso's weekly support payments to his
estranged wife after Miss Myerson gave the $19,000-a-year job to
Sukhreet Gabel in August 1983.
   Hafetz likened the gossipy testimony of many prosecution
witnesses to a soap opera, saying ``it has been rich in gossip, it
has been rich in rumor, it has been rich in innuendo but the only
thing it hasn't been rich in is hard evidence.''
   But his harshest criticism was reserved for the use of Ms. Gabel
as a witness against her mother.
   Ms. Gabel, 39, said she took shopping bags full of documents from
her mother's home to prosecutors and twice tape-recorded phone
conversations with her mother for the government.
   ``Shame on them!'' Hafetz said of the prosecution. ``It's a low,
an all-time low. You can sit in an American courtroom for the rest
of your life and you will never see anything as low.''
   Hafetz, who got Ms. Gabel to admit on cross-examination that
electroshock treatments for clinical depression had left her memory
like ``Swiss cheese,'' asked the jury: ``Are they so desperate? Do
they want to win the case that badly that they will stoop into the
gutter with such indecent behavior.''
   Miss Myerson, 64; Capasso, 43, and Mrs. Gabel, 75, who made
interim rulings in Capasso's bitter divorce, are all charged with
conspiracy, fraud and bribe-related charges.
   Miss Myerson is also charged with obstruction of justice. She
faces a maximum penalty of 30 years in prison if convicted of all
charges.
   Her two co-defendants face up to 25 years in prison, if convicted.
</TEXT>
