<DOCNO> AP881216-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Laos-USMIAs     12-16 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laos-US MIAs,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains Found In Joint Excavation Of U.S. Warplane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Laotian team found one set of
human remains during a joint excavation of an American warplane
crash site that ended today, a U.S. spokesman said.
   The seven-day excavation was aimed at resolving the fate of the
pilot of a reconnaissance aircraft shot down in March 1968 over
Sepone, in Laos' southern Savannakhet province, said Lt. Col. Thomas
J. Boyd, a spokesman for the U.S. Pacific Command.
   He said much of the plane wreckage remained at the site, a
sparsely populated, overgrown jungle.
   ``Remains were found at the site and have been flown to Bangkok
today,'' Boyd said. ``They will then be flown to the Army Central
Identification Laboratory in Hawaii for evaluation.''
   He said the 16-member U.S. military team received good
cooperation from the Laotian government and local residents, and the
United States hoped for more such efforts to account for the 547
Americans missing in action in Laos. The team worked with 20 Laotian
workers.
   Many of the Americans missing in Laos were airmen on missions to
interdict the Ho Chi Minh Trail, a route in Laos which Communist
North Vietnam used to send men and supplies to U.S.-backed South
Vietnam during the Vietnam War.
   It was the fourth joint excavation in Laos. Boyd said the
American team also looked at other crash sites that may be jointly
excavated in the future.
   Most team members were from the Army laboratory and the U.S.
Joint Casualty Resolution Center, also based in Honolulu. They
stayed in pitched tents and lived military-style during the project.
   In total, 1,747 Americans are listed as missing in action from
the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
