<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vanuatu     12-16 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vanuatu,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Dissolves Parliament, Orders New Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Sokomanu dissolved
parliament today and ordered national elections in February for the
politically troubled South Pacific country.
   His announcement follows months of political turmoil in this
former Anglo-French territory, once called the New Hebrides.
   Sokomanu, citing economic problems and reports of violence, took
the action after Prime Minister Walter Lini's government handily won
by-elections this week.
   Longtime rival Barak Sope, who challenged Lini's leadership by
boycotting the polls, led a demonstration today outside the
parliament in defiance of a government ban against such gatherings.
   Roads leading to the capital were blocked and cars were searched
for weapons, while police in riot-gear manned barricades around
Parliament House. Most of central Vila was boarded up in
anticipation of violence.
   Local radio meanwhile said an Australian tourist was recovering
after being shot in the shoulder late Thursday by a member of the
paramilitary Vanuatu Mobile Force.
   The teen-ager, Michael Hendersen, was shot when he drove through
a checkpoint without stopping, news reports said.
   An Australian Embassy spokesman said Henderson was in a local
hospital recovering from surgery.
   The Australian Associated Press said Sokomanu dissolved
parliament during a 30-minute speech in Vanuatu's Bislama language.
   Sokomanu blamed Vanuatu's economic problems on the current
political turmoil.
   This week's ballot, which was boycotted by the main opposition
parties, gave Lini control of two-thirds of the 46-seat parliament.
</TEXT>
