<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-16 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHARDSON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl would like to find a
man who acted like Santa Claus but looked ``like Superman'' so she
could thank him for making a Christmas wish come true.
   Judy Darr was shopping with her parents last Sunday at Zale's at
Valley View Mall in Dallas when a crystal teddy bear caught her eye.
It cost $30.
   The girl told her father if she saved $7 more, she'd have enough
for the bear. The family continued shopping, and a few minutes later
``a gentleman came up and dropped a box in front of me,'' Judy wrote
in a letter to the Dallas Times Herald.
   ``He tapped me on the shoulder and said, `Merry Christmas.' We
looked up, and he was gone. We opened the box, and there was a
beautiful crystal teddy bear,'' she wrote.
   ``We were startled and looked around for him. We could not find
him. Now I have the teddy bear on my TV stand. Every time I look at
it or think of it, I wish I could thank him. I hope he will read
this and know I wish him a Merry Christmas.''
   Patricia Bohn, the girl's mother, said her daughter described the
man as looking ``like Superman before he was Superman, which I guess
means like Clark Kent.''
   The third-grader ``is obsessed with trying to thank this man,''
her mother said.
   Mrs. Bohn said this stranger has brought the meaning of Christmas
home to her family.
   ``It's experiences like this that renew our faith in people, that
they are good and kind,'' Mrs. Bohn said. ``This man made a little
girl very happy, and she wants to grow up and be just like that. I
wish we could thank him.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Motor Vehicles Division computer,
showing no deference for politicians, scheduled Gov.-elect Judd
Gregg for an eye exam for his license renewal on inauguration day.
   ``I think it would be fair to say we've got a scheduling conflict
here,'' said Gregg's spokesman, Brian Grip.
   The division expects to change the appointment.
   ``I'm sure they will be more than happy to change it for him to a
time that is more convenient,'' a motor vehicles official said.
   Gregg is to be sworn in at the Statehouse at noon on Jan. 5. His
eye exam appointment is in Peterborough, more than an hour away, at
1 p.m.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chisholm High School officials don't know who
to blame: the publisher, the postal service or school officials, but
yearbooks for the class of 1986 arrived a little late.
   The school received them Tuesday.
   Some of the students who ordered and paid $20 for the yearbooks
are now juniors in college, said school Superintendent Alan
Livingston.
   ``It's been a fiasco,'' Livingston said.
   School officials mailed material for the yearbook to Taylor
Publishing Co., of Dallas, four separate times, Livingston said.
Some material sent by certified mail was received. Other material,
sent uncertified, was not and had to be redone.
   ``Everytime we'd get a notice the material didn't make it, I'd
get out my Kleenex box and cry a little,'' Livingston said.
   Each time the yearbook material was lost, publishing company
executives searched their warehouses but never found it.
   ``Was the U.S. mail service that poor, to lose it four times? I
don't think so,'' Livingston said.
   That leaves Taylor Publishing. Livingston is willing to let them
off the hook too.
   ``Do I think we dropped the ball and messed up? That I don't
know,'' Livingston said.
</TEXT>
