<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-PlaneCrash     12-16 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Plane Crash,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Killed In Commuter Crash In Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter airplane crashed today in a
remote gold-mining region of western Australia, killing all 10
people aboard, officials said.
   The twin-engine plane exploded in a ball of flames, local
residents said, scattering wreckage across a wide area. The crash
occurred in the desert near the gold-mining town of Leonara,
authorities said.
   Civil Aviation Authority spokesman Doug Holden said the plane
spiralled to the ground near an Outback ranch from an altitude of
about 5,000 feet.
   The turboprop, chartered by a mining company, was en route to
Kalgoolie, site of the Australian gold rush of the late 1800s.
   It was the worst air accident in Australia since 1983, when 12
people were killed in the crash of another mining company plane in
Queensland.
   The Australian Associated Press said the plane was believed to be
transporting directors and staff of the Perth-based Independent
Resources Ltd., a mining company.
   Police said the victims included the pilot, six women and three
men.
   Air safety investigators were sifting through the wreckage to
determine the cause of the crash.
</TEXT>
