<DOCNO> AP881216-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-GandhiAssassination     12-16 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Gandhi Assassination,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Directed To Review Gandhi Assassin's Mercy Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today directed the
president to reconsider the mercy petition of a Sikh sentenced to
death for the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi.
   A five-judge panel headed by Chief Justice R.S. Pathak ordered
the execution of the Sikh, Kehar Singh, be held in abeyance in the
meantime.
   Lawyers said the stay also applies automatically to the execution
of Satwant Singh, the other Sikh sentenced to death in the case.
   A trial court convicted the two in 1986 and sentenced them to
hang. The convictions and the sentences were upheld by the Delhi
High Court later that year and by the Supreme Court in August.
   Kehar Singh, convicted of conspiracy in the case, appealed to
President Ramaswamy Venkataraman for mercy, the only recourse left
to a prisoner condemned to death by the Supreme Court. The president
dismissed the appeal last month and said in a letter he could not
consider the merits of a case already decided by the highest court
in the land.
   The rejection of the appeal was challenged by Kehar Singh's
lawyers, who claimed Venkataraman had powers to reconsider the
facts. The challenge came 15 hours before the two Sikhs were
scheduled to be hanged at New Delhi's Tihar Jail on Dec. 2. The
death sentences have been stayed since then.
   The judges ruled the president has the power to go into the
merits of the case, despite the Supreme Court's rulings.
   ``They've done justice. It's a great judgment,'' said Rajender
Singh, Kehar Singh's son, who was in court for the verdict of the
five-judge panel.
   R.S. Sodhi, the lawyer for Satwant Singh, said the stay on the
execution applied also to his client.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot in the garden of her New Delhi residence on
Oct. 31, 1984, by two of her Sikh bodyguards. One of them, Beant
Singh, was killed in a shootout with other bodyguards minutes later.
   The other assassin, Satwant Singh, was arrested and charged after
he recovered from gunshot wounds received in the shootout.
   Kehar Singh, a maternal uncle of Beant Singh, was arrested later
and charged with conspiracy.
   All Sikhs take the name Singh, which means lion in the Punjabi
language, by doctrine of their faith.
   Mrs. Gandh's assassination was in revenge for an army raid she
had ordered four months earlier on the Golden Temple, Sikhism's
holiest shrine.
   The shrine in Amritsar had been taken over by armed Sikh
militants agitating for an independent homeland in the northern
state of Punjab. About 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died in the
army raid.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are a
majority in Punjab. Sikh militants have been fighting for a separate
state since 1982, claiming discrimination by the Hindu community,
which makes up 80 percent of the country's population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
