<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bombs,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Damage Government Offices In Three Areas Near Cape Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs damaged government offices
in three white communities near Cape Town but caused no injuries,
police said today.
   Police said the first explosion damaged the magistrate's court in
Paarl, a wine-growing town where African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela was transferred to a prison farm Dec. 7.
   The explosion occurred overnight, police said.
   There did not appear to be any connection between it and
Mandela's presence at the Victor Verster prison farm in Paarl.
Mandela, 70, was moved from a Cape Town clinic, where he had been
treated for tuberculosis. He is serving a life sentence for plotting
to overthrow the government.
   Two other overnight bombs caused limited damage to municipal
offices in the Parow and Goodwood residential areas, police said.
   Two more bombs slightly damaged a police station and library
early Thursday in Randfontein, a mining center west of Johannesburg,
police said.
   Most bomb explosions in South Africa are attributed to ANC
members or other militants opposed to apartheid, under which the
nation's black majority has no voice in national affairs.
</TEXT>
