<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0824EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cambodia-Vietnam     12-16 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Nearly All Vietnamese Advisers Have Left</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen said today all
of Vietnam's advisers and nearly three-quarters of its troops have
left Cambodia, but he said his government can defend itself against
the Khmer Rouge and other guerrillas.
   Noting that all Vietnamese troops are to be out of his country by
1990, Hun Sen said, ``We still have two years and we must race
quickly to get ready.''
   Hun Sen spoke to about 150 foreign correspondents as Hanoi's army
units began withdrawing from western Cambodia toward the Vietnamese
border. The partial pullout, said to involve 18,000 troops, began
Thursday and will continue until Wednesday.
   Hun Sen said his government would be willing to unconditionally
accept about 300,000 Cambodian refugees along the Thai-Cambodian
border and claimed they could be reintegrated into society within
six months. He said his government and the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees were close to signing an agreement for
repatriation of the refugees.
   The prime minister said Pol Pot remains the most important leader
of the Khmer Rouge and that titular president Khieu Samphan has no
military power.
   Khieu Samphan said in Paris this week that Pol Pot, who led a
reign of terror in Cambodia between 1975 and the 1978 Vietnamese
invasion, was no longer active in the leadership.
   Khieu Samphan has become the most visible of the Khmer Rouge
leaders internationally.
   Hun Sen said he would negotiate a peace settlement with Khieu
Samphan but still regarded him and other Khmer Rouge leaders blamed
for massive atrocities as unacceptable for any future political role
in Cambodia.
   Hun Sen said only 50,000 Vietnamese troops would be left in
Cambodia after next Wednesday, when six divisions would have
returned to Vietnam.
   He said all military and civilian advisers had left.
   ``This will not affect the balance of forces on the battlefield
due to our Cambodian troops who are in control of all areas from
which the Vietnamese have withdrawn,'' he said.
   ``Vietnamese assistance ... is considered very important, but
final success depends on the Cambodian people,'' he said. ``We still
have another two years, which we think is reasonable to build our
own forces.''
   He said his government would wage a ``people's war'' using local
and regional militia to eliminate the guerrillas. He admitted,
however, that these units face a shortage of ammunition and must
rely on a mix of ``traditional'' and modern weapons.
   ``We don't have the budget for a million troops, but all citizens
must master forces to defend their villages and districts,'' he said.
   Hun Sen said he met Thursday with Rafeeuddin Ahmed, special envoy
of U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez De Cuellar, to discuss a
political settlement of the conflict.
   He said the two agreed that a dissolution of the pro-Hanoi
government in Cambodia prior to a peace agreement would ``certainly
bring chaos.''
   Hun Sen repeated his opposition to an international peacekeeping
force in Cambodia but said an international control commission would
be needed to supervise any political settlement.
   Hun Sen, who is regarded as the Phnom Penh government's most
capable political leader, also carries the foreign ministry
portfolio.
</TEXT>
