<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchofLove     12-16 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church of Love,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Church of Love Creator and Assistant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury today convicted a man and
woman of bilking thousands of lonely men nationwide out of $4.5
million with false stories of a garden paradise inhabited by nude
``love angels.''
   The jury deliberated 13 hours before convicting Donald S. Lowry,
59, of Bettendorf, Iowa, and Pamala St. Charles, 25, of Moline, of
mail fraud, conspiracy and money-laundering in their Church of Love
sex-fantasy scheme.
   Prosecutors said Lowry, a former English teacher who founded the
Church of Love in 1965, and Ms. St. Charles sent lonely old men nude
photos and letters from fictional ``love angels'' living in a
paradise called Chonda-Za.
   In exchange, Lowry and Ms. St. Charles solicited membership fees,
contributions and ``love offerings'' for the angels' supposed needs,
including garden seeds, winter coats and sewing machines,
investigators said.
   About 31,000 men nationwide contributed money to the Church of
Love.
   Lowry solicited models to pose nude for the photographs.
   ``I still feel what we did was right and that's what's
important,'' Ms. St. Charles said. ``People just continue to
misunderstand us.''
   Lowry said he had no regrets and vowed to continue his fantasy
letter business from behind bars.
   ``We made a lot of people happy,'' he said. ``That's all that
matters.''
   Prosecutors called the pair ``con artists, liars and
manipulators.'' Assistant U.S. Attorneys K. Tate Chambers and
Darilynn Knauss accused them of preying on men ``sick with the
illness of loneliness.''
   Defense attorney William G. Schick of Moline said his clients
conducted a ``legitimate business that helped a lot of people.'' He
described Lowry and Ms. St. Charles as ``dream merchants'' and the
letters as ``healthy fantasies.''
   Lowry faces up to 125 years in prison and $5.2 million in fines.
Ms. St. Charles faces 65 years in prison and $2.2 million in fines.
Sentencing was scheduled for April 7.
   Lowry used contributions to pay himself a huge salary, buy a
fleet of expensive cars and pay for sexual favors from some of the
models, the government said.
</TEXT>
