<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpicyFood 1stLd-Writethru a0514 12-16 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spicy Food, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spicy Food May Cause Heartburn, But Not Stomach Damage, Study Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT that study compared spicy food
and meals taken with aspirin; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The doctors
...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pass the spicy food; hold the aspirin.
   Researchers today reported that meals taken with aspirin are more
likely to harm the stomach than hot stuff.
   The doctors fed 12 healthy volunteers four meals: a bland steak
dinner; steak with three aspirin tablets; an enchilada dinner with
an ounce of jalapeno pepper, and half a pepperoni pizza.
   Once a week for four weeks, the eight men and four women, ages 24
to 43, ate one of the meals for lunch and dinner.
   The researchers found that stomach linings were much worse after
the meal with aspirin than after the Mexican food, pizza or bland
steak, the researchers said in the Journal of the American Medical
Association.
   The lining protects the stomach from digestive acids that can
cause ulcers.
   In a further experiment, the researchers sprayed Tabasco sauce
directly on the stomach lining. Examination later revealed bleeding,
but the researchers said they didn't know which ingredient to blame,
the red pepper or the vinegar.
   So they inserted jalapeno pepper directly into the stomach.
Examination later revealed no apparent damage to the lining, the
researchers said.
   The researchers concluded that ingesting spicy meals poses no
threat to the stomach linings of people who have no history of
stomach problems.
   The research was led by Dr. David Y. Graham of the Veterans
Administration Medical Center and Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston.
</TEXT>
