<HEAD>Coors Workers Reject Union Representation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brewery workers at the Adolph Coors Co.,
which has been non-union for a decade, have voted against joining
the Teamsters.
   The vote count Thursday night was 1,081 against the union and 413
in favor, a Coors spokesman said.
   The balloting followed 18 months of union and company politicking
at the brewery, the nation's fourth largest. Coors has 1,600 brewery
workers.
   ``It came out loud and clear that they're satisfied at this
time,'' Dave Laughton, a Teamsters leader.
   ``We are delighted that our employees have decided that
third-party representation is not needed at Coors,'' said Peter
Coors, president of the company's brewing division.
   The brewery has been non-union since 1978, when workers voted
overwhelmingly to withdraw from the AFL-CIO after a bitter 20-month
strike.
   The dispute led to a nationwide labor boycott of Coors products
that officially ended in 1987 with an agreement between the brewery
and the AFL-CIO, including the Teamsters.
   Coors and the Teamsters agreed before the union representation
vote that win or lose, the boycott will not resume.
   Key issues in the election included wages and pensions.
   The Teamsters touted the wages recently implemented and the
pension plan under consideration at an Anheuser Busch Co. brewery.
Coors warned employees that Busch is four times as big as Coors and
can afford higher salaries and benefits.
</TEXT>
