<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Jury Resumes Deliberations Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New lead, past-tensing; Picks up 2nd graf pvs, The jury.
Further lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors resumed deliberations today in the
tax and mail fraud conspiracy trial of Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. with a
federal judge's warning that the perennial presidential candidate's
controversial political views should not sway their verdict.
   The jury of eight women and four men debated the complex case for
4{ hours Thursday and recessed until this morning. Chief U.S.
District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. said they should be prepared to
work through Saturday if necessary to decide all 49 counts involved.
   LaRouche and six associates were charged with mail fraud and
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans from
supporters without any intention of repaying them.
   In addition, LaRouche, 66, was charged with conspiring to defraud
the Internal Revenue Service by having all his personal expenses
paid by various corporations he controls and claiming he had no
taxable income.
   LaRouche has not filed federal income tax returns for any year
since 1978, government prosecutors say.
   If convicted of all 13 counts against him, LaRouche faces a
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and $3.25 million in fines.
   The six other defendants faced lesser penalties if convicted.
They are William Wertz, the chief of LaRouche's fund raising; Edward
Spannaus, legal coordinator for LaRouche, and fund-raisers Paul
Greenberg, Joyce Rubinstein, Dennis Small and Michael Billington.
   Bryan reminded the jurors before they received the case that
membership in a political organization, even one with ``honest
albeit controversial views,'' is lawful under the Constitution and
is not evidence of any criminal activity.
   The judge also said they should not attach any significance to
the fact that LaRouche was never summoned to testify in his own
defense during the 15-day trial.
   In his rebuttal to the closing defense arguments, U.S. Attorney
Kent Robinson told jurors the only issue they must decide is whether
LaRouche and his fund-raisers were lying when they assured
prospective lenders they would get their money back.
   Defense lawyers insisted that the fund-raisers made such
assurances in good faith, but Robinson said everybody in the
LaRouche organization knew they were part of a ``bankruptcy waiting
to happen'' when they solicited the loans, and probably wouldn't be
able to repay them.
   The result, the chief prosecutor said, was ``an enormous crime _
a $30 million crime'' in which LaRouche followers were being ``bled
dry.''
   Robinson denied defense lawyers' suggestions that the
government's charges were an attempt to ``quiet a political
movement.'' Defense lawyers claimed the LaRouche organization was
the victim of government harassment because of unorthodox positions
and a conspiratorial view of world events.
</TEXT>
