<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0958EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     12-16 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Part-time Soldier Killed In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA today set a one-week
deadline for families of British soldiers to leave Northern Ireland,
and its gunmen shot and killed an off-duty, part-time soldier.
   After the deadline passes, ``the responsibility for casualties
rests solely with them (the families),'' the Irish Republican Army
said in a statement telexed to news media in Belfast.
   In the statement, signed by P. O'Neill, a traditional signature
for the outlawed organization, the IRA claimed responsibility for
killing a member of the locally recruited Ulster Defense Regiment
who was gunned down today. The regiment is a mainly Protestant unit
attached to the British army.
   Two gunmen fired at close range into the cab of a truck the man
was driving in a Roman Catholic working-class district of
Downpatrick, County Down, police said. He was delivering coal in the
town, which is 30 miles southeast of Belfast. The victim's name was
not immediately released.
   The gunmen fled in a car that was later found abandoned in the
district, a public housing estate called Model Farm, police said.
   The IRA threat to families of the 10,500 British troops deployed
in Northern Ireland followed three bomb attacks on British army
married quarters in the past month. The attacks caused no injuries.
   Britain sent troops into Northern Ireland in 1969 after sectarian
feuding flared. Since then nearly 3,000 people have been killed.
   In March, the IRA launched a campaign against British servicemen
and since then 44 have died. The toll includes four people who were
at British bases in continental Europe and one killed in an attack
on a London base.
   The part-time soldier shot today was the 12th member of the
6,280-strong Ulster Defense Regiment killed this year. Since 1969,
179 members of the regiment have been killed.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
the Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
