<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SandinistaDefects 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-16 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sandinista Defects, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Author of Sandinista Anthem Reportedly Defects in Spain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads to UPDATE throughout with embassy denial of report,
other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. newspaper today said the author of
Nicaragua's Sandinista national anthem defected from his diplomatic
post in Spain, but the Nicaraguan Embassy denied the report and said
he never worked there.
   Embassy spokeswoman Claudia Chamorrosaid Carlos Mejia Godoy had
returned to Nicaragua.
   The Washington Times quoted unidentified diplomatic sources in
Washington and Europe as saying that the composer resigned his post
as cultural attache to the embassy about two weeks ago. He turned in
his passport and card as a senior member of the Marxist Sandinista
party, the newspaper said.
   ``We categorically deny this report,'' Chamorro said. ``In
addition, Mejia Godoy was never accreditted as a diplomat at this
embassy and was only in Spain on personal matters.''
   Mejia Godoy wrote the ``Sandinista Hymn,'' which describes the
United States as ``the enemy of humanity'' and is given equal
billing with the traditional Nicaraguan national anthem, the
newspaper said.
   The paper quoted one diplomat as saying that Mejia Godoy was
``lying low and doesn't want to make a big deal about it. But I was
told he was kind of fed up with things back in Nicaragua.''
   Mejia Godoy, 52, wrote anti-government songs that became popular
when the Sandinistas overthrew President Anastasio Somoza in 1979.
   One of his songs, titled ``Monimbo,'' is often played on
Nicaraguan radio stations just before major government
announcements, the Times said.
</TEXT>
