<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrunkBusters     12-16 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drunk Busters,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Who Ya Gonna Call? Drunk Busters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers of cement mixers, floral vans and
tow trucks are being recruited as Drunk Busters in an effort to cut
down on drunken driving.
   The program unveiled by Jefferson County on Wednesday calls on 21
agencies and businesses with a fleet of nearly 3,700
radio-dispatched vehicles to ask that employees who observe drunken
drivers relay the information to police.
   ``Drunk Buster On Board'' stickers will be placed on the
vehicle's bumpers.
   ``By pulling this community together, we're showing that
Jefferson Countians are serious when we say, `We want it to stop,'''
said Jefferson County Judge-Executive Harvey Sloane.
   John Woodford, assistant executive director of Louisville's
transit agency, said the idea originated with a suggestion from a
bus driver days after a May 14 bus crash in northern Kentucky killed
27 people. The bus was struck head-on by an alleged drunken driver.
   Lt. Col. Dave Whalin, assistant county police chief, said it may
be difficult to apprehend drunken drivers by the time the tip is
relayed to a patrol car, ``but hopefully we'll have a car in the
vicinity that can respond immediately.''
   ``And the program should have a deterrent effect because drunken
drivers will know it's not just the police looking for them,'' he
said.
   Whalin added that motorists with car telephones can report
drunken drivers.
   Jerry Vincent, of a Teamsters local representing truck drivers
and corrections officers, said union workers would take part.
   ``Nobody wants them (drunken drivers) out there,'' he said.
   Roger Coffey, a tow service operator who is participating, said
``if the drunks saw some of these vehicles we tow in, maybe they'd
stop it. This carnage has got to stop.''
</TEXT>
