<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sweden-Palme 1stLd-Writethru a0492 12-16 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Palme, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closed Hearing Set for Assassination Suspect</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with plea, arguments, result. Adds
byline, other detail, background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 41-year-old Swede with a long criminal
record was arraigned today for the slaying of Prime Minister Olof
Palme and ordered to remain in police custody for further
investigation.
   Christer Pettersson, who was arrested Wednesday, pleaded
innocent. Prosecutors argued that there were reasonable grounds to
believe he killed Palme nearly three years ago, and that he should
be held while they build a case for trial.
   District Court Judge Mikael af Geijerstam found for the
prosecution during the closed negotiations.
   Pettersson covered his face with his hands as he entered the room
under guard from an emergency entrance. He wore blue jacket and
jeans and appeared nervous and confused as the hearing got under way
and he was asked to respond to murder charges.
   Palme, the popular four-term prime minister and a leader of the
world disarmament movement, was gunned down as he walked down a
Stockholm street with his wife the night of Feb. 28, 1986.
   Reporters were allowed to hear opening statements today before
the courtroom was closed for further deliberations.
   Under Swedish law, a suspect ordered to remain in custody can
continue to be interrogated by police while they build their case.
   Pettersson has a history of violent crime and a previous
conviction for manslaughter. He has been interrogated since he was
detained Wednesday.
   According to press accounts, a witness identified him in a lineup
as the man who was seen loitering outside the Grand Theater in
downtown Stockholm, where Palme and his wife saw a movie just before
the killing.
   Palme's killer followed the couple down the street from the
theater and shot him.
   Police have offered no motive.
   The initial murder inquiry focused on a political motive. Ousted
Iranian President Abolhassan Bani-Sadr claimed Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini ordered Palme's slaying when the prime minister discovered
and stopped a Swedish company's illegal arms shipments to Tehran.
   Pettersson is the first suspect arrested in the case.
Investigators have been sharply criticized by several government
inquiry commissions for mishandling the manhunt and squabbling among
themselves.
</TEXT>
