<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tibet-DutchWoman     12-16 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet-Dutch Woman,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Woman Shot in Tibet Arrives in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch woman who was shot in the arm and
accused of violating Tibetan laws won permission to leave China and
arrived in Hong Kong today.
   Ms. Christa Meindersma, 26, of Amsterdam, arrived in this British
colony aboard a train from the southern Chinese city of Canton.
   Holding her injured left arm in a sling, she told reporters she
was in Hong Kong for medical treatment.
   She said she also has come to the colony to ``testify for the
people who were killed or wounded like I am and about whom the
Chinese government doesn't seem to be worried or ashamed like they
are about a foreigner like me.''
   She is to hold a news conference Saturday.
   The woman was among at least 13 people injured during a Dec. 10
anti-government demonstration in the central square of Lhasa, the
Tibetan capital.
   Chinese officials have said a Tibetan Bhuddhist monk was killed
when police fired on protesters carrying a banned Tibetan flag near
Jokhang monastery.
   Western witnesses have said they saw two bodies, one of a small
child. They said Tibetans told them seven people were killed.
   On Thursday, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said
Ms. Meindersma violated a law forbidding foreigners from mingling
with Tibetans during riots.
   He said she also violated customs regulation by bringing into
Lhasa a book by the Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled leader. The book,
``My Land And My People,'' is banned in China because it advocates
Tibetan independence.
   Ms. Meindersma denied the accusations. She said she has been in
Lhasa since September studying Tibetan. And she told The Associated
Press earlier that she was reading the book to learn Tibetan. She
said stood not among demonstrators in Lhasa, but with a large crowd
of onlookers.
   During the shooting, she said a bullet entered her arm and exited
through her shoulder.
   Earlier this week, Tibetan authorities confiscated her passport
and barred her from leaving Lhasa. She was allowed to leave after a
request from her government.
</TEXT>
