<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-GreatTrek     12-16 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Great Trek,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Calls For Racial Harmony on Afrikaner Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the holiest day in Afrikaner
history, President P.W. Botha called for racial harmony today on the
150th anniversary of the Great Trek that took white settlers into
the African wilderness.
   ``We must strive for national unity and for unity in our
different communities,'' Botha said in a speech to 15,000 whites
gathered at the Voortrekker Monument to the 19th century pioneers.
   His call contrasted sharply with a rival celebration by
extreme-right Afrikaner cultural and political groups, who view
Botha's limited race reforms as capitulation to the 26 million black
majority.
   ``This is a demonstration, a protest of the Afrikaner against
what is going on in South Africa, so-called reform,'' said Carel
Boshoff, leader of the Afrikaner Volkswag cultural organization that
sponsored nearby alternative celebrations. They also attracted about
15,000 people.
   ``We do not see (reform) only as political change, but total
cultural change,'' Boshoff said. ``We don't think it's possible for
the (white) South African nation to survive in that situation.''
   Afrikanerdom's most momentous event took place when
Dutch-descended Afrikaners left the British-ruled Cape Colony for
the country's uncharted interior.
   Stories of hardships on the Great Trek and battles with African
warriors have taken on mythical proportions for the country's 3
million Afrikaners, who dominate government and make up 60 percent
of the white population.
   The pioneer party, which included some blacks, vowed Dec. 16,
1838, to make the date sacred if they defeated a hostile Zulu tribe.
They did so in the Battle of Blood River.
   ``White, brown and black stood together in the laager (circled
wagons) at Blood River, in spite of those who want to suppress this
fact today in an attempt to justify their own standpoints,'' said
Botha. ``It was not only a trek of white Afrikaners.''
   All races were invited to the government celebrations, but only a
handful of non-whites participated.
   Extreme-right groups barred blacks from their ceremonies.
   Eugene TerreBlanche, charismatic leader of the neo-Nazi Afrikaner
Resistance Movement, described the Battle of Blood River as the day
``when the white nation of Africa was born.''
   TerreBlanche called for Afrikaner unity, drawing cheers from his
followers in khaki uniforms with swastika-like patches.
   The 100th anniversary proved a catalyst that united Afrikaners
and propelled the National Party to power 10 years later. The
Nationalists have ruled uninterrupted since 1948 and codified the
apartheid policies of racial segregation.
   Blacks do not celebrate the holiday.
   But a coalition of anti-apartheid groups said they would pay
homage to the chiefs who fought the whites in the 18th and 19th
centuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
