<2ND_LINE>PM-Teachers-Dinner,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Offered $1,000 To Dine With Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There may be no such thing as a free lunch, but six
teachers are being offered a $1,000 bonus just to go out to dinner
next semester with the parents of all their first-grade pupils.
   A relaxed meal together will give teachers and parents a chance
to discuss how parents can get involved in their child's education,
said businessman Philip Garvin, who is offering the bonus plus the
cost of the meals to Valdez Elementary School teachers.
   ``When the student goes to this special dinner and sees parents
and teacher together on this festive occasion, it should make an
impression that school is important,'' Garvin said.
   Garvin, president and owner of Norac Television Productions, also
gave $2,000 checks to five high school teachers deemed outstanding.
   He contends that businessmen should contribute to education and
that outstanding teachers, like valued employees in the corporate
world, should be recognized with cash bonuses.
   The only catch, said Garvin, is that the teachers must spend the
bonus on themselves, not on the classroom.
   Teacher Eloise Garcia said she is thrilled with the idea and will
use the money to ``throw a big party and celebrate.''
