<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Angola     12-16 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Angola,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New U.N. Peacekeeping Force Prepared For Cuban Pullout From Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new U.N. peacekeeping force will monitor
the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, senior U.N.
officials said today.
   Angola and Cuba have agreed in principle to have the U.N. force
verify the pullout, said an official involved in planning the
southwestern Africa peace settlement.
   Another official said the force probably will be no larger than
50 men and is largely symbolic. U.S. spy satellites are expected to
provide the actual intelligence data that South Africa insists on.
Both officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Marrack Goulding, a U.N. undersecretary-general, has been meeting
this week with Cuban and Angolan officials to work out the size and
deployment of the force.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar is to meet Cuban and
Angolan officials Saturday and Sunday to complete the discussions.
   The two Marxist countries Tuesday signed an agreement in
principle with South Africa pledging to withdraw the troops over 30
months, with half to be gone by Nov. 1.
   South Africa promised to start implementing a 10-year-old U.N.
independence plan for neighboring South-West Africa, the territory
better known as Namibia that it has ruled for 73 years.
   The force monitoring the Cuban withdrawal is in addition to plans
for 7,500 U.N. peacekeepers and 2,000 military police and civilian
officials to monitor the South African troop withdrawal from Namibia
and oversee independence elections.
   South Africa apparently wanted a U.N. force to verify the Cuban
withdrawal partly because the United Nations is monitoring its
pullout and it did not want to be seen as the only party requiring
international supervision.
   Under the accord, independence will begin April 1, when 3,000
Cuban troops are to have been withdrawn from Angola.
   Nov. 1 is the date set for electing a Namibian national assembly.
   A final agreement between South Africa, Cuba and Angola is to be
signed Thursday in New York.
   Cuban troops went to Angola in 1975 to help the government fight
invading South African troops and U.S.-backed rebels of the
right-wing National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
</TEXT>
