<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BombBlast     12-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bomb Blast,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Blast Injures Sheriff and Deputy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THIBODAUX, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today said they found a radio
receiver that may have been used to detonate a nail-packed bomb that
injured the sheriff and a deputy.
   The bomb, contained in a bag left next to Sheriff Duffy Breaux
Jr.'s car, went off outside the Thibodaux Civic Center on Thursday
afternoon.
   Breaux, 60, suffered serious injuries to a hand and foot and was
admitted to Thibodaux General Hospital, said sheriff's Capt. Benny
Musso. Deputy Daniel Leche, 62, was in stable condition with
puncture wounds, Musso said.
   ``We can't think of anything in the recent past that would lead
us to believe (the sheriff) had some sort of enemy,'' Musso said.
``We don't know. As far as threats, we can't think of any that's
been made.''
   The fourth-term sheriff and Leche, a sheriff's office employee
for about 30 years, were leaving a Christmas party when they spotted
the bag, Musso said. ``He had to move it to get into the car, and he
kicked it and it went off,'' Musso said.
   ``We did find a receiving unit at the scene,'' Police Chief
Milfred Zeringue said, adding that authorities were not sure whether
the device was used to detonate the bomb. ``It could be either way.''
   Thibodaux Police Chief Milfred Zeringue said state and local
police, sheriff's deputies and the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms would investigate.
</TEXT>
