<HEAD>Bush Says He and Tower Both Support Star Wars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Bush quotes, picking up in 5th
graf pvs, ``He's not</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush said today that he and
John Tower, his choice for defense secretary, pointment surfaced, but aides
said he has been a strong
supporter of SDI in negotiations with the Soviets in Geneva,
Switzerland.
   Edward Rowny, a special adviser to President Reagan on arms
control, said he has always known Tower to support Star Wars.
   But Graham said Tower sought to have a watered-down platform on
Star Wars adopted at the Republican National Convention in New
Orleans. The former general also said he fears Star Wars will fall
victim to budget-cutting in the early 1990s as Pentagon officials
seek to pay for existing weapons systems while aiming to cut the
deficit.
   But Wallop said early deployment of Star Wars ``is not a big
expense.''
   On the other side of the fence, some Democrats have complained
that Tower may be too close to defense contractors to make the tough
cuts needed to trim federal spending.
   Reagan's military budget, slated to go to Congress Jan. 9, calls
for increasing this year's total of $299.5 billion by 2 percent
after allowing for inflation.
   Bush has indicated he will settle for zero growth after inflation.
   Meantime, Wallop said he doesn't think Tower is ``so totally
crippled'' by the prolonged appointment process that he wouldn't be
an effective defense secretary.
   But both Democrats and Republicans, including Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., complained that Bush should not have kept Tower hanging.
Former Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger said the delay ``may
have done damage to the office or to Sen. Tower personally.''
</TEXT>
