<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTalks     12-16 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Talks,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Soviet Negotiations End In Geneva Without Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and Soviet negotiators have concluded
four months of talks on limiting underground nuclear tests without
agreement, Reagan administration officials said today.
   The round that ended Thursday had begun in Geneva on Aug. 29. The
negotiators adjourned without setting a date for resumption.
   But the negotiators made ``significant progress toward completion
of effective verification protocols,'' the White House said in a
statement Thursday.
   Disagreement centered on ways to verify compliance with 1974 and
1976 U.S.-Soviet treaties limiting underground nuclear blasts _ the
only kind still permissible _ to 150 kilotons.
   The treaties have never been ratified by the Senate. President
Reagan promised to seek Senate approval, but only after verification
measures were adopted.
   The Soviets have stopped pushing for a moratorium on further
tests and the two sides conducted two joint experiments on
verification measures, said a U.S. official speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   One test was held in Nevada in July and the second in
Semipalatinsk in the Soviet Union in September.
</TEXT>
