<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Tibet-Knives     12-16 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tibet-Knives,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Knives Forbidden In Capital of Tibet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to reduce violent crime in Tibet's
capital, officials have outlawed the long, decorative knives that
many residents wear attached to their hips, a newspaper reported
Friday.
   The Chinese-language Ta Kung Pao said that although carrying the
knives is a part of Tibetan custom, many people in Lhasa, the
capital, have used the weapons in murders, robberies, rapes and
burglaries.
   So far this year, 25 people have been killed and 34 injured in 56
criminal cases involving the long knives, the newspaper reported.
   The Lhasa Public Security Bureau responded by forbidding
residents, businessmen, travelers and pilgrims from carrying knives
longer six inches.
   The newspaper said offenders would be punished and their knives
confiscated. The report did not say when the regulations took
effect, how many knives have been confiscated or what punishment
offenders face. It also did not say whether the knives were used in
recent anti-Chinese riots in Lhasa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
