<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Traffic     12-16 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Traffic,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rome Limits Traffic To Avoid Holiday Gridlock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rome increased the area of the city closed to most
private cars to prevent traffic jams during the Christmas holidays,
officials said Friday.
   The plan, adopted by the City Council Thursday, goes into effect
Saturday through Jan. 15, when officials will consider adopting it
on a permanent basis.
   The mayor dropped a plan to limit access to the city based on an
alternate license-plate scheme after it was criticized at the City
Council meeting.
   The 900-acre area already off-limits to most private cars from 7
a.m. to 11 a.m. and 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. Monday to Saturday was
increased by 250 acres.
   The entire area includes streets near the Spanish Steps, the
Trevi Fountain, the monument to Victor Emmanuel and the Pantheon.
</TEXT>
