<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-PLO Bjt   12-16 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO, Bjt,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-PLO Talks Force Israel To Rethink Its Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dialogue with the Palestine Liberation
Organization is forcing Israel to reassess its policy and construct
an alternative plan for Middle East peace negotiations.
   Washington's decision to meet with PLO representatives caught
Israel in the midst of complex talks on forming a new coalition
government and without an agreed-upon peace program.
   Politicians both left and right now are searching for a format
that would fulfill at least some aspirations of 1.7 million
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a rebellion
against Israeli rule began a year ago.
   They have focused on approaches that would exclude the PLO, which
prominent Palestinians say will not work.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, leader of the center-left Labor
Party, proposed elections in which Palestinians of the occupied
lands would choose local leaders with whom Israel could negotiate.
   ``We are facing a new situation,'' he told reporters. ``I hope
Israel will say to the Palestinians: Stop shooting and go voting.
Give up your bullets and go to your ballots.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who leads the conservative Likud
bloc and has vowed never to deal with the PLO, is described by aides
as recognizing the need for a credible Israeli plan.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, said in an interview the prime
minister is considering ``new moves'' to be announced when a new
government is formed.
   ``Be sure that Mr. Shamir is preparing a peace move which will
surprise everyone,'' he added on Israel radio, but refused to
disclose details.
   Ehud Olmert, a leading Likud figure, recommended that Israel
establish self-rule for Palestinians as envisioned in the
U.S.-mediated 1978 Camp David Accords between Egypt and Israel.
Those accords led to the peace treaty of March 1979.
   ``This would be an Israeli initiative to bring about autonomy in
direct talks with the local population, which is the true partner we
need to talk with,'' Olmert said.
   The PLO rejects limited self-rule and is committed to creating an
independent Palestine, which Israel says would threaten its
existence. The Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO
legislature, proclaimed an independent state Nov. 15 in Algiers.
   Saeb Erakat, a political science professor at An Najah University
in the West Bank, said Palestinians would reject both autonomy and
elections.
   ``Palestinians will not buy products they don't like even if
there are new labels on them,'' he said.
   Erakat added, however: ``We always used to say there could be no
comprehensive peace without the PLO, but whether we like it or not
it is also true that peace can't be realized without Israel.''
   Shlomo Avineri, former director-general of Israel's Foreign
Ministry, said: ``Now you see the beginnings of a reassessment that
is reflecting the changes in the PLO. Now some in Israel are
demanding a rethinking of policy regarding negotiations with the
PLO.''
   He proposed some dramatic test of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat,
such as urging him to follow the path of Anwar Sadat, the late
president of Egypt, who came to Jerusalem in November 1977 to make
peace. Avineri is on the political science staff of Hebrew
University.
   One sign of a shift in Israeli thinking was a call for
recognition of the PLO by prominent Labor Party doves, among them
former Defense Minister Ezer Weizman and Uzi Baram, the party
secretary-general.
   ``We have to establish new policies that will not make us a new
rejection front,'' Baram said.
   Weizman, a former fighter pilot, said on Israel radio: ``A people
with such an air force and army and readiness to take a risk in
battle can also take a risk for a peace process.''
   Nimrod Novick, political adviser to Peres, said Israel must
develop a peace plan capable of reducing international pressure.
   ``If we put an initiative on the table, we force all other
parties to deal with it,'' he said on the radio. ``If we sit
quietly, we will be forced to deal with the initiative of someone
else.''
</TEXT>
