<HEAD>Man Involved in Police Shootout Sentenced To 5 to 15 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man arrested in a shootout that wounded
six white police officers was sentenced to five to 15 years in
prison on weapons charges, while 1,500 officers outside the
courthouse demanded the maximum penalty.
   ``I am not some racist brutal beast or killer that the drug
trafficking police are trying to paint me as,'' Larry Davis, 22,
told Acting Supreme Court Justice Bernard Fried on Thursday. ``I
challenge you to give me the same sentence as you would give your
own son.''
   The judge called Davis a ``violent, gun-carrying drug dealer'' in
sentencing him on weapons possession charges. Davis could have
received 10 to 20 years.
   A jury in the Bronx found Davis innocent Nov. 20 of attempted
murder and aggravated assault in the 1986 shootout. Six police
officers were wounded. Davis escaped unscathed through a window,
setting off a 17-day nationwide manhunt.
   Police had come to arrest him in the slayings of four suspected
drug dealers. Davis was acquitted of murder in that case on March 3.
   Prior to the sentencing, about 1,500 police officers incensed by
the verdict gathered outside the Bronx courthouse to demand the
maximum prison term.
   Davis at sentencing called Fried his ``persecutor'' and accused
him of having attempted to ``pre-try my case,'' at one point rolling
up his shirt sleeve and pants leg to show off injuries allegedly
inflicted by correction officers.
   The lead prosecutor in the case, Brian Wilson, said he was
disappointed by the sentence.
   Davis' attorney, William Kunstler, called it a ``racist
sentence.'' Davis must serve at least five years before being
eligible for parole.
   Kunstler had argued that police, without a warrant, came to the
apartment intent on killing Davis and that he fired in self-defense
when the officers began shooting without provocation. Prosecutors
contended Davis fired first.
</TEXT>
