<HEAD>Los Angeles to Appoint City AIDS Coordinator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley says he will appoint a
full-time city official to coordinate efforts to fight the spread of
AIDS and promised $1 million toward housing assistance for AIDS
patients.
   ``While health services are mainly a state and county
responsibility, the city cannot idly sit by and watch as thousands
die each year from AIDS,'' Bradley said Thursday.
   AIDS activists had requested $5 million for housing assistance.
The $1 million announced by Bradley will provide assistance over two
years.
   Activist Chris Brownlie said the allocation will help get ``a
foot in the door for more money.''
   The AIDS coordinator's responsibilities will include promoting
AIDS education, advocating greater state and federal spending for
AIDS treatment, lining up transportation services to AIDS
outpatients and trying to determine those AIDS victims most in need
of help, officials said.
