<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GandhiAssassin     12-16 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gandhi Assassin,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Blocks Execution of Gandhi Assassin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Friday blocked the
execution of a Sikh convicted of assassinating Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi and ordered the president to reconsider the man's request for
clemency.
   The order effectively prevented the execution of a second man
convicted in the 1984 assassination, a defense attorney said.
   A five judge-panel said the constitution allows President
Ramaswamy Venkataraman to examine the case and decide whether a
pardon is warranted.
   Kehar Singh, who was convicted of conspiracy in the
assassination, appealed to Venkataraman for mercy, but the president
dismissed the appeal last month, saying he could not consider the
merits of a case decided by the Supreme Court.
   The president's denial was appealed to the court, the nation's
highest.
   In its ruling, the court compared the U.S. and Indian judicial
systems:
   ``In the United States ... a pardon by the president has been
regarded not as a private act of grace but as a part of
constitutional scheme. We have no doubt in our mind that it should
be so treated also in the Indian republic.
   ``The petition invoking that power shall be deemed to be pending
before the president to be dealt with and disposed of afresh,'' the
court said.
   The appeal was filed 15 hours before Kehar Singh and another
Sikh, Satwant Singh, were scheduled to be hanged at New Delhi's
maximum-security Tihar Jail on Dec. 2. The death sentences have been
stayed since then.
   The men were convicted and sentenced in 1986 and their appeals
were rejected in 1986 by the Delhi High Court and in August by the
Supreme Court.
   ``They've done justice. It's a great judgment,'' said Rajender
Singh, Kehar Singh's son, who was present in court to hear the
verdict Friday.
   R.S. Sodhi, the lawyer for Satwant Singh, said the stay of
execution also applied to his client, but government officials could
not be reached immediately to confirm this.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot in the garden of her New Delhi residence on
Oct. 31, 1984 by two of her Sikh bodyguards. One of them, Beant
Singh, was killed in a shootout with other bodyguards minutes later.
   The other, Satwant Singh, was arrested after he recovered from
wounds received in the shootout. Kehar Singh, a maternal uncle of
Beant Singh, was arrested later and charged with conspiracy.
   All Sikhs take the name Singh, which means lion in the Punjabi
language, by doctrine of their faith.
   Mrs. Gandh's assassination was in retaliation for an army raid
she had ordered four months earlier on the Golden Temple, Sikhism's
holiest shrine.
   The shrine in Amritsar had been taken over by armed Sikh
militants demanding an independent homeland in the northern state of
Punjab. About 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died in the army
raid.
   Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but
are in a majority in Punjab. Sikh militants have been fighting for a
separate state since 1982, claiming discrimination by the Hindu
community, which makes up 80 percent of the country's population.
</TEXT>
