<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PhysicianIncentives     12-16 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Physician Incentives,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Payments to Doctors Could Cut Quality of Care, GAO Report Warns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cost-control incentives provided by Health
Maintenance Organizations serving Medicare patients could threaten
the quality of medical care by leading doctors to cut corners, a
congressional report says.
   The General Accounting Office, a congressional investigative
agency, says strong HMO management controls are needed to prevent
abuses.
   The report was issued this week at the request of Rep. Fortney H.
(Pete) Stark, D-Calif., who has been attempting to reach a
compromise with Health Maintenance Organizations on regulatory
legislation.
   Stark-sponsored legislation that was approved in 1986 would
outlaw in 1990 incentives paid by Health Maintenance Organizations
to their participating physicians to control the cost of services to
Medicare patients.
   That measure, however, was so sweeping that it would ban
profit-sharing payments and certain other benefits paid by even the
best-run HMOs to participating physicians. Congress thus can be
expected to take another look at the issue in the year ahead.
   Incentive payments have raised questions because Medicare pays
HMOs a fixed monthly amount for each beneficiary enrolled to provide
all health services covered by the program. The system gives the
HMOs an incentive to control services and make certain that
unnecessary ones are not provided. The HMOs often pass along
incentives to participating physicians.
   ``Many are concerned that the incentives given to the
participating physicians may be so strong that they represent a
potential threat to the quality of care by encouraging inappropriate
reductions in service,'' the report said.
   Stark, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee's health
subcommittee, said in a statement that the report ``confirms my
fears'' that ``some HMOs may give so many incentives to doctors not
to order tests or refer patients to specialists that the quality of
care could suffer.''
   He cited a suggestion in the GAO's report that ``Congress may
wish to retain a ban on financial incentive arrangements that
closely link financial rewards with individual treatment decisions
and-or risk for services by physicians.''
   The report outlined four ways in which HMOs provide cost-control
incentives to physicians.
   Some pay the doctors a fixed amount of money for each Medicare
patient. ``Under such arrangements, physicians can be forced to fund
care out of their own pockets,'' the report said.
   Other HMOs distribute incentives among participating physicians
based on the cost performance of individual doctors. This could
dramatically affect the size of such payments, the report said.
   HMOs have at times paid participating physicians a percentage of
overall cost savings. The report said that could mean ``the greater
the potential for in appropriate reductions in services.''
   Finally, some physicians are measured for cost-control
performance over a short period of time. The report said it would be
better to take a long-term view of such matters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
