<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     12-16 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3-Lawyer Team Will Prosecute North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh today
announced appointment of a three-lawyer trial team to prosecute
former presidential aide Oliver L. North while Walsh supervises the
continuing Iran-Contra investigation.
   Walsh said in a statement that he would oversee his office and
``continue dealing with the complex issues raised'' posed by the
large number of secret documents in the cases against North and
three co-defendants.
   Walsh, an experienced trial lawyer who once said he would like to
try the North case himself, said in a statement he would ``continue
to supervise the ongoing investigation'' of the Iran-Contra affair
and ``press for completion at the earliest possible date.''
   The independent prosecutor appointed associate counsel John W.
Keker, like North a Marine combat veteran of Vietnam, to head the
trial team. Keker will be joined by associate counsels Michael R.
Bromwich and David M. Zornow, both former federal prosecutors in New
York City.
   Keker is a founding partner in the San Francisco law firm of
Keker & Brockett. He graduated from Princeton University in 1965 and
went to Vietnam as a Marine officer.
   Following service in Vietnam, where one of his elbows was shot
off while leading an infantry platoon, Keker obtained his law degree
from Yale University.
   He later was a law clerk for then-Chief Justice Earl Warren.
   North, a retired Marine lieutenant colonel who also served in
Vietnam, is accused of conspiring to illegally divert U.S.-Iran
arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   His trial could begin as early as late January.
</TEXT>
