<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--NoisePollution     12-16 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Noise Pollution,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Pays Damages To Residents Plagued By Airport Noise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government was ordered Friday to pay 319
residents of a southern Japanese city $1.59 million in damages to
compensate them for suffering caused by noise at their local airport.
   Those compensated were among 507 residents of Fukuoka who filed
civil suits in 1976 and 1981 against the government. They asked for
a ban on night flights at the airport to end the noise pollution.
   The plaintiffs complained of stomach ulcers, sleeplessness and
hearing difficulties caused by nighttime military and civilian
flights, according to a court spokesman, Yuichi Shiona.
   The court ruled Friday it could not ban nighttime flights at the
airport, partly because of national security concerns outside its
jurisdiction, but it ordered the government to pay $1.59 million in
damages to 319 of the plaintiffs for suffering caused by the noise
pollution, Shiona said.
   The city is 560 miles southwest of Tokyo.
