<1ST_LINE>u a PM-INS-PoliticalAsylum 1stLd-Writethru a0537 12-16 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-INS-Political Asylum, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0537,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS Hoping New Asylum Procedure Reduces Flood Of Central Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to ADD that procedure is also in effect
in Los Angeles and Miami and ADD that applications could take
several months. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `But officials ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new immigration policy taking effect
today in the Lower Rio Grande Valley will prevent thousands of Latin
American aliens seeking asylum in the United States from getting
jobs and discourage them from traveling.
   Advocates for the aliens said the measure will sharply limit the
number of people granted asylum and cause overcrowding that could
overwhelm area social services.
   Omer G. Sewell, Harlingen District director for the Immigration
and Naturalization Service, said the new procedure, which is also
being followed in Miami and Los Angeles, will make it tougher to
file frivolous applications for political asylum.
   ``We're going to provide almost instant service here in the Rio
Grande Valley and give them answers here and give them answers
quickly,'' Sewell said.
   Under the new policy, asylum applications will be processed
within 30 days, and applicants cannot work while awaiting a
decision, Sewell said.
   Aliens must also present their asylum applications at their point
of entry in the United States on a given appointment date, a new
procedure that does not actually prohibit immigrants from leaving
the area but makes travel unlikely.
   Previously, applications could take several months to process,
aliens were allowed to travel to their U.S. destinations and present
their asylum applications there, and they were generally allowed to
work in the meantime.
   But officials here and in such popular destinations as Miami and
Los Angeles say they are overwhelmed by the steadily increasing tide
of applicants.
   About 2,000 applicants arrive at the Harlingen office each week,
compared to a total of 405 for all of 1987, according to INS
records. South Texas is the closest and most popular crossing point
for undocumented aliens from Central America.
   Nearly 30,000 people, primarily Central Americans, have applied
for asylum with the INS in Harlingen since May 30.
   ``We are a outraged about this new policy at the immigration
service, because what it's going to do is hold people even longer in
the valley, intensifying the problem that we're already seeing with
homeless refugees in the streets, in shelters and in the motels,''
said Brian Szittai, chairman of the Rio Grande Valley Refugee Rights
Coalition.
   ``It sets up a procedure where I would be surprised if more than
1 or 2 percent are approved,'' said Mark Schneider, an attorney with
Proyecto Libertad, a Harlingen legal office that assists Central
Americans. ``You have adjudicators who are predisposed to denial and
it's going to be a masquerade.''
   The INS plans to send six additional adjudicators to Harlingen
early next year, Sewell said.
   ``We're going to provide almost instant service here in the Rio
Grande Valley and give them answers here and give them answers
quickly,'' he said.
   More than half of the asylum applicants are Nicaraguans. There is
a nationwide backlog of 21,000 pending asylum applications from
Nicaraguans, including 11,000 pending in the valley, officials said.
   Those denied asylum will receive letters telling them to leave
the country within 30 days, Sewell said. Applicants have the right
to appeal through the immigration court, the Executive Office of
Immigration Review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GunSentence     12-16 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Sentence,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Sentence Ordered For Student Convicted On Gun Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college student with a criminal record
received too stiff a sentence when he was sent to prison for 15
years because he owned an Old West six-shooter that didn't work, a
federal appeals court ruled.
   Kevin Sherbondy, 23, of San Clemente was arrested in 1986 on the
day the federal ``career criminal'' law went into effect. The law
mandated a 15-year sentence, with no possibility of parole, when a
person with three convictions for violent felonies was found guilty
of being an ex-felon in possession of a gun.
   The unanimous decision Thursday by a three-judge panel of the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals came 25 months after Sherbondy was
sent to Lompoc penitentiary. The 30-page opinion upheld the
gun-possession conviction but ordered a new sentence hearing in U.S.
District Court in Los Angeles.
   Sherbondy's attorney, Dennis Riordan, said he will argue that his
client be released.
   Trial testimony showed the gun did not work and that Sherbondy
never used it after it was given to him as a gift when he was 16.
His grandparents, who reared him, said he kept the gun strapped to
his bedpost as a souvenier.
   The judges ruled that only two of Sherbondy's previous
convictions, both robberies, qualified as violent crimes. In the
third, Sherbondy was placed on three years probation for urging a
friend not to testify in a cocaine case.
   Riordan said Sherbondy held two part-time jobs while making the
honor roll in college before his conviction on the gun charge.
   Riordan was hired to represent Sherbondy by a group of people
concerned about his plight. The group included former San Francisco
Police Chief Con Murphy and state Court of Appeals Justice William
Newsome.
</TEXT>
