<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NailRemoverDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0556 12-16 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nail Remover Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0556,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fake Fingernail Remover Causes Death in Child: Study</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `A 16-month-old ...' to CORRECT spelling
of
ingested.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One boy was found dead and another nearly died
after swallowing solvent used to remove artificial fingernails,
doctors reported today.
   The doctors said in the Journal of the American Medical
Association that SuperNail Nail Off, made by American International
Industries of North Hollywood, Calif., contains acetonitrile, which
slowly converts to cyanide in the body.
   The makers of SuperNail Nail Off did not immediately return a
telephone call for comment today.
   Glue removers containing acetonitrile are produced by other
manufacturers as well and sold under various names, said Dr. E.
Martin Caravati of the University of Utah and Dr. Toby L. Litovitz
of Georgetown University Hospital.
   They said the government should consider removing such products
from the market. The products often are sold without childproof
packaging, they said.
   A 16-month-old boy who ingested SuperNail Nail Off one night was
found dead in his crib the next morning, and a 2-year-old nearly
died after swallowing some, the doctors said. The report did not
give the names or locations of the children.
   Acetonitrile is a colorless liquid often used in industrial
processes, the researchers said.
   SuperNail Nail Off removes the glue used to attach so-called
sculptured fingernails to the underlying nail.
</TEXT>
