<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Christmas     12-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Christmas,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uprising Dampens Christmas Tourism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas tourism has dropped sharply because of
the Palestinian uprising, and some hotel managers in the biblical
cities of Nazareth and Jerusalem say they have no bookings at all
for the holidays.
   The Tourism Ministry predicts that 70,000 visitors will arrive in
December, a decline of 14 percent from 1987, said ministry official
Mordechai Ben Ari.
   Before the uprising began a year ago in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip, the ministry was predicting that 1988 would be a
record tourism year because it coincided with the 40th anniversary
of Israel's founding.
   But hotel managers said this will be a blue Christmas.
   ``This is the worst Christmas I've ever had,'' said Mustafa
Hamed, manager of the 65-bed Galil Hotel in the northern Israeli
town of Nazareth, where the Bible says Jesus spent most of his life.
   ``This year, the hotel is completely empty,'' Hamed said in a
recent interview. Six European groups that made reservations several
months ago for Christmas have canceled their bookings, he said.
   He said they apparently were scared off by the uprising in which
more than 320 Palestinians and 13 Israelis have died. The rebellion
in the occupied lands is aimed at ending 21 years of Israeli rule.
   In Arab east Jerusalem's 40 hotels, at least two-thirds of the
1,200 rooms will remain empty during Christmas week, said Fouad Abul
Haj, vice president of the Arab Hotel Association.
   ``The situation is very bad,'' said Haj, who also manages the
110-room National Palace Hotel where 80 rooms are vacant. ``Pilgrims
used to be our main business. Now they're not coming anymore.'' He
said seven smaller east Jerusalem hotels have closed for lack of
business.
   In Bethlehem, Mayor Elias Freij said many of the city's
traditional Christmas festivities have been canceled in solidarity
with the uprising.
   ``The Christmas party we hold every year on the 24th has been
canceled,'' said Freij, adding that there also will be no Boy Scout
parade, no city-sponsored decorations and no reception for diplomats.
   ``You decorate when you are happy,'' he said. ``The situation is
so discouraging, so tense ... that there is no spirit of joy.''
   The Tourism Ministry will hold its holiday activities in
Bethlehem, including choir performances in Manger Square on
Christmas Eve. Midnight Mass will be celebrated at St. Catherine's
Church, part of the Church of the Nativity complex built over the
cave where the Bible says Jesus was born.
   Nazareth also has canceled some festivities.
   Sofuan Fahoum, secretary to the mayor, said that there will be no
municipal decorations or any appeal to merchants to decorate their
shops.
   ``It's because of the situation in the territories,'' Fahoum
said. ``It's not the time to be happy.''
</TEXT>
