<1ST_LINE>u a PM-NuclearWaste     12-16 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE, Three Governors and DOE Meet Today On Nuke Waste Impasse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Department officials met behind
closed doors today with the governors of three Western states in an
attempt to resolve an impasse over storage of radioactive waste from
nuclear weapons plants.
   The governors of Idaho, Colorado and New Mexico conferred with
Joseph Salgado, chief deputy to Energy Secretary John Herrington,
and other regional DOE officials.
   ``I think all of us come here expecting to find a solution,''
Colorado Gov. Roy Romer said outside the hotel meeting room. ``We
ought to solve it today.''
   The immediate problem is finding a storage site for the
equivalent of 24 boxcars of radioactive material from the Rocky
Flats nuclear weapons plant near Denver. Seven boxcars of the
nuclear waste are sitting outside the plant.
   Romer said Rocky Flats, which manufactures plutonium for weapons,
will reach its capacity for temporary storage between March and May,
at which point he will require the government-operated plant to
suspend production.
   Waste has been stacking up there since October, when Idaho Gov.
Cecil Andrus turned away a boxcar headed for the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory and said the state would accept no more
shipments.
   The other question taken up today is when the government will
open a permanent waste storage site in New Mexico. The facility will
hold contaminated equipment and clothing in salt deposits more than
2,000 feet underground.
   On Thursday, Romer said the facility is not expected to open
before Rocky Flats reaches capacity.
   Doug Elmet, a DOE spokesman in Washington, said Thursday the
purpose of the meeting was to provide ``a chance for some straight
talk between the governors and the federal government.''
   Andrus said today he would not open the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory to shipments until the New Mexico facility
opens and DOE outlines a plan to remove more than 4 million cubic
feet of waste from the lab.
   Don Caviness, spokesman for New Mexico Gov. Garrey Carruthers,
said his boss wants the Energy Department to provide a firm deadline
for opening the storage facility and an update on $240 million the
state has been promised.
   The money is to be used to build bypasses around major cities
through which waste would be shipped and to compensate for lost
mining royalties.
   Caviness said Carruthers would not permit the New Mexico facility
to open until those pledges are fulfilled.
   ``New Mexico has no intention of rolling over because the
governors of other states have problems,'' said Caviness.
</TEXT>
