<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Polio-Eradication     12-16 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polio-Eradication,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polio Could Be Eradicated from Western Hemisphere by 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of active polio cases in the Western
Hemisphere has dropped from thousands in Latin America alone in the
1970s to around 300 so far this year, giving hope the disease can be
eliminated in the region by 1990.
   Ciro de Quadros, a Brazilian epidemiologist, told a group at the
Johns Hopkins School of Public Health on Thursday that the public
health strides against the disease compare only to those against
smallpox.
   So far this year, thanks to mass inoculations of children in the
crowded barrios and remote villages of Latin America, health
officials say the number of cases of the muscle-wasting disease has
been reduced to a few hundred, de Quadros said. The decline has
encouraged the Pan American Health Organization to believe that
polio can be wiped out in the region within the next two years.
   ``We are extremely confident that the target can be met,'' said
de Quadros, an epidemiologist who is directing the polio eradication
program in the Americas for the subsidiary of the World Health
Organization.
   ``It's very hard work. The wild virus circulates in crowded urban
areas with poor sanitation. And we have guys out there working in
countries with civil war,'' he said. ``But they have a true sense of
accomplishment. They're doing something that has been done only once
before, with smallpox.''
   Polio, which attacks the nerves that control muscles and often
strikes children, began to fade from the United States and Western
Europe after the introduction of the injectable Salk vaccine in 1955.
   The oral Sabin vaccine followed shortly thereafter, and polio
vaccinations were made part of the standard children's immunization
schedule.
   The World Health Organization estimates there are 270,000 polio
cases annually, with more than half of those in India.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
