<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DressCode     12-16 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dress Code,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baltimore City Schools Adopt Dress Code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new public school dress code bars students
from wearing gold jewelry, leather or fur coats and torn clothing at
middle and senior high schools.
   The dress code presented Thursday by school Superintendent
Richard C. Hunter takes effect in February. The rules, similar to
others adopted in Detroit and New Orleans, are part of an effort to
stem school violence.
   A task force on violence appointed by Hunter proposed adopting a
dress code along with other measures after a student was shot in a
corridor at Edmondson-Westside High School in October.
   ``The code will set the standard for what is unacceptable,'' said
Jacquelyn Hardy, spokesman for the school system. ``Each school will
adopt its own dress code to tell children what they should wear.
This just tells them what they shouldn't wear.''
   Hunter said students would be given time to conform to the new
dress code, but said violators probably would be sent home at
principals' discretion.
   Other items off-limits under the code include sweat suits or
jogging outfits, multiple rings or precious non-school rings,
pajama-type attire, hair rollers or curlers, slippers, shorts,
halter tops, see-through tops and apparel printed with vulgar or
obscene statements or statements related to the use of drugs,
alcohol, sex or violence.
   Joyce Quarles, an English teacher at City College, said clothing
often causes tension because of competition among students seeking
to outdress others. She said students have means of self-expression
besides clothing.
   ``Dress is one. Intellectual development is another. Clothing can
detract from the business of education. At first the students didn't
see that, but they came around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
