<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     12-16 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Injure Three At Opposition Rally; Attacks Kill 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded Friday at a campaign
rally of the main opposition leader. Police said Sirimavo
Bandaranaike was unhurt, but three of her supporters were critically
injured.
   Elsewhere, 19 people were killed in attacks blamed on a Sinhalese
extremist group and a shadowy new organization that opposes it, the
military said.
   The government began flying officials to Jaffna, a northern Tamil
city, to supervise Monday's presidential contest on this island
nation south of India.
   Extremists from the Sinhalese majority, fighting government
concessions to the minority Tamil, have vowed to block the election.
   The bombs exploded 200 yards from the Sri Lanka Freedom Party's
leader, who had just given a a speech, said a police officer who
demanded anonymity.
   ``Mrs. Bandaranaike is safe; we took her away soon after the
explosions. Three of her supporters were badly hurt; they are in a
very critical state,'' said the officer. ``There was lots of blood.''
   The meeting at Ratnalana, 10 miles south of Colombo, was the
former prime minister's last meeting before the election.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility.
   Sinhalese extremists killed nine party workers, a soldier and a
government agriculture officer, military officials said on condition
of anonymity.
   The bodies were found in several towns in southern and central
Sri Lanka. All were believed to be Sinhalese.
   Of the political workers, three supported President Junius R.
Jayewardene's United National Party and six the Sri Lanka Freedom
Party, the officials said.
   The bodies of eight other people, all believed to be Sinhalese
radicals, were found in various villages, the officials said. They
blamed these killings on the People's Revolutionary Red Army.
   The Red Army emerged suddenly a few weeks ago as the latest
lethal force in Sri Lanka's tangled web of armed bands and rival
ethnic groups.
   Villagers say the Red Army includes members of the
Sinhalese-dominated government's paramilitary forces and targets
young men suspected of belonging to the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese extremist group.
   Military officers deny government troops are involved in the Red
Army and say the group is a spontaneous outgrowth of the people's
rejection of violence by the radical front.
   The government has blamed the front for the killings of more than
600 people, mostly Sinhalese, since July 1987, when the government
signed an accord designed to end guerrilla warfare and terrorist
attacks by Tamil separatists.
   The front said the accord, which was negotiated with India's
help, made too many concessions to the Tamils and that the
government sold out the Sinhalese. It vowed to kill anyone who
supported the accord.
   The predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese account for 75 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people, and the Tamils, who are mostly Hindu,
18 percent.
   The accord granted Tamils a measure of autonomy in the north and
east. The Tamil insurrection began in 1983 and has claimed more than
8,500 victims, mostly Sinhalese.
   As the presidential election drew closer, the People's Liberation
Front stopped confining its attacks to government employees and
began targeting members of opposition parties competing in the
election.
   The front has demanded Jayewardene's resignation and the
immediate dissolution of Parliament. Jayewardene, who cannot seek a
third term under the constitution, has said Parliament will be
dissolved the day after the election.
   The front says the government will not conduct fair elections and
has demanded a multiparty caretaker government to oversee the
polling.
   More than 100 government workers were flown Friday to the Tamil
town of Jaffna to prepare for the voting, Election Department
officials said.
   Jaffna, now largely pacified, was once the chief stronghold of
Tamil separatists still battling Indian peacekeeping troops in the
north and east.
   Election Commissioner Chandrananda De Silva said 90,000 officials
will be deployed to man the 8,070 polling stations across the
nation. He denied rumors the election will be postponed because of
the violence.
</TEXT>
