<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DesperatePriest     12-16 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Desperate Priest,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Sells Art To Keep Job Center Going</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Russian Orthodox priest with only $40 left to
keep his jobs center open says the hard times are forcing him to
sell his prized possessions, two 19th-century French lithographs.
   The Rev. John DaeCheck, who operates the non-profit New Times
Service Center in nearby Glassport to help unemployed steel workers,
has an overdue telephone bill of several hundred dollars, and he has
already tapped businesses in the depressed Monongahela Valley for
donations.
   To raise money, he placed classified ads in Pittsburgh newspapers
Wednesday and Thursday offering two works by French artists Honore
Daumier and Jacques Villone for a total of $500. He estimates they
are worth $500 to $1,500 each.
   ``I have to do what I have to do and if I look stupid doing it,
that's too bad. I've had these for 20 years, but to keep the place
going, I'd sell them,'' he said.
   DaeCheck, 42, received 10 such lithographs as gifts when he was a
businessman nearly 20 years ago; the two are all that remain.
   ``Slowly and surely through my life, whenever a financial crunch
came up, I would sell one,'' he said. ``I'm terrible at asking for
money. It kind of tears something out of you to have to do that.''
   DaeCheck, assistant pastor of a small independent church in
Washington, Pa., founded the center seven months ago with $800 of
his own money and a monthly $50 stipend from his church. Job-seekers
are asked, but not required, to make a $2 donation for job leads and
a $5 donation for resume help.
   The agency, staffed by volunteers, has provided about 900
laid-off steel workers and others with a free, fast and simple way
to find employment and job training.
   On a wall in the cramped storefront office are about 1,000 job
listings, which are updated daily. Volunteers also help job-seekers
with resumes and career counseling and steer them to other agencies
if they need clothing, food or a place to live.
   ``I wanted to do something to help alleviate the unemployment
problem in our area,'' DaeCheck said. ``It seemed there were so many
people taking advantage of others with job services, many of which
charge fees of $60 or $80. What if you don't have any money? That
$60 or $80 could be someone's rent money.''
   Dennis Saputo, 34, of Lincoln, said he turned to the center when
other agencies failed to help. The agency recently found training
for him in asbestos abatement and volunteers helped him fill out a
resume.
   ``I've been on public assistance and have gone through their
programs and, quite frankly, they're a joke. They go through the
motions to help you, but they really don't help,'' said Saputo.
   ``This place here makes you feel good. They will do everything
they can to help you get going. It's the best program I've ever
dealt with, and I've dealt with enough to know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
