<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Flu     12-16 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Flu,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worst Flu Epidemic In 20 Years Sweeps France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France has been hit with its worst flu epidemic in
20 years, and by Christmas one in five people will have suffered
from high fever, aching bones, stuffy nose and other unpleasant flu
symptoms, doctors say.
   ``The flu has hit harder and earlier than ever before,'' said Dr.
Jean-Marie Cohen, head of France's Regional Groups For Influenza
Observation.
   Cohen, a general practitioner, said one in three patients he
treats have ``la grippe.''
   The epidemic is currently making its way south from northern
France, where it surfaced two weeks ago, to the Riviera, where it is
expected to peak during the holiday season.
   More than 2 million people have been struck so far with this
year's variety, which doctors attribute to the A-H1N1 virus. It is
affecting mostly young adults and school-age children.
   ``The A-H1N1 virus caused a major outbreak of flu in the late
1940s, so people over 40 are likely to be immune to it,'' said Karin
Esteves of the Division of Communicable Diseases at the World Health
Organization in Geneva.
   Cohen said the virus first appeared during the summer in Britain
but did not reach epidemic proportions. Czechoslovakia was hard hit
in early fall, and Sweden is now in the grip of the flu.
   The A-H1N1 virus also has turned up in Canada and the United
States, with cases reported in Arizona, Michigan, Maryland, Texas,
South Dakota and Hawaii, he said.
   In the French city of Nantes, on the Atlantic coast, about 30
percent of school-age children have been bedridden with the flu. And
in some scattered towns around France, schools have been closed.
   Some doctors say recent transit strikes can be blamed for the
flu's rapid spread in the greater Paris region.
   ``Many of my patients have walked miles in the cold and rain to
get to work,'' said Dr. Joseph Danon, an ear, nose and throat
specialist. ``And when they do catch buses or subways, they're
crammed in like sardines, an ideal way to spread germs.''
   Cohen said it was virtually impossible to know why the flu struck
so early this year, especially since the weather in November was
relatively mild.
   In 1968, more than 30,000 people died throughout France during a
flu epidemic that lasted three weeks.
   Cohen was more optimistic for this year's epidemic because a
vaccination against the virus has been on the market since early
Oct. With 12 percent of the population vaccinated, it is expected to
reduce incidence of the flu by 20 percent.
   Though doctors say the flu does not rank among the ``serious
illnesses,'' it does cost the French economy billions of dollars.
   In 1985, workers missed 16 million days of work because of flu,
costing the French economy $1.5 billion. Many companies have begun
vaccinating employees free of charge or for a nominal sum.
   French pharmaceutical companies, however, did not produce enough
vaccine to meet the demand, and many pharmacies are sold out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru a0611 12-16 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Hit Seven-Month Peak in November</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to include percentage increase</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction in November reached its
highest level in seven months, the government said Friday in a
report cited as further evidence of a robust economy.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units last
month, up 1.4 percent from the October rate of 1.54 million.
   It was the third increase in a row and the highest level of
construction activity since April. Housing starts soared 5.1 percent
in October and rose 0.4 percent in September.
   Housing permits, a good barometer of future housing activity,
edged up 0.1 percent to a rate of 1.52 million units, the highest
level since June 1987. The slight gain followed a robust 8.8 percent
increase in October.
   The strength surprised analysts, who for many months have been
saying that rising interest rates would dampen the housing sector.
Activity this year is down from last year, but not by as much as
expected.
   ``Home buyers are simply either ignoring or looking through all
the uncertainty that surrounds interest rates ... and saying, `Hey,
I've got a job, things look pretty good, my company is growing, it's
time to buy a house,''' said James Christian, chief economist of the
U.S. League of Savings Institutions.
   He cited an unemployment rate near 14-year lows and strong sales
of new homes from June through October, which pushed the backlog of
unsold homes below a six-month supply for the first time in a year
and a half.
   ``Builders are going to build them if people are going to buy
them,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, economists say mortgage rates will probably edge
higher through the middle of next year and will eventually take
their toll on housing. A higher rate increases monthly mortgage
payments.
   Rates on fixed-rate mortgages, which fell from about 10} percent
in mid-August to 10[ percent in late October, have since climbed
back to nearly 10{ percent, according to the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp.
   ``The housing industry is clearly slowing down. ... There are
some areas of the country still doing fairly well, but others have
slowed significantly,'' said Kent Colton, executive vice president
of the National Association of Home Builders.
   He predicted housing starts would total 1.5 million this year,
down from 1.62 million last year and a recent peak of 1.81 million
in 1986. Next year, they will head still lower, to about 1.37
million, he said.
   For the first 11 months of the year, starts were running 9.1
percent behind the same period of last year.
   Single-family homes in November were built at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.15 million units, the highest since March
and up 0.8 percent from a month earlier. Single-family starts shot
up 9.3 percent in October.
   Apartment construction, a volatile subcategory, rose 3.0 percent
last month to 412,000 units after a 5.2 percent decline in October.
Because of high vacancy rates and less favorable tax treatment of
real estate investment, apartment starts are running far below their
1986 peak of 669,000 units.
   By region, housing starts shot up 12.9 percent in the Northeast
to 228,000 units. They rose 4.8 percent in the South to 612,000
units, the highest rate in a year. Starts dropped 8.3 percent in the
Middle West and fell 2.2 percent in the West.
   Housing activity has been strong in California in recent months
because of brisk population growth and weak in the Northeast, partly
because of high prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
