<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WarToys     12-16 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-War Toys,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Gives Out Teddy Bears In Exchange For War Toys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that promotes peace handed out teddy
bears Friday to youngsters who dumped their war toys in a trash can
at a day care center.
   ``We encouraged children to bring in a toy that promotes violence
and they received a cuddly teddy bear,'' said Margaret Matthews, the
Toledo YWCA's child care director and member of the YWCA's Peace
Coalition.
   ``The idea that we are trying to share with children and parents
is that war toys scare bears, and disarmament begins at home when
you educate children about non-violence and peaceful playthings,''
she said.
   The children brought in a gamut of toys ranging from Uzi
submachine guns that squirt water to battery-powered tanks. In
exchange, the group handed out 32 teddy bears.
   ``They were very much aware of what was going to happen. They put
the toys right in (the trash can) and went over and got their bears
and a badge that said `War Toys Scare Bears.' They were real
pleased,'' she said.
   War toys promote violence and aggressive play among children, she
contended.
   ``Children do have violence in play. And when it is something
they create on their own, without adult influence, I do not think
there is anything really wrong with that.
   ``But when they are playing with air-to-ground missiles that are
obviously adult-created and really created by toy companies, then we
are really influencing their play too much.''
</TEXT>
