<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0598 12-16 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0598,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Seize Irish Troops, Demand Israel Return Guerrilla Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Israel saying it detained
guerrilla leader, details; PICKS up 4th graf pvs, ``In the ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen today seized three Irish soldiers
from the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon in retaliation for
Israel's abduction of a Shiite Moslem guerrilla leader, police and
U.N. officials said.
   Lebanese police said the men who seized the Irish soldiers
demanded the return of guerrilla leader, Jawad Kasfi, who was
kidnapped Thursday.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army said it detained Kasfi and three
guerrillas suspected in raids against the army. ``The suspects are
undergoing interrogation,'' the army said in a statement.
   The army announcement did not say where the guerrillas were held.
   In the port city of Sidon, eight people died when Shiite Moslem
militiamen and Palestinian guerrillas battled with mortars,
rocket-propelled grenades and heavy machine guns, police said. The
fighting sparked fears a major confrontation would negate a
20-month-old truce.
   Timor Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
said the three Irishmen today ``disappeared in the village of
Tibnin,'' which is 13 miles north of the Israeli border.
   The Irish battalion's headquarters are at Camp Shamrock just
outside Tibnin.
   Goksel said in a statement that U.N. forces backed by mainstream
Shiite Moslem Amal militia will search until they find the missing
men.
   Reliable Lebanese sources identified Kasfi as a leader of the
Iranian-backed Shiite Hezbollah, a fundamentalist movement at odds
with Amal.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said four gunmen in two cars seized the Irish soldiers,
bundled them into a white Mercedes-Benz and sped away.
   He did not name the hostages.
   Amal, which regularly cooperates with the U.N. force,
``threatened to crack down on the kidnappers if the three soldiers
were not released by nightfall,'' the spokesman added.
   He declined to identify the kidnappers saying, ``We will not
identify them now to give peaceful efforts a chance.''
   Israel has said Kasfi has planned and led raids against its
forces and the South Lebanon Army in Israel's self-proclaimed
security zone.
   Lebanon today ordered its U.N. Ambassador Rashid Fakhoury to
protest to the Security Council about Kasfi's abduction.
   Armed Tibnin villagers Thursday retaliated by seizing three other
Irish troopers. But they released them after an hour when Amal
promised the U.N. force would try to locate and return Kasfi.
   The nine-nation U.N. force patrols a zone that overlaps Israel's
self-designated security zone, an area 6-10 miles deep.
   In Sidon, residents said sirens echoed throughout Ein el-Hilweh
Palestinian refugee camp on the port's southern outskirts and the
hilltop village of Maghdousheh, above the shantytown, as fighting
raged.
   Police said it erupted in the afternoon shortly after two
Palestinian guerrillas were killed when a rocket-propelled grenade
fired from Maghdousheh hit their jeep.
   Four other guerrillas and two Amal militiamen were killed in
fighting after the attack.
   Amal fought Palestinian guerrillas for two years before the
Syrian-sponsored truce took hold. More than 1,500 people were killed
and 3,500 wounded in the fighting.
   In a separate development, the South Lebanon Army said its
militiamen killed two Arab guerrillas today in a firefight near the
Christian town of Marjayoun. The statement gave no details.
</TEXT>
