<DOCNO> AP881216-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristmasHouse     12-16 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas House,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Opens Christmas House To Thousands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They only moved in a month ago, but the
guest list for a couple who have set up a Christmas spectacle
outside their new home is starting to run into the tens of thousands.
   John and Gloria MacKoul say they have averaged 1,000 visitors
nightly to the house they had barely finished building in November
when they unveiled a display of lights, trees and Christmas
characters, live and mechanical.
   ``I guess we're so happy, we wanted everyone else to be, too,''
said Gloria MacKoul. ``Just to see the faces of the children is
enough for me.''
   The display includes three Christmas trees at their picture
windows and one in a loft, 40 moving dolls on their octagonal
staircase, life-sized mechanical reindeer and carolers, 30 Disney
characters on the front lawn, and several friends and neighbors
acting as Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, Frosty the Snowman, Mrs.
Frosty and assorted helpers.
   Mrs. MacKoul said she and her husband, an electrical contractor,
designed the house just for the Christmas spectacle that they have
planned for years. Even the carpenters who built the house donated
their services to make a stable for the life-sized Nativity scene
that was lifted by crane onto a ledge in the front yard.
   And the MacKouls show the spectacle for free.
   ``A lot of people come in and are very skeptical. They walk out
and are very moved,'' Mrs. MacKoul said.
   Word about the house has spread so fast through the central
Massachusetts city of 180,000 people that the MacKouls get thank-you
cards addressed only to ``the Christmas house.''
   Their doors are open nightly until Dec. 24, when Santa takes off
to deliver presents, but the house reopens from Dec. 26 to New
Year's Eve. The couple counts 1,200 visitors on weekend nights and
they average 900 on weekdays.
   Their neighbors in the expensive development have not raised a
fuss about the sudden stream of guests. ``We haven't heard one
complaint and the traffic is unbelievable,'' she said.
   One neighbor, an Orthodox Jew, even dons a moose suit every night
to entertain children.
   The couple have collected Christmas figures for years with an eye
to the production. Their daughter, Jennifer, 15, made the Disney
figures for the yard.
   The Nativity figures were imported from Italy with the vacation
money the couple had saved.
   The MacKouls, who have lived their entire lives in the Grafton
Hill section of the city, hosted a smaller version of the Christmas
spectacle in their former apartment there, but most of the guests
were neighborhood children.
   They prepared this year's display behind shaded windows in the
weeks before Thanksgiving to keep it secret. The lights went on
Thanksgiving night and within minutes cars began stopping.
   Their visitors have included a motorcycle rider in black leather
who thanked them profusely and children without coats.
   Mrs. MacKoul said older visitors are particularly touched by the
display.
   ``We have people crying sometimes. They can't believe we're
letting them in the house,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
