<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WireFraud     12-16 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wire Fraud,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Apologized For Defrauding Government Gets 4{-Month Jail
Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who helped sell substandard electrical
wire used in nuclear submarines and then apologized in a $26,000
newspaper ad for defrauding the Defense Department was sentenced
Friday to 4{ years in prison.
   ``I was very, very wrong and I'm sorry,'' Lawrence Koffler, 54,
of Providence, R.I., told U.S. District Judge Clifford Scott Green,
fighting back tears.
   However, the judge turned down a defense plea for probation
because ``the offenses are very serious.''
   Besides the prison term, Koffler was fined $15,000, ordered to
pay $47,000 for the cost of prosecution, given three years'
probation when he is released from prison and ordered to perform 750
hours of community service during that probationary period.
   In a plea-bargain agreement 13 months ago, Koffler pleaded guilty
to one count of conspiracy to defraud, five counts of mail fraud and
two counts of filing false income tax returns.
   He previously made restitution to the government of $475,000 and
paid $3.7 million to settle his income tax liabilities.
   Koffler cooperated with the government during its lengthy
investigation of conspiracy, bribery, tax evasion and mail fraud
charges that, overall, resulted in conviction _ either at trial or
through guilty pleas _ of 43 defendants in a scheme that defrauded
the Defense Department of more than $5 million.
   Last week, in an advertisement he placed in The Philadelphia
Inquirer, Koffler said he was ``disgusted with what I had done'' and
appealed to others who do business with the government to avoid
cheating.
   ``Please learn a lesson from my mistakes,'' he said in the ad.
``Don't make the almighty dollar the guiding force for your business
decisions. If only one person learns from my mistakes, then
something good has come out of this.''
   The government said it demanded a prison term because Koffler, as
vice president of marketing for Carol Wire and Cable Co. of
Pawtucket, R.I., was critical in carrying out the scheme.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Karl Lunkenheimer said Carol, in its
sales to companies that shipped the wire to the Defense Industrial
Supply Center in Philadelphia, made product substitutions that were
extremely dangerous.
   ``Substituting tin-coated wire for silver-coated when used in
guided missiles, nuclear submarines, tanks, jet bomber-fighters and
other critical military systems created a risk of the destruction of
extremely expensive military equipment and the crews involved in
using it,'' Lunkenheimer said in a memorandum.
   Koffler's lawyer, Thomas Ostrander, said ``the sentence wasn`t
what we expected, but Mr. Koffler thinks it is fair.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
