<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRouche     12-16 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Fraud Case for Second Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury deliberated Friday for the second
day in the tax and mail fraud conspiracy trial of political maverick
Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr.
   When they left for lunch at mid-day, the eight women and four men
had debated the complex case against LaRouche and six associates for
eight hours beginning Thursday.
   Chief U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. has said they
should be prepared to work through Saturday if necessary to decide
all 48 counts involved.
   LaRouche, 66, a perennial independent presidential candidate, and
the six aides were charged with mail fraud and conspiracy for
allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans from supporters
without any intention of repaying them.
   LaRouche was charged separately with conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service by having all his personal expenses paid by
various corporations he controls and claiming he had no taxable
income.
   LaRouche has not filed federal income tax returns for any year
since 1978, government prosecutors say. If convicted of all 13
counts against him, LaRouche faces a maximum penalty of 65 years in
prison and $3.25 million in fines.
   The six other defendants, who face lesser penalties if convicted,
are William Wertz, who was in charge of fund raising for LaRouche;
Edward Spannaus, LaRouche's legal coordinator, and fund-raisers
Michael Billington, Paul Greenberg, Joyce Rubinstein and Dennis
Small.
   LaRouche did not testify in his own defense during the 15-day
trial.
   Defense lawyers said LaRouche and the others were innocent of all
charges. They said the loans were solicited with good-faith
assurances that they would be repaid.
   Government prosecutors countered that everybody in the LaRouche
organization knew that they were part of a ``bankruptcy waiting to
happen'' and lied when they told prospective lenders that the terms
of the loans would be honored.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kent Robinson told the jurors that
LaRouche and his followers had perpetrated ``an enormous crime _ a
$30 million crime.'' LaRouche's chief lawyer, Odin Anderson of
Boston, said the government was charging a ``voodoo conspiracy''
without any evidence to support its allegations.
</TEXT>
