<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece     12-16 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says Major Differences Remain In Negotiations Over Bases In
Greece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major differences remain in negotiations over
the leases on U.S. military bases in Greece, which expire next week,
the State Department said Friday.
   The latest round of talks, which have been going on since
November 1987, was completed Friday and another session was
scheduled for January, said spokesman Charles Redman.
   But Redman said that if the negotiations fail, the bases would
have to close 17 months from the Dec. 20 expiration date.
   ``Important differences remain on many issues, but the
negotiators are not at an impasse,'' said Redman.
   ``Both sides right now indicate that it is our intention to try
to work together to reach a mutually agreeable decision to
continue,'' he added.
   The biggest bone of contention is the Hellenikon Air Force base
outside Athens, which is a particular irritant to Greek nationalists
resentful of the U.S. presence in their country.
   Greece announced in September that it would close down the
facility once the lease expires, but the United States contends the
Hellenikon base is part of the overall negotiations which have yet
to be resolved.
   About 1,400 servicemen, 200 civilian employees and 700 Greeks
work at the base, opened in the late 1940s to help distribute
Marshal Plan aid to the war-torn country.
   Nationalists have urged Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou to eject
the United States, and the pressure on him is likely to mount during
the campaign for June elections.
   Three other U.S. bases have been operating in Greece since the
early 1950s _ a navy communications station near Athens, a 6th Fleet
supply base at Souda Bay in Crete and an Air Force electronic
listening post at Gournes, also on Crete.
   The United States pays the Greek government more than $430
million a year in credit for military armaments as a form of rent
for the bases, and for some 20 additional communications posts in
Greece.
   A statement issued in Athens said any new agreement would have to
serve Greece's ``highest national interests'' and would have to be
approved in a national referendum.
   Greece wants a new accord to guarantee U.S. help in solving some
of its longstanding disputes with neighboring Turkey.
   The two NATO allies are at odds over military control of the
Aegean Sea, its seabed mineral rights and control over the
Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   U.S. officials say they don't want to involve regional politics
in the talks.
</TEXT>
