<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     12-16 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expelled Priest Remains In Haiti and Ponders Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ An activist priest expelled from his
religious order for being a ``destabilizing'' influence in Haiti is
in excellent spirits and contemplating a future outside the
priesthood, friends said Friday.
   On Thursday, the Salesian order in Rome expelled the Rev.
Jean-Bertrand Aristide after he ignored an order to move from Haiti
to Canada by Oct. 17.
   ``His morale is excellent, excellent,'' said Paul Dejean, a
social worker and close friend of Aristide. ``He is going to take a
few days off now for meditation to decide on what steps to take
next.''
   Aristide, 35, has been the target of at least three assassination
attempts. On Sept. 11, while he was celebrating Mass, his St. Jean
Bosco church was attacked and burned down by armed thugs. At least
12 worshipers were killed and 70 wounded. Some died trying to shield
Aristide.
   In its communique Thursday, the Salesian Society accused Aristide
of being a ``destabilizing'' influence who instigates violence and
exalts class warfare.
   The most popular priest in Haiti, the bespectacled, charismatic
Aristide is called ``the prophet'' by his followers.
   In his impassioned and popular sermons, Aristide never explicitly
called for armed uprising, but he advocates ``active non-violence''
as a means for impoverished Haitians to achieve social justice.
   As a follower of liberation theology, Aristide also believes the
Church should play an active role in society.
   ``Aristide is not a radical. He preaches what every priest should
preach: the condemnation of oppression,''' said Jean-Claude Bajeaux,
director of Haiti's Ecumenical Center for Human Rights.
   The expulsion did not change Aristide's status as a priest, and
he could go to another diocese. The Rev. Jacques Mesidor, Aristide's
superior in Haiti, said the priest might dedicate himself to running
the charity organization The Family is Life, which he founded.
   ``The decision of the congregation will permit Rev. Aristide to
have his full liberty. He will not be bound by his obedience to a
religious community,'' Mesidor said.
   As a seminary student and then as a priest, Aristide has been
with the Salesians for 20 years. The order was founded by St. Jean
Bosco in Turin, Italy, in the 19th century and is chiefly dedicated
to education.
   The Salesians ordered Aristide to transfer to Canada by Oct. 17,
setting off a wave of demonstrations in Haiti. Aristide never obeyed.
   Aristide has called for an uprooting of remaining loyalists of
the former regime of Jean-Claude Duvalier, who fled to exile in
France in 1986.
   The massacre at his church provoked presidential guardsmen to
overthrow the military regime of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy on Sept. 17
and to replace him with Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1552EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VisitationDispute     12-16 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Visitation Dispute,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Denies Prisoner Visitation Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky's Supreme Court has thrown out a
judge's ruling that required a woman to allow her two children to
visit their father, who is in prison for shooting her.
   The court said Jefferson Circuit Judge John Potter was wrong when
he granted limited visitation rights to Gary Owen Gooch, who was
sentenced to 20 years for ambushing his wife, Edith, outside the
bank where she worked on Sept. 25, 1985.
   Potter had ruled that a parent is entitled to visitation even if
it is harmful to the child, but the high court said that ruling was
``a misstatement of the law.''
   Edith Vice, who now uses her maiden name, said she was thrilled
by the unanimous decision Thursday.
   ``It's the end of a nightmare that I've had since September
1985,'' she said. ``To think we don't have this cloud hanging over
us any more _ the euphoria is incredible.''
   Gooch, 37, is being held at the Marion Adjustment Center in St.
Mary. His attorney, Julie Gregory, said she was considering her
client's options but would not discuss them.
   ``I feel an injustice has been done,'' she said.
   Ms. Vice has not had to allow Alex, 6, and Amanda, 5, to see
their father since Potter's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
