<HEAD>Radio Says Winkler Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss delegate serving with the
International Committee of the Red Cross was released Friday from a
month in captivity, a local radio station said.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon interrupted its
programs to report that Peter Winkler was freed. The station,
quoting security sources for its brief report, did not say when or
where Winkler was set free.
   There was no immediate confirmation of his release.
   Spokesmen for the Red Cross headquarters in Beirut declined to
comment on the radio report.
   Winkler, 32, led Red Cross operations for south Lebanon from the
port city of Sidon, where he was snatched by gunmen Nov. 17. No
group has claimed reponsibility for Winkler's abduction.
   Red Cross officials have been in continuous contact with Lebanese
and Palestinian factions in a bid to gain Winkler's release.
   Earlier Friday the Red Cross addressed an open letter to Winkler
and said it will not rest until he gains his freedom.
   ``We would like you to know that we are here and we are exerting
all our energies and efforts to obtain your release,'' said the Red
Cross letter sent to Beirut newspapers for publication on Saturday
to mark Winkler's first month in captivity.
   ``These efforts shall not cease until the day you are back with
us,'' the letter said.
   Fourteen foreign hostages, including nine Americans, were
kidnapped and are believed held in Lebanon. The longest held is
Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
