<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildDeath     12-16 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Death,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother, Boyfriend Charged In Child's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abused 9-year-old boy was recovering from
beating injuries Friday as his mother and her boyfriend awaited
arraignment on murder charges in the death of the boy's 5-year-old
stepsister, authorities said.
   Meanwhile, city officials denied assertions by the girl's family
that reports of child abuse had been filed with the city's Bureau of
Child Welfare.
   Nicky Lebron Alvarez was in serious but stable condition at
Woodhull Hospital, where he was brought Thursday after police found
him cowering in a closet in his family's Brooklyn apartment, said
hospital spokeswoman Maria Reyes.
   ``He was undernourished, beaten, marked and very scared,'' said
Deputy Chief Ronald Fenrich, head of Brooklyn detectives.
   The hospital spokeswoman said she could not reveal the boy's
injuries. The couple has not been charged in his case.
   On Wednesday, the boy's stepsister, Jessica Cortez, died of a
beating allegedly inflicted by their mother, Abigail Cortez, 25, and
the woman's boyfriend, Adrian Lopez, 25.
   The girl was discovered Wednesday night by Housing Authority
police summoned by a neighbor who heard screams coming from the
apartment. She was pronounced dead an hour later at a hospital.
   The girl was bruised from head to toe, had a broken left arm, a
possible skull fracture and a 2-inch open wound on her lip, said
Fenrich. She had also been sexually abused before her death, he said.
   As the couple left a police station Thursday after their arrests,
Ms. Cortez shouted to reporters, ``He did it! He did it all the way!
... I'm going to fight this.''
   Lopez had been living with the family for about a year, police
said.
   The dead girl's grandmother and aunt said they had complained
about mistreatment of the 5-year-old, but Human Resources
Administration spokeswoman Suzanne Trazoff said a check of files
showed no such information.
   Authorities confirmed a Bureau of Child Welfafe investigation had
taken place at the home about 18 months ago, when Jessica's father,
Carlos Cortez, was arrested on a murder charge. At that point, no
problems were cited.
   A 1-year-old girl belonging to the couple was turned over to the
bureau, Trazoff said. Two of Ms. Cortez's other children are living
with their maternal grandmother in Puerto Rico.

</TEXT>
