<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviets-Zionism     12-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Zionism,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Said Disbanding Anti-Zionist Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Jewish leaders say the co-chairman of
a Soviet committee which generated anti-Israel propaganda has told
them the state-sponsored panel will be dismantled by the end of the
year.
   The decision to disband the Soviet Anti-Zionist Committee
reflects recent improvement in relations between the Soviet Union
and Israel, as well as better treatment of Jews wishing to emigrate.
   A letter purportedly written by Samuel Zivs, a Soviet lawyer who
was one of the founders of the panel in 1983, was sent to prominent
Jewish leaders in New York. A copy of the letter, dated Nov. 14, was
obtained by The Associated Press on condition that the people to
whom it was addressed were not identified.
   A Soviet Embassy spokesman, Boris Malakhov, said Friday he did
not know about a decision to disband the committee, ``although I do
not exclude it is possible.''
   After saying the panel would be terminated, Zivs added that he
was ``sincerely committed and excited about'' working with the
Jewish community in the United States and in his own country.
   Jewish leaders from the United States had urged that the
committee be disbanded, saying it was anti-Semitic as well as
anti-Zionist. Zivs said in the letter that the panel's activities
``were never intended to be, contrary to how they have unfortunately
been perceived, anti-Semitic.''
   The committee, composed of Jews with close links to the
government, was formed in a bid to dissuade Jewish dissidents from
seeking permits to leave their country for Israel and to discredit
their attempts in the eyes of the West. It is headed by David
Dragunsky, a retired three-star general.
   At a news conference in June 1983, eight committee leaders said
Zionism is a ``racist ideology'' akin to the anti-Semitic dogma
espoused by Nazi leader Adolf Hitler. Zionism is an ideology which
supports Israel as a homeland for the Jews.
   The committee also announced that emigration levels would remain
at their low ebb because most Jews who had wanted to leave had
already done so. The number of exit visas had been dropping
progressively from an all-time high of 51,320 reached in 1979,
hitting a record low of less than 1,000 in 1986.
   With the advent of a more liberal and open policy instituted by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, emigration has again risen to
16,572 through November, nearly doubling the 1987 figures.
   Israel and the Soviet Union this year exchanged consular
delegations for the first time since the Soviets broke ties in 1967.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
