<2ND_LINE>PM-Stealth Cost,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber recently unveiled by the
Air Force will cost $516 million per plane, making it the most
expensive aircraft ever built, the secretary of the Air Force said
today.
   The secretary, Edward C. Aldridge, told a news conference the
design, development and construction of 132 of the planes is
expected to cost $68.1 billion by the time production ends in
mid-1995.
   The pricetag has grown from $36.6 billion to $42.5 billion in
fiscal 1981 dollars _ an increase of about 16 percent, Aldridge said.
   Subtracting the cost of research and development, which is about
a third of the total cost, the actual production cost of the
long-range bomber amounts to $305 million per plane, he said.
   The B-2 is called stealth because it is designed to be extremely
difficult for radar to detect.
