<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-ArabAmerican     12-16 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Arab American,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Bars Arab American From Entering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel refused an Arab-American leader
permission to enter the country Friday because of ``a long record of
anti-Israeli activities.''
   Abdeen Jabara, born in the United States, arrived from New York
via Paris on a Pan Am flight and was told of the decision by police
at Ben Gurion airport near Tel Aviv. He is president of the
American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee based in Washington.
   Alon Liel, Foreign Ministry spokesman, said the objectionable
activities included acting as a defense lawyer for Palestinians held
in the United States for alleged terrorist attacks in Israel.
   He said Jabara also had criticized Israel and demanded that Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir be barred from the United States.
   Jabara told reporters: ``This is an unconscionable act. I am not
an enemy of the state. I have been here at least 15 times before,
and this is a violation of our treaty agreement.''
   In Washington, former Sen. James Abourezk, chairman of the
American-Arab committee, said: ``He has been singled out because of
his political views, views which happen to be shared by many Israeli
and American citizens. It is not a coincidence that this outrageous
action occurred just two days after our government announced that it
would begin talks with the PLO.''
   Police said Jabara would be given a room for the night and put on
the return Pan Am flight Saturday morning.
   Sandra Campbell, a U.S. Embassy official, met Jabara at the
airport. She said the embassy was told in advance he would not be
allowed to enter and American diplomats discussed the situation with
Israeli officials.
   She would not give details.
   Liel said the decision was made by the Interior Ministry, which
is responsible for passport control and immigration, and approved by
the Foreign Ministry. ``We decided, after seeing the record, to back
the decision.''
   Jabara's committee claims to have more than 23,000 Arab-Americans
as members. Earlier this year, the group opened a chapter in Arab
east Jerusalem to represent about 8,000 Palestinian Americans living
in the Israeli-occupied territories, most of them in the West Bank.
   People who attended the group's first meeting in Jerusalem in
June claimed they were harassed at the Israel border and subjected
to demeaning searches. Israeli officials denied the allegations.
   An official of the local chapter said privately the Israelis may
have been displeased with the committee's activities, which include
arranging visits to the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip by aides
to U.S. congressmen.
</TEXT>
