<HEAD>Fed Cattle Down From A Year Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as of
Dec. 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 7.98 million head,
down 5 percent from a year ago but 2 percent more than inventories
of two years ago, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported at 1.68 million head, up 4 percent from a year
ago but down 8 percent from two years ago.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in November totaled 1.51 million
head, up 3 percent from a year ago and up 4 percent from two years
ago.
   As of Dec. 1, feedlot inventories were smaller than a year
earlier in Arizona, Colorado, Kansas, Nebraska and Texas. But
California showed an increase and Iowa was unchanged. The seven
states produce about three-fourths of the nation's beef.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of Dec. 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
