<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NorthwestCrash-Lawsuits     12-16 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Crash-Lawsuits,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest May Accept Liability In Crash That Killed 156</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines said in federal court Friday
that it would accept liability in the August 1987 jet crash that
killed 156 people if families of victims agree to drop demands for
punitive damages.
   Lawyers for the families of 121 victims, who are suing the
airline, announced the possible agreement in a federal court hearing.
   Attorney Lee Kriendler, a member of the committee coordinating
the families' cases, said the airline may make such offers to
plaintiffs who agree to seek only compensatory damages. Those are
damages a jury awards to compensate a plaintiff for lost
companionship, wages and the like. Punitive damages are awarded by a
jury to punish a defendant.
   An attorney for the airline, Carroll Dubuc, said only that the
airline has agreed to consider such offers under certain conditions
on a case-by-case basis.
   U.S. District Judge Julian Cook said he would read the sealed
agreement and question attorneys on the terms.
   Kriendler said such agreements could make it possible to try
compensatory damage cases as early as March and wrap up much of the
litigation within the next year.
   The Aug. 16, 1987, crash of the McDonnell Douglas MD-80 at
Detroit Metropolitan Airport was the second-deadliest in the
nation's history, behind the May 1979 American Airlines DC-10 crash
at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport that killed 275 people.
</TEXT>
