<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Eggs     12-16 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Eggs,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Health Minister Resigns In Egg Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwina Currie, a controversial deputy health
minister rated the best-known politician in Britain after Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, resigned Friday in a national crisis
over a salmonella scare.
   Mrs. Currie, 42, caused the furor Dec. 3 when she said most
British eggs were tainted with salmonella, a bacteria that causes
food poisoning that in rare cases is fatal.
   The government launched a $925,000 advertising campaign Friday to
try to make Britons buy eggs again and announced plans to bail out
producers by spending millions more to buy unsold eggs piling up at
farms and warehouses.
   Earlier Friday, egg producers filed multimillion-dollar damage
claims against Mrs. Currie.
   ``I think in all the circumstances it (resignation) is the best
course,'' Mrs. Currie said in a letter to Mrs. Thatcher after a
private meeting at the prime minister's 10 Downing St. residence.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who provided some defense for Mrs. Currie as the
uproar over the egg scare built through two weeks, said she accepted
the resignation ``with great personal sadness.''
   ``We shall miss the great energy and enthusiasm you have brought
to all your work,'' she said in a reply letter.
   But it remained uncertain just how risky Britain's eggs are.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who in one parliamentary exchange last week
announced she'd had an egg for breakfast, reported Thursday that 49
outbreaks of salmonella from eggs had affected 49,000 people.
   Appearing to back Mrs. Currie, she acknowledged that many other
cases probably went unreported.
   Producers say egg consumption, normally 200 million a week or
four per person, has slumped by as much as 60 percent since Mrs.
Currie's warning.
   Mrs. Currie was the most headline-grabbing member of the
Conservative government.
   Since being elected to Parliament five years ago, she has become
noted for down-to-earth, colorfully phrased advice on health care,
eating habits and life styles.
   This year, Mrs. Currie advised retirees to mortgage their homes
to pay for private health care and told the old to don ``woolly
night-caps'' to ward off winter cold.
   A poll in September in the respected weekly Economist showed Mrs.
Currie's face was the most instantly recognizable in the government
after Mrs. Thatcher's.
   Egg producers expressed delight at Mrs. Currie's resignation. The
opposition Labor Party said she'd been fired and deserved it, but
added she'd be missed.
   Government ads in national newspapers Friday said the incidence
of salmonella is ``very small.'' But the advertisements also advised
against uncooked eggs in homemade mayonnaise and Yuletide eggnog,
and it prescribed hard-boiled eggs for the sick, elderly, infants or
expectant mothers.
   ``This woman with her outrageous statement has caused us
tremendous damage,'' said John Coles, managing director of Thames
Valley Eggs Ltd., the first producer to institute legal proceedings
against Mrs. Currie. ``We have lost tens of millions of pounds.''
   But he said the government's advertising campaign would help ``in
no way'' because it mentions the salmonella risk.
   Mrs. Currie, born and raised in a working-class family in the
northwest England port of Liverpool, is a right-wing Conservative in
the Thatcher mold.
   But unlike Mrs. Thatcher, she discusses her views frankly on
everything from politics, health and sex to her personal life,
including her two daughters and the refusal of her Orthodox Jewish
father ever to see her again after she married a gentile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
