<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TobaccoOutlook     12-16 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tobacco Outlook,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reduced Tobacco Supply Translates Into Higher Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reduced supply of tobacco is translating into
higher prices for farmers this year, the Agriculture Department said
Friday.
   The 1988 crop was larger but failed to offset a decline in U.S.
inventories prior to the new harvest.
   ``Tighter supplies and the generally better quality 1988 crop
have boosted prices of virtually every type of tobacco this
season,'' the department's Economic Research Service said.
   The flue-cured crop averaged $1.61 per pound, up 2 cents from
last year. And with larger marketings, cash receipts of flue-cured
producers were up about 16 percent, the agency said in its latest
outlook report.
   Prices were up because of ``a tighter supply-demand balance, a
better quality crop and higher support prices,'' the report said.
   ``Burley sales began Nov. 21, with prices averaging about 4 cents
a pound higher than a year earlier,'' the report said. ``Burley
supports were increase 1.2 cents a pound this season.''
   U.S. cigarette consumption in calendar 1988 may be down about 2
percent from last year, although total output is larger to meet an
increase in export demand, the report said.
</TEXT>
