<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Free Red Cross Official</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines bulletin series and edits. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers in this southern port released a
Swiss official of the International Red Cross on Friday after a
month of captivity, police reported.
   A police spokesman said Peter Winkler, 32, of the International
Committee of the Red Cross was freed at 9 p.m. (2 p.m. EST) at
Hisbeh Square, the same spot in Sidon where he was abducted Nov. 17.
   ``Mr. Winkler has been handed over to the ICRC and is now at the
ICRC center in Sidon,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be identified
under standing regulations. ``He is cleanshaven and looks fit, with
no sign of any physical torture or maltreatment.''
   He said the Nasserite leftist militia that has ruled Sidon since
the 1975 outbreak of Lebanon's civil war took delivery of Winkler.
   The former captive then was turned over to Eric N. Pfister, the
Swiss ambassador to Damascus, and Mohammed Bizri, the Lebanese
representative of the International Red Cross in Sidon, 25 miles
south of Beirut.
   ``Mr. Winkler wore the same clothes that he had on when he was
kidnapped,'' the spokesman said.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio station in east
Beirut said Winkler was freed by the Fatah-Revolutionary Council,
the guerrilla group led by terrorist Abu Nidal.
   Winkler was among 15 foreigners known to be held captive in
Lebanon, including nine Americans. Held longest is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
