<HEAD>US Concerned About Soviet Air Strikes in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed concern Friday
over the ``very intense pattern of Soviet offensive activity'' in
Afghanistan, including air strikes on rebel positions that sometimes
exceed 100 per day.
   But department spokesman Charles Redman said he does not believe
the Soviet activities, which date back about seven weeks, mean the
Kremlin will renege on its promise to remove its forces from
Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   Redman said Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost very likely
raised the issue during a meeting Friday with Soviet Ambassador Yuri
Dubinin.
   ``We feel very strongly that this is not what needs to be done in
Afghanistan,'' Redman said.
   He added that the air strikes violate promises the Soviets made
to Washington at the time of the Soviet-American summit meeting a
year ago.
   The Soviets contend that withdrawing Soviet troops have been
attacked by Afghan rebels and that the United States and Pakistan
have acted in bad faith by continuing the flow of arms and
ammunition to the rebels.
