<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain     12-16 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands March to Support Union Demands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of festive demonstrators marched
through Madrid on Friday night to demand a greater share of Spain's
economic prosperity for union workers, the unemployed and the
elderly.
   No incidents were reported as 40,000 cheering people crowded into
Puerta del Sol square for the march called by the the largest union,
the Socialist General Workers Union, and the communist-dominated
Workers Commissions.
   The same demands were the basis of a general strike called by the
unions on Wednesday that closed the nation's businesses and public
transportation.
   News reports said many other marchers had not yet reached the
square considered the geographical center of Spain.
   The marchers and the unions want Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez's
Socialist government to share the fruits of an economic boom Spain
is enjoying.
   Antonio Gutierrez, secretary-general of the communist-led union,
told state television the march was ``the finishing touch on the
most important lesson in democracy the Spanish people have given for
some time.''
   Gonzalez called the general strike Wednesday, the first in Spain
in 54 years, ``a tough political blow'' to his 6-year-old government
and repeated his offer to talk with union and business leaders. Both
unions rejected the invitation unless the government first meets
five basic demands.
   These include broadening unemployment insurance to include up to
48 percent of Spain's 2.7 million jobless and boosting the smallest
retirement pensions to the monthly minimum wage of $400.
   Spain's 5 percent annual growth rate is the highest in Western
Europe and the country's banks quadrupled their profits this year.
   But it retains Europe's highest unemployment rate of 18.7 percent.
   Union leaders and rank-and-file say it was their agreement to
moderate wages that made the boom possible. They have threatened
more strikes if their demands are not met.
   State railroad engineers plan to strike Sunday, while the union
representing maintenance technicians of the national airline Iberia
said they would stay away from work on Dec. 23, 26, 30 and Jan. 2, 5
and 9.
   After the strike, 53 percent of the Spaniards polled by the
country's leading daily, El Pais, said they believe Gonzalez should
make concessions to the unions for the sake of social peace.
   On Jan. 1, Spain assumes the six-month rotating presidency of the
European Economic Community for the first time since it joined the
12-member trading bloc in 1986. Socialist leaders claim the labor
agitation is an embarrassment on the eve of the historic occasion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
