<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill Four Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with one graf and SUBS 19th pvs, `Doctors said...' to
UPDATE with five more wounded.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed four Palestinians in the
occupied territories Friday, one of the bloodiest days of the
year-old rebellion against Israeli rule. Arab doctors said 32 were
wounded.
   At least 328 Palestinians have been killed and more than 7,000
wounded since the uprising began in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel has controlled since the 1967 war. Thirteen Israelis
also have been slain.
   Friday's violence was among the worst since April 16, when
soldiers killed 14 Palestinians during riots protesting the
assassination in Tunisia of Khalil Wazir, the PLO military commander
known as Abu Jihad.
   Israel denied entry Friday to Abdeen Jabara, a U.S. citizen and
president of the American Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee,
``because of his long record of anti-Israeli activities.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said the activities included
serving as a defense lawyer in U.S. courts for four Palestinians
accused of terror attacks in Israel and making statements against
Israel and Zionism.
   Jabara called the ban ``an unconscionable act'' and declared: ``I
am not an enemy of the state. I have been here at least 15 times
before.''
   A military court convicted an Israeli army private, Eli Yadid,
19, of killing a Palestinian in March with a rubber bullet to the
head and sentenced him to 21 months in prison, an army spokesman
said.
   He said Yadid violated army regulations by firing at ``very close
range'' when his life was not in danger.
   Black smoke from burning tires filled the air Friday in Nablus,
where the killings occurred, and Arab witnesses said the wail of
ambulance sirens was heard throughout city of 120,000, largest in
the West Bank. Soldiers imposed a curfew, barring journalists and
photographers.
   Residents went into the streets when word of the deaths spread.
They built dozens of roadblocks and hung black flags of mourning
from the roofs of houses.
   Confrontations between soldiers and young Palestinians were
inspired by the death Thursday night of Ashraf al Haj Daoud, 15, of
a gunshot wound in the chest suffered Nov. 25, according to doctors
at Anglican Hospital in Nablus.
   Nablus residents declared a general strike in protest and street
battles began during a funeral procession in the Ras el Ein
neighborhood, where the teen-ager lived, witnesses said.
   Dozens of masked youths carried the coffin, which was wrapped in
the outlawed Palestinian flag and draped with a checkered Arab
headdress, the witnesses reported. As they marched, many young men
waved Palestinian banners and chanted ``We will avenge your blood,
Daoud!''
   Some began hurling stones at soldiers who shot and killed two
Palestinians, and two more were killed when riots spread to other
areas, the reports said.
   Officials of Anglican Hospital identified three of the victims as
Yassin Sharshir, 21, shot in the head; Fayez Shaku, 20, hit in the
chest; and Iyad Abul Helal, 18, shot in the head and chest.
   Family members identified the fourth as Nidal Shafik, 26. They
said he was hit in the neck and chest.
   Doctors said 20 people were wounded in Nablus, four of them
critically. An army spokesman confirmed four killed and nine wounded.
   Soldiers wounded five Palestinians in villages near Tulkarem in
the West Bank, including a 9-year-old boy shot in the neck, Arab
witnesses said.
   Seven Palestinians, including five teen-agers, were wounded in
the Gaza Strip refugee camps of Rafah, Jabaliya and Nuseirat,
doctors reported.
   An aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the day's outburst
was evidence the United States should not have contacts with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, which began this week.
   ``This is the result of giving in to people of violence,'' Avi
Pazner said on Israel radio.
</TEXT>
