<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport Grant,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA To Spend $100 Million At Dallas-Fort Worth Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced
Friday it will spend $100 million to build a new taxiway and apron
system at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, one of the
nation's busiest.
   The funds will be used in the airport's expansion of its west
side. Airport spokesman Joe Dealey said negotiations were under way
between the airport and American Airlines over building a terminal
on the west side.
   The bulk of airport traffic is now concentrated on the east side,
and the money will allow the airport to ``to operate more
efficiently and accommodate the projected growth,'' said FAA
spokesman John Leyden.
   The airport is the country's largest in size, and was the
third-busiest through the first 10 months of the year, with 564,000
takeoffs and landings.
   The FAA said it was signing a letter of intent to spend $12.5
million a year over eight years on the airport construction project,
beginning in fiscal year 1990.
   The grant represents the largest such commitment ``ever made, to
any airport, anywhere,'' Dealey said.
   Opened in 1974, the airport has 1,200 employees along with 25,000
workers of airlines and support industries, generating an estimated
$5.5 billion annually for the area economy.
</TEXT>
