<2ND_LINE>AM-Vanuatu,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops shoot Australian Tourist, Political Turmoil Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Sokomanu dissolved
parliament Friday and called elections for February, citing economic
problems and political violence, but Prime Minister Walter Lini
rejected the decision.
   He said Sokomanu was a ``political fool'' with no power to
dissolve the parliament of these South Pacific islands suggested the
president resign.
   Sokomanu's office is largely ceremonial, and he acknowledged to
an Australian news service he had no authority to dissolve
Parliament. He announced the dissolution after Lini's candidates
easily won by-elections this week.
   Barak Sope, a rival of Lini who challenged the prime minister's
leadership by urging a boycott of the by-elections, led a
demonstration outside Parliament on Friday despite a government ban
on protests.
   Roads leading to the capital were blocked and cars were searched
for weapons. Riot police manned barricades around Parliament and
most of central Vila was boarded up in case of violence.
   Sokomanu said he decided to act after paramilitary troops shot
and wounded a teen-age Australian tourist who drove through a
checkpoint Friday without stopping.
   The president said violence was hurting the economy. He did not
elaborate, but tourism provides most of Vanuatu's foreign exchange.
   The country, known as the tax haven of the South Pacific, has a
population of 130,000 and is 1,200 miles northeast of Brisbane,
Australia.
