<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     12-16 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., South Korea Discuss U.S. Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and South Korean officials began
talks Friday on the future of U.S. bases here and on revising
agreements protecting 42,000 American troops stationed in South
Korea.
   South Koreans called for U.S. military facilities to be moved
from central Seoul to rural locations and for a revision of
regulations exempting American forces from local law.
   ``Both sides agreed to continue these kind of discussions on the
grounds that the reinforcement of the security relationship between
the two countries is important,'' a South Korean statement said
after the first session.
   A U.S. statement said, ``The discussions were held in an
atmosphere of friendly cooperation and were very useful to both
sides.''
   The meeting was organized for South Korea to express its concerns
and U.S. officials to study them. No date was set for the next
meeting.
   American officials already have indicated their willingness to
relocate the sprawling Yongsan base if South Korea provides
comparable facilities elsewhere. This would help reduce
anti-American sentiment among some South Koreans and open up prime
real estate in the capital.
   U.S. troops have been based here since 1950 to help defend South
Korea from North Korean attack. The communist North invaded the
South in 1950, touching off the Korean War.
   Talks are to center on the Status of Forces Agreement, a 1966
pact some critics want rewritten to give South Korea greater
jurisdiction over U.S. soldiers in criminal and other matters.
   Dissidents and radical students demand the immediate withdrawal
of American forces, which they contend hamper unification with North
Korea.
   But recent surveys show most South Koreans support the U.S.
presence as a deterrent to war on the divided Korean peninsula.
   In Seoul, the opposition-controlled National Assembly narrowly
approved President Roh Tae-woo's nomination of former Gen. Kang
Young-hoon as prime minister on Friday.
   The nomination was approved by 160 of 294 legislators, with
disapproving abstentions from 123 opposition lawmakers, 10 ``no''
votes and one invalid ballot.
   More than 70 members of the main opposition Party for Peace and
Democracy abstained, saying Roh violated the constitution in naming
Kang as premier this month and appointing 18 new Cabinet ministers
in a major reshuffle.
   Legal experts say Roh needs parliamentary approval first under a
new constitution adopted in a referendum last year.
   The nomination was approved only with the help of former Premier
Kim Jong-pil, whose moderate opposition New Democratic Republican
Party controls 35 seats.
</TEXT>
