<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Embassies     12-16 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Embassies,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cash Crunch May Force Cuba to Shut Embassies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba may close up to 15 of its diplomatic
missions abroad because the government is short on cash, the Cuban
news agency Prensa Latina reported Friday.
   President Fidel Castro told the Central Committee of the Cuban
Communist Party the closings might be needed to direct foreign
exchange reserves to domestic development, the agency said in a
dispatch received in Mexico City.
   Castro said the 1989 Cuban Economic Program ``had to be
elaborated in extremely difficult conditions and is directed at
solving problems,'' the report said.
   It did not say in what countries Cuban embassies and consulates
might be closed.
   Castro said the economic strategy is designed ``to prevent
reductions in what already has been accomplished, to maintain levels
of nutrition and health and to continue working to solve the
currency deficit that for several years has wounded the economy of
the island.''
   Under an economic cooperation agreement, the Soviet Union sends
the dollar proceeds of its oil export sales to Cuba. The dollar's
depreciation in international currency markets has hit Cuba's
foreign exchange reserves.
   Citing a dollar shortage, Cuba asked Western creditor nations
this year to reschedule its estimated $5.5 billion foreign debt over
15 years and ask for a five-year grace period, according to a
central bank document released in March.
   The request reportedly was turned down, according to Manuel
Sanchez Perez, a former deputy trade minister who defected in 1985.
</TEXT>
