<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Vietnam-MIAs     12-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains Arrive In Hawaii For Possible Identification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight sets of remains believed to be those
of U.S. servicemen killed during the Vietnam War were returned to
U.S. soil Friday, 13 years after the war ended.
   The repatriation was the seventh and largest since the Vietnamese
government agreed in August 1987 to help the United States recover
the remains of its lost soldiers. Since then, 172 sets of remains
returned by Vietnam have been identified as Americans.
   The remains of two others have been recovered from China, and 26
other sets of remains were recovered and identified from Laos, the
military said.
   Thirty-eight metal caskets were unloaded from the C-141 Army
transport plane under drizzly skies at Hickam Air Force Base. Draped
with American flags, the caskets passed honor and color guards as
military personnel carried them to waiting buses for transfer to the
Army's Central Identification Laboratory. About 50 people, mostly
base employees, attended the solemn, 1{-hour ceremony.
   At the lab, forensic experts will try to determine if the remains
are those of any of the 1,747 Americans listed as missing in action
in Vietnam.
   Currently, 2,383 Americans are listed as MIA: 1,747 in Vietnam,
547 in Laos, 83 in Cambodia, and six in China.
   Hanoi officials released the remains to U.S. officials Thursday.
They also turned over dog tags, military identification cards and
other information that might help identify the bodies, said Maj. Dan
Trout of the U.S. Pacific Command.
   Military officials said they did not know how long it would take
to identify the remains and refused to release the details of their
recovery.
   ``It's absolutely unpredictable, and we won't release any
identity until it's an absolute positive one,'' said Trout. ``We
don't release specific information about the recovery sites or what
exactly was found in deference to the families (of missing
servicemen). We don't want them to have to speculate.''
   The previous largest turnover of suspected MIA remains involved
27 sets handed over April 6.
   In addition to turning over the latest remains, the Vietnamese
also gave information on 12 other missing Americans, Trout said.
``The level of cooperation from the Vietnamese has been very good.''
   He said Vietnamese and American technical experts would meet in
Hanoi Monday through Wednesday to review work and discuss future
joint projects.
   Meanwhile, other officials were investigating reports that some
Americans were still prisoners in Southeast Asia, the major said.
   ``A lot of reports of Americans still alive come from refugees in
the area,'' he said. ``We don't have any evidence ... but we don't
rule that out as a possibility.''
   About 58,000 Americans died during the Vietnam War. U.S.
involvement extended from March 1965 to the signing of the Paris
Peace accords in January 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
