<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Microgravity     12-16 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Microgravity,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Order On Microgravity Research Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed an executive order
Friday that establishes a National Microgravity Research Board to
oversee scientific studies on the near-weightlessness of space.
   On Feb. 11, in announcing a sweeping new space policy for the
United States, the president said he would establish a such a board
``to assure and coordinate a broader range of opportunities for
research in microgravity conditions.''
   The board, to be chaired by the administrator of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, is to advise on priorities for
research in the near-weightlessness of space and to consult with
private industry and universities on research opportunities.
   It also is to develop policy recommendations to the government on
matters bearing on types of research, the roles of government,
industry and academia, and on access to space.
   The executive order calls for the board to be composed of the
secretaries of State, Defense, Commerce, Health and Human Services,
Transportation, Energy and the director of the National Science
Foundation or their designees.
</TEXT>
