<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GAO-NORAD     12-16 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GAO-NORAD,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says NORAD Computer Project Running Behind And Above
Estimates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study says the Air Force is
running two years late and well above cost estimates with a
problem-plagued project to replace a vital computer link in the air
defense system for North America.
   The latest projected pricetag for the new computer system for the
North American Aerospace Defense Command is $281 million, according
to the General Accounting Office, the investigative agency for
Congress.
   That figure is $39 million above what the Air Force in April 1987
estimated it would cost to replace the aging computers that are
supposed to provide U.S. and Canadian leaders with vital information
in case of an air attack.
   When the new system for the Colorado installation was proposed in
1981, the Air Force estimated it would cost $202 million, GAO said
in a report to the House Appropriations defense subcommittee.
   The study said the new system, being developed by General
Telephone and Electronics Inc., is not expected to be operational
until September 1991, two years later than planned.
   According to GAO, a number of problems have been encountered with
the first phase of the project, a semi-automated control unit that
monitors communication lines and switches to backup lines and
equipment when communication quality deteriorates.
   The problems include unreliable computer software that would
cause a loss of communications if the software failed to perform
properly in an emergency.
   ``A failure of this nature during actual operations could
seriously affect the Air Force's ability to satisfy mission
requirements during a crisis,'' GAO said.
   The Defense Department told GAO that the software problem has
been isolated and will be fixed by GTE.
   The department said the contractor is also fixing another problem
cited by GAO: during a test, it took 31 minutes to restart the unit
after a power failure _ 29 minutes longer than specified by the
contract.
   GAO said the Air Force will have to spend $5 million rewiring
NORAD's Cheyenne Mountain communications center because the wiring
on the new gear is not compatible with wiring on some, and perhaps
all, existing electronics equipment in the center.
   The Defense Department said that GTE followed the ``circuit
interface standards specified by the Air Force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
