<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Last Temptation,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Drops Anti-`Temptation' Ordinance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first ordinance banning the
movie ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' has been repealed by a
county in the Florida Panhandle.
   The ordinance was thrown out by a federal judge Sept. 9, the day
after the Escambia County Commission adopted it, but remained on the
books until Thursday night's meeting. The commission also agreed to
pay the $10,000 legal fee for the Tampa law firm of Holland & Knight
that successfully challenged the constitutionality of the movie ban.
   The commissioners passed the emergency ordinance 4-1 after
several people charged the film directed by Martin Scorsese was
anti-Christian.
   Commission Chairman Willie Junior said jokingly Thursday that he
will ask the people who requested the ordinance for contributions
toward the $10,000 bill.
   ``They said they would help out, and we would really appreciate
them passing the plate on Sunday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
