<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GlacierLanding 1stLd-Writethru a0667 12-16 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Glacier Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0667,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Delays Efforts To Rescue Men Stranded on Remote Glacier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with next rescue attempt unlikely until Saturday,
new quotes from Haley, night temperatures about 20 degrees, RESTORES
first name to Merchant, CORRECTS location of Tarr Inlet to 60 miles
north of Gustavis sted 45, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow thwarted rescuers Friday from
reaching two pilots stranded since Tuesday on a remote glacier in
British Columbia after their vintage plane made an emergency landing.
   A Coast Guard H-3 helicopter couldn't reach the site because of
whiteout conditions on Grand Pacific Glacier and returned to Alaska
to wait for the weather to clear, Coast Guard spokesman Ed Moreth
said.
   The forecast called for clearing Saturday, and officials expected
the next rescue attempt then. Meanwhile, the two men prepared to
spend their fourth night in the World War II-era Grumman Widgeon
amphibious plane.
   ``They were a little bit colder than they were, but they're doing
OK,'' said Chris Haley, a petty officer at the Coast Guard station
in Juneau. ``They're still inside the plane and just biding their
time until we can get in there and pick them up.''
   The pair are equipped with survival gear and have enough food to
last two to three more days, officials said. Nightly temperatures on
the glacier were estimated at about 20 to 25 degrees, said Robert
Jacobson, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service.
   Coast Guard officials have kept in radio contact with pilot
Michael Mills, 38, and passenger Charles Ferguson, 31, of Gustavus,
by flying a C-130 transport plane over the glacier. The plane was
sent back to Kodiak Friday morning and will return Saturday, said
Haley.
   Neither the men nor the plane was hurt in the emergency landing
Tuesday. Mills' wife said the plane had recently been restored and
Haley said it may have been forced down by engine trouble.
   On Thursday, the helicopter landed near the face of the glacier
at Tarr Inlet, but the weather never cleared. The craft reached an
elevation of only 1,500 feet above sea level, and the stranded men
are several miles inland at the 3,400-foot level, said Cmdr. Bruce
Merchant.
   Tarr Inlet is in Glacier Bay National Park and Preserve and is
about 60 miles north of Gustavus, a small southeast Alaska port
town. The huge glacier stretches far into British Columbia.
   The two men are several miles inside Canada. Coast Guard
officials said they had received permission from the Canadian
government to conduct the rescue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
