<DOCNO> AP881216-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 2005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-16 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Pays Homage To Slain Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa on Friday
led 3,000 people in honoring Baltic seacoast workers killed in 1970
riots, and said he is beginning to see signs of a new opportunity
for Poland.
   ``Something is becoming visible in this country. I don't know
what it is. Maybe we will fail once more,'' Walesa told a rally at
the Lenin Shipyard.
   ``But when there is a chance, even a minimal chance (we) must
undertake it. Because it is a chance for Poland, for all of us, and
especially for youth.
   ``We cannot waste it.''
   Walesa seemed to be referring to the communist government's
growing tolerance for Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first
independent union movement, which was crushed under martial law in
1981.
   The official media have increased non-critical coverage of Walesa
and the government has made overtures to him to begin a dialogue.
   Walesa walked at the head of a procession of work crews from
inside the shipyard to the monument to the slain workers outside its
gates.
   As the crowd pressed around him, he gently laid a wreath of red
and white carnations and led the singing of two patriotic hymns,
including the national anthem.
   The ceremony, under gray skies. marked the 18th anniversary of
the riots for ``freedom and bread.'' Security forces shot down
dozens of coast workers, including at least 27 in Gdansk. The exact
number of victims was never revealed.
   Also on this date in 1981, riot police stormed the Wujek mine in
Katowice and killed nine miners during the imposition of martial law.
   Officially outlawed Solidarity also sponsored peaceful rallies
outside the Lenin Steel Mill in Nowa Huta, near Krakow, and in
Katowice, in southern Poland.
   Walesa attended a memorial Mass on Friday evening in Gdansk.
Later, hundreds of riot police shepherded the worshipers to a train
station a few blocks away. The crowd sang only religious songs
punctuated by a few chants of ``Solidarity!''
   Departing from past practice, state-controlled radio and
television Friday covered the Solidarity wreath-laying in addition
to the official ceremonies.
   ``One of the most tragic dates in the history of the nation,'' a
TV commentator said.
   The 1970 killings were a seminal event in the development of the
modern opposition movement in Poland. Workers began rioting when the
government announced drastic food price increases just before
Christmas.
   The brutal repression of the protests created an outcry that
ended the 14-year national leadership of Wladyslaw Gomulka and
radicalized a generation of young workers, including Walesa.
   Walesa led the next Gdansk workers' revolt of 1980 that resulted
in Solidarity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
