<DOCNO> AP881216-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 2010EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Economy     12-16 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Economy,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President to Seek $6 Billion in Foreign Credits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRACSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has asked
congress for approval to seek $6 billion in foreign credits next
year as a means of reviving the economy.
   Salinas, sworn in Dec. 1, said the $6 billion would cover a
projected $5 billion balance of payments deficit next year and
provide money for development.
   In a message with the 1989 budget sent to the Chamber of Deputies
late Thursday, he said the deficit would stem from ``dynamism in
imports associated with the economic recovery and conservative
petroleum export income.''
   ``It is my conviction that the construction of the economic
future ... must be the prerogative and responsibility of all
society,'' he said.
   Reductions in trade barriers have caused a 50 percent increase in
imports this year from 1987. Weak demand and low prices on the world
oil market have cost Mexico at least $2 billion in anticipated 1988
export revenue.
   The Salinas budget forecasts a ``positive, though moderate'' 1.5
percent growth rate next year, up from 0.4 percent this year. It
said the economy grew 1.4 percent in 1986.
   Under a wage-price freeze begun in March, Mexico's 1988 inflation
rate is expected to be 51 percent, the document said.
   Inflation for the first 11 months was just over 48 percent, after
a record 159.2 percent in 1987, the central bank has reported.
   For 1989, inflation is expected to be 22 percent or lower,
according to the budget. Earlier this week, the president announced
an extension of freeze through June 1989.
   Among his 1989 policy goals, Salinas included:
   _Achieving price stability.
   _Protecting the jobs and purchasing power of workers.
   _Increasing business and labor support for his anti-inflation
program and his proposals for negotiating better terms on the $102
billion foreign debt.
   Forthcoming talks with foreign creditors dominated Salinas'
message to congress. He promised a ``firm'' stand with creditor
banks and dwelt on what the debt has cost the Mexican economy.
   Salinas said, ``The national product has been checked, investment
has abated, real salaries have been reduced and the creation of jobs
has been insufficient to give the opportunity of well-paid work. ...
The priority is growth. The net transfer of resources will have to
be reduced substantially.''
   The president contends Mexico no longer can afford to spend 5
percent of its gross national product on debt service _ about $14
billion in interest and principal this year.
   On Tuesday, Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe said the government
wants to reduce the debt-service figure to 3 percent.
</TEXT>
