<HEAD>Haraldson Named Chief of New AP Bureau</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS style in Texas in last graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press announced Friday it is
creating a new control bureau for South Dakota and North Dakota, and
named Tena Haraldson as bureau chief.
   The new bureau will be in Sioux Falls, S.D., which had been a
satellite office under the news agency's Minneapolis bureau, AP
President Louis D. Boccardi said.
   Haraldson, who has been correspondent in Sioux Falls, will direct
AP's news, photo and newspaper marketing operations in the two
states. Other AP offices in the new territory are in Pierre, S.D.,
and in Bismarck and Fargo, N.D. All had been under the direction of
the AP's Minneapolis bureau chief.
   ``This restructuring will allow us to expand and improve our
coverage of the Dakotas and bring control of our services closer to
our members in the two states,'' said Boccardi. ``In Tena Haraldson
we have a talented journalist and manager who is familiar with the
region, its issues and the needs of our members.''
   Haraldson, 34, has worked for the AP in South Dakota since 1976.
She joined in Sioux Falls, was named Pierre correspondent in 1980
and Sioux Falls correspondent in 1983.
   Haraldson is a native of San Angelo, Texas, who grew up in South
Dakota and graduated from South Dakota State University.
</TEXT>
