<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ShipCollision     12-16 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ship Collision,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Freighter Burns, Capsizes After Collision With Dutch Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 154-foot British freighter caught
fire and capsized after colliding Friday with a Dutch freighter
about 10 miles east of Puerto Rico, the U.S. Coast Guard said.
   All 13 crew members of the British ship Wishing Star were rescued
from the water by the 594-foot Dutch-registered container ship
Nedlloyed Van Noork, and no one was injured, Coast Guard spokesman
Alan Burd said.
   The Wishing Star, carrying propane and general cargo, caught fire
in the collision and the crew had to abandon ship, Burd said. The
Coast Guard was working to sink the vessel to protect beaches and
nesting areas along northeast Puerto Rico.
   Burd said the reason for the collision was not immediately known.
   He said the collision occurred around 2 a.m. between Puerto Rico
and Culebra Island, which is under Puerto Rican jurisdiction. The
Wishing Star caught fire shortly after the collision and capsized
around 5 a.m., Burd said.
   He said the ships were traveling in opposite directions, with the
Dutch ship headed for San Juan. He did not know their ports of
origin.
   Burd said the Coast Guard would not investigate,since the
collision happened in international waters and involved foreign
vessels.
