<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     12-16 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economist Replaces Hardliner On Foreign Affairs Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Czechoslovak Communist Party
appointed a top economic official to replace a veteran party
hardliner as head of a commission on foreign affairs, a party
spokesman said Friday.
   The appointment of Jozef Lenart, 65, indicates the leadership
wants to focus greater attention on boosting foreign economic
cooperation.
   Lenart replaces Vasil Bilak, 71, who resigned all his political
posts Thursday, citing his 20-year service as a Central Committee
secretary and member of the ruling Politburo.
   Spokesman Vladimir Patek made the announcement to journalists at
the end of a two-day party Central Committee meeting.
   He said Miroslav Valek also resigned as Slovak culture minister
at his own request, but remained a member of the Central Committee.
Valek last month called on the country's leadership to correct
mistakes made since the ``Prague Spring'' reforms of 1968 were
crushed by Soviet-led troops.
   Lenart is a Central Committee secretary in charge of the economy
and heads the party's commission for the national economy.
   He served as premier from 1963 to 1968, when the country began
implementing economic reforms leading up to the Prague Spring
reforms of then-Communist leader Alexander Dubcek.
   Patek told journalists the personnel changes were ``nothing but a
healthy variation of cadres and should not be given any other
context.''
   Communist Party leader Milos Jakes said in a closing speech to
the Central Committee meeting that economic reforms must be speeded
up, the official CTK news agency reported.
   The meeting examined economic results for this year and plans for
next year. It decided to convene the next party congress on May 10,
1990, one year ahead of schedule.
   Addressing the session Thursday, Premier Ladislav Adamec
criticized the country's trade status with Western countries. ``We
export to maintain our production and markets, but this does not
improve our position in convertible currencies,'' he said.
</TEXT>
