<HEAD>Ohio Senators, O'Neill Back Stanton for Party Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ohio Rep. Jim Stanton is being backed by
former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill of Massachusetts and Ohio
Sens. John Glenn and Howard Metzenbaum to be the Democratic Party's
next national chairman, a Metzenbaum spokeswoman said Friday.
   O'Neill, Glenn, Metzenbaum and Ohio Reps. Mary Rose Oakar and
Louis Stokes signed a Mailgram urging labor leaders nationwide to
throw their support behind Stanton, said Nancy Coffey, Metzenbaum's
press secretary.
   Stanton has not been in the public eye since his 1976 loss to
Metzenbaum in the Democratic Senate primary in Ohio. But he recently
moved to Washington and started laying plans for a return to
political life.
   The Mailgram praises Stanton as ``a friend of the labor movement
for many, many years.''
   ``For all practical purposes the Democratic Party's race to the
presidency in 1992 has already begun,'' it said. ``Our first step
must be to unite behind a leader who can reach out and appeal to
every corner of our diverse party. We believe Jim Stanton is such a
leader, and the support of labor is crucial to his candidacy.''
   The party's new leader is to be chosen at a meeting in Washington
Feb. 9 and 10 of the nearly 400 voting members of the Democratic
National Committee.
   Stanton so far has not been considered a front-runner for the job
being vacated after four years by Paul Kirk.
   Michigan Democratic Party Chairman Richard Wiener and longtime
party activist Ronald H. Brown have been mentioned most often as the
leading candidates in a field that also includes former Reps. James
Jones of Oklahoma and Michael Barnes of Maryland.
   Stanton was not in his office Friday afternoon and could not be
reached for comment.
