<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inclement Weather Dominates Both Coasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The sand dunes of Cape Hatteras, N.C., got some rare snow Friday
and Southern California endured a second day of snow, rain and high
winds, but the nation's midsection had mostly sunny, clear weather.
   In addition to coastal North Carolina, parts of northeastern
South Carolina also got some snow and sleet. Heavier snowfall during
the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 3 inches at New Bern,
and 2 inches at Hatteras, Wilmington and Cherry Point, all in North
Carolina.
   Snow and winter weather advisories were still in effect for the
northern and central coastal areas and the outer banks of North
Carolina.
   In Southern California, snow ended in the lower elevations but
continued in the mountains. A winter storm warning was extended for
the San Bernardino mountains northward, with a snow advisory for the
higher deserts of Southern California. A wind advisory issued for
the mountains of San Diego County.
   Mount Wilson, Calif., has received more than 3.5 inches of
precipitation since the storm began Thursday, most of it rain.
   A low pressure system moved across northern Minnesota toward the
Great Lakes, spreading light snow from eastern North Dakota to the
Upper Mississippi Valley. Gusty northwest winds caused blowing and
drifting snow in eastern North Dakota and northwest Minnesota. Gusts
were clocked at 43 mph at Alexandria, Minn.
   Travelers to the Northeast should expect of significant snowfall
expected over the weekend from New York City through much of New
England as a storm developed along the East Coast, the weather
service said.
   Although inclement weather dominated both coasts, the nation's
midsection enjoyed mostly sunshine and clear skies Friday.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 4
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 80 degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
The morning low for the nation was 18 degrees below zero at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   Saturday's forecast called for snow throughout most of New
England and into northern parts of the Middle Atlantic Coast. Snow
also should extend from the northern and central Appalachians across
the upper Ohio Valley into the Great Lakes. Rains also should
continue over much of central and Southern California. Fog and low
cloud cover was expected over Washington and Oregon.
   High temperatures should be in the teens and 20s from the North
Atlantic Coast across the upper Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes and the
upper half of the Mississippi Valley to eastern parts of the
northern Plains. Highs should range in the single digits over
northern Minnesota and northwest Wisconsin. Highs should warm into
the 50s and 60s from Florida across the Gulf Coast, most of Texas,
southern New Mexico and the desert Southwest to most of California,
climbing into the 70s over parts of southern Florida. Elsewhere
highs in the 30s and 40s should be the rule.
</TEXT>
