<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JacobsCaptured     12-16 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jacobs Captured,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Carolina Indian Fugitive Freed, Returns To Reservation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAMPSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian who fled North Carolina after
he was charged with taking hostages at a newspaper was released from
jail Friday following his arrest this week stemming from a car chase
with police.
   Timothy Jacobs was freed after the National Council of Churches
posted his $25,000 bail and the Onondaga Indian Nation, on whose
reservation he had sought refuge, provided a sworn statement that it
would not harbor him should Gov. Mario Cuomo order his extradition
to face the North Carolina charges.
   Jacobs, 20, of Pembroke, N.C., was arrested Tuesday near Oneida
after a chase with police that followed a traffic violation.
   Jacobs had been staying with the Onondagas after fleeing North
Carolina last week following his indictment on kidnapping charges
for the armed takeover of the Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton,
N.C., last February.
   Jacobs will live at the reservation near Syracuse, but is not
confined there, said his attorney, Alan Rosenthal of Syracuse.
   Rosenthal said he and attorney Lewis Pitts plan to formally ask
Cuomo to deny North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin's extradition request.
He said the extradition process could take weeks or even months.
   ``The governor of North Carolina is chomping at the bits to get
him back,'' said Rosenthal.
   A Robeson County grand jury on Dec. 6 indicted Jacobs and Eddie
Hatcher, 31, also of Pembroke, on 14 counts of kidnapping for taking
20 people hostage for 10 hours.
   The two Tuscarora Indians said that taking over the newspaper was
the only way they could draw attention to what they said was
pervasive public corruption in their home county. Hatcher is free on
$25,000 bail in North Carolina.
   Jacobs has said he fled North Carolina because he feared for his
life.
   Jacobs' bail was originally set at $50,000 by Madison County
Judge William F. O'Brien. The judge reduced the bail after he
received written assurance from Onondaga Nation Chief Leon
Shenandoah that the reservation would not provide sanctuary for
Jacobs.
   The Onondagas, members of the Six Nation Iroquois Confederacy,
consider their reservation a sovereign nation, and authorities are
reluctant to enter it without the tribe's permission. The Onondagas
harbored Indian activist Dennis Banks in the early 1980s.
   Jacobs will marry his 19-year-old fiancee next week, said the
bride-to-be, Kirsten Drummond.
   Jacobs is scheduled to appear in Madison County Court on Jan. 12
to face charges stemming from the car chase with state police.
</TEXT>
