<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FernaldLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0663 12-16 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald Lawsuit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uranium Plant's Neighbors Sue Over Alleged Radiation Pollution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `Because of..., with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
further attorney arguments, judge saying he is taking case under
review and hopes to issue ruling soon. Pickup 15th graf: `Production
at ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fernald uranium-processing plant repeatedly
contaminated its environs with radioactive materials and violated
pollution laws in three decades of operation, its neighbors told a
federal judge Friday.
   The neighbors are suing the Department of Energy plant's former
operators, National Lead of Ohio Inc. and its parent company,
National Lead Industries, in a $300 million class action.
   Their chief lawyer, Stanley Chesley, on Friday asked U.S.
District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel to issue a summary judgment in
favor of the plaintiffs. An Energy Department lawyer representing
National Lead argued that a summary judgment _ a judge's ruling
based on the evidence already presented without further proceedings
_ should be issued in favor of the company.
   Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio took over operation of the
37-year-old plant from National Lead, the facility's only previous
operator, on Jan. 1, 1986.
   The plant dumped radioactive radium and uranium daily into the
Great Miami River which flows by the 1,050-acre site, often
exceeding its stated desire to limit the uranium dumping to 36
pounds daily in the 1950s, said Chesley and his assistant, Louise
Roselle.
   The Great Miami aquifer, an underground regional water extending
southward from Dayton to Hamilton, Ohio, flows under the plant, and
there is evidence of radioactive ground water contamination at the
plant site, Chesley said.
   The plaintiffs' attorneys also said they have evidence to show
that the plant has subjected residents to excessive daily doses of
radiation and has failed to qualify for federal Clean Air Act
operating permits since 1984.
   Chesley told the court he has documents indicating that the
government apparently lied when it told residents in the past that
the plant was not contaminating the environment.
   But Energy Department lawyer Marc Johnston said the department
found that National Lead did not violate its contract with the
government in running the plant. That is critical, he argued,
because Congress exempted Energy Department facilities from the laws
that the neighbors cite and instead left it up to the Energy
Department to regulate its own facilities.
   ``We do not dispute that there were emissions of various
materials from that plant, including uranium,'' Johnston said. ``We
do deny that there were hazardous conditions created.''
   The Energy Department admitted in 1985 that the plant had
released an estimated 300,000 pounds of uranium oxide dust into the
atmosphere through faulty exhaust-air filter systems during three
decades of operations.
   The Energy Department is representing National Lead of Ohio and
its parent because they ultimately were told by the government how
to operate the plant, Johnston said. The government is not a
defendant in the lawsuit.
   Johnston also said he was challenging Spiegel's previous decision
to grant class-action status to the lawsuit.
   He argued that National Lead cannot be found liable because it
was following the government's orders to run the plant, and an
Energy Department contract enforcement officer concluded that the
company had carried out its responsibilities.
   Chesley introduced in court a January 1985 letter by Joe LaGrone,
an Energy Department manager who oversees the plant from Oak Ridge,
Tenn., to National Lead Industries of Hightstown, N.J.
   LaGrone said in the letter that he found National Lead of Ohio's
performance unsatisfactory in production operations, health, safety
and fire requirements, environmental management and budget
administration.
   The Energy Department penalized the company by subtracting more
than $1 million from its contract payments, Chesley said. ``It
certainly belies that this company was in compliance,'' Chesley said
of the letter.
   The judge ended the court session by saying he was taking the
case under review and would try to issue his ruling soon.
   Because of Spiegel's previous decision to certify the lawsuit as
a class-action, it represents 14,000 people living within five miles
of the plant, formally known as the Feed Materials Production
Center, which has operated since 1951 and processes uranium for the
government's production elsewhere of nuclear weapons.
   Production at the plant has been halted since Oct. 7 because of a
strike by workers who are to vote Saturday on a tentative contract.
   The neighbors allege the plant contaminated the environs 18 miles
northwest of Cincinnati, polluting air, water and land and
subjecting neighbors to excessive radiation exposure. They say they
are due damages for emotional distress, exposure-caused health
impairments and reduced property values caused by the plant's
proximity.
   Chesley cited a series of presidential executive orders since
1948 that he said required federal agencies to work with state and
local agencies to avoid pollution and to comply with environmental
laws unless the president grants specific exemptions because of
national security. No president has granted any such exemption for
the Fernald plant, he said.
   The state of Ohio on Dec. 2 reached a court-approved settlement
with the Energy Department granting the state environmental
supervision of hazardous wastes at the plant. Ohio officials said
the agreement will allow the state to police the federal cleanup of
the site.
   But Chesley said the agreement does not commit the federal
government to the cleanup and does not give Ohio regulatory power
over radioactive wastes stored at the plant. Radioactive wastes are
regulated separately from hazardous materials.
</TEXT>
