<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChappellConcedes     12-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chappell Concedes,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Congressman Gives Up Fight To Keep Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. William Chappell, who lost his
bid for re-election by 791 votes in the Nov. 8 general election,
formally conceded Friday.
   Republican newcomer Craig James, a DeLand attorney, defeated the
10-term Democrat by a margin of less than 1 percent of the 250,000
votes cast in the northeast Florida district.
   ``I must acknowledge the Republican Party has won the seat in the
4th Congressional District of Florida, and I have decided against
pursuing a challenge any further,'' said Chappell, whose campaign
was dogged by reports linking him to investigations of the Pentagon
procurement scandal. He has not been charged in any defense
contractor investigations.
   James was not immediately available for comment; a message was
left on his home answering machine.
   Chappell, 66, of Daytona Beach Shores, sought to have the state
Supreme Court throw out nearly 11,000 votes from Flagler County, but
the court turned back his request Nov. 30.
   The Flagler County results reached the state division of
elections office one day after a seven-day state deadline. If
results from that county had been thrown out, Chappell would have
won the race by 229 votes.
   In addition to his 20 years in Washington, Chappell served in the
Florida House of Representatives for 10 years and was its speaker in
1961. He was prosecuting attorney in Marion County between 1949 and
1954.
</TEXT>
