<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1922EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-SovietQuake     12-16 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Quake,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head of US Disaster Team Says Distribution of Supplies is Key
Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a U.S. government delegation to the
earthquake zone of Soviet Armenia returned home Friday saying
distribution of relief supplies is the major concern there now.
   Julia Taft, director of the Agency for International
Development's office of foreign disaster assistance, said she would
meet with President Reagan on Monday and recommend more U.S.
assistance to meet the immediate needs of housing, shelter and
storage facilities.
   ``The major concern that we see is one of logistics _ how we can
facilitate the reception, sorting out and distribution of the kinds
of commodities that have gone in,'' she said.
   ``The U.S. government has sent in tents and blankets and plastic
sheeting and medical supplies. Much of that has gotten out but there
still are warehouses full,'' she said. ``... There just isn't enough
space. And there aren't enough buses and trucks to get it out to the
villages. And some of the villages are inaccessible at this point.''
   Taft spoke upon her arrival at Washington Dulles Airport in
suburban Virginia on Friday night, one week after she and a team of
46 U.S. disaster relief workers, doctors, emergency experts and
Armenian officials left for the earthquake-stricken region of the
Soviet Union.
   She said no more medical supplies should be sent to the region.
She said the way individual Americans can best help is by donating
money to assistance funds.
   The U.S. government has donated $1.8 million in assistance, she
said, and private U.S. efforts have contributed another $5 million.
Efforts in Armenia, she said, are now shifting from emergency
efforts to more long-term assistance for individuals left homeless
or without family members.
   The U.S. team was greeted warmly and emotionally as team members
personally delivered masks and gloves and other emergency supplies
to survivors, she said. Many of the team members remained in the
Soviet Union and will stay beyond Christmas.
   ``It's so cold there. It's snowing and it's bitter,'' she said.
   ``Almost every local Armenian in the cities is shellshocked,''
she said. ``It looks like a war zone. These people are stunned.
They're living next to hovels that were their homes. ... They are
sitting by fires at night, waiting to hear the voice of a loved one
buried. During the day, they are in the rubble, digging.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
