<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smith-Execution     12-16 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smith-Execution,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Block Missouri Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court that twice
blocked the death of double murderer Gerald Smith refused Friday to
stop Smith's latest scheduled execution, set for 12:01 a.m. Tuesday.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis ruled 7-3 to
deny a petition filed by Smith's wife that sought to reopen the case.
   Lynn Smith's request cited a recent newspaper article that raised
doubts about Smith's guilt.
   The court rejected the request without comment.
   The ruling apparently leaves it to the U.S. Supreme Court or to
Smith to stop the execution, which would be the first in Missouri
since 1965.
   Smith has ordered appeals dropped and on Friday, prison officials
said he appeared ``committed to carrying through with it.''
   Smith, 30, is sentenced to die for two unrelated murders. He
faces death warrants for the 1980 murder of Karen Roberts and the
1985 stabbing death of fellow death row inmate Robert Baker.
</TEXT>
