<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliticalPayments     12-16 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Payments,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide To Sen. Chiles Earns $99,000 While On Paid Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administrative assistant to Sen.
Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., earned $99,000 while on a paid leave of
absence to help Florida Democrats in state legislative races, a
newspaper reported Friday.
   Charles E. Canady earned the money for five months of work as
campaign chairman of the Florida House Leadership Council while
continuing to draw his full $85,000-a-year Senate salary, the St.
Petersburg Times reported.
   Chiles said Canady had accumulated enormous amounts of
compensatory time and unused vacation and holidays during his 18
years on the senator's staff.
   ``So when Charles wanted to get involved actively with the House
Leadership Council during the campaign season, I agreed he should be
compensated for all the extra time he had applied in his Senate
job,'' Chiles said in a statement.
   Canady continued to consult with Chiles' staff when needed during
his paid leave, the senator said.
   ``I took (the paid leave) with the senator's approval,'' said
Canady, 55. ``Instead of taking a long vacation, I decided to work
with the House Leadership Council.''
   Senate rules do not prohibit staff members from carrying vacation
time from one year to another.
   ``It's left up to the individual senator's discretion,'' said
Timothy S. Wineman, assistant financial clerk in the Office of the
Secretary of the U.S. Senate.
   Chiles did not seek re-election this year and will leave office
next month. His seat was won by Republican U.S. Rep. Connie Mack.
</TEXT>
