<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0670 12-16 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Seize Three U.N. Soldiers, Demand Release Of Leader Held By
Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with Swiss Red Cross man's
release. Picks up 3rd pvs, `Friday's abduction...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen on Friday kidnapped three Irish
soldiers serving with the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon
and demanded the release of a guerrilla leader abducted by Israel,
police said.
   In other developments Friday:
   _Peter Winkler, a Swiss official of the International Committee
of the Red Cross who was kidnapped on Nov. 17, was released in the
southern city of Sidon. He said he did not know who kidnapped him.
Voice of Lebanon radio said Winkler was released by the
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, the guerrilla group headed by
Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal.
   _Police said eight fighters were killed and four wounded in Sidon
when the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia fought guerrillas of
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Friday's abduction was the second time in less than 24 hours that
Lebanese gunmen captured Irish troops to retaliate for Israel's
seizure of Jawad Kasfi.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army said its soldiers in south Lebanon
seized Kasfi, another senior local guerrilla commander and two other
guerrilla suspects in the village of Tibnin on Thursday.
   Police said four gunmen in two cars seized the three Irish
soldiers in Tibnin on Friday, bundled them into a white Mercedes and
sped away. The village borders on Israel's self-proclaimed security
zone.
   Lebanese police said on condition of anonymity that the
kidnappers demanded that the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, with
which the three Irish soldiers served, negotiate with Israel for the
release of the four guerrilla suspects.
   UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel said the U.N. force has not
negotiated with Israel so far.
   ``They (Israel) acknowledged that they are holding these people.
This was our only official contact,'' Goksel said. ``Of course,
there was a very strong protest from UNIFIL because it was an
infringement on UNIFIL zone. But we got no response to that.''
   The Israeli army identified Kasfi as a leader of the Religious
Resistance Front headed by Mustafa Dirani, a splinter faction of
Amal.
   The faction is affiliated with the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, a fundamentalist movement at odds with Amal.
   The military command said Kasfi was suspected of organizing and
participating in kidnappings and dozens of attacks against Israeli
army forces and the allied South Lebanon Army militia since 1984.
   ``The suspects are undergoing interrogation,'' the army said in a
statement. ``Those ... found innocent of attacks will be released.''
   Kasfi was abducted by two Israeli soldiers and three South
Lebanon Army men who drove into Tibnin in civilian cars, Lebanese
police said. A spokesman made no mention of other captives.
   Goksel said U.N. peacekeeping troops, backed by Amal militiamen,
would keep searching in the area until the missing men are found.
   Tibnin is 15 miles north of the Israeli border in the U.N.
force's zone of operations.
   The zone patrolled by the nine-nation U.N. force overlaps the
Israeli security belt, which is six to 10 miles deep and runs from
the Mediterranean to the foothills of mount Hermon. It is designed
to curb cross-border guerrilla raids.
   U.N. troops ``blocked all roads in its area of operations ... in
an effort to prevent the gunmen from smuggling the three Irish
soldiers out of south Lebanon,'' a police spokesman said.
   Amal, which regularly cooperates with the U.N. force,
``threatened to crack down on the kidnappers ``if the three soldiers
were not released by nightfall,'' the spokesman said.
   Asked after sundown whether Amal had taken direct action to
rescue the Irishmen, he said: ``No. Apparently they are still
considering giving peaceful efforts a chance.''
   He declined to say to which group the kidnappers belonged, but
said they are known to Amal, the U.N. force and police.
   Three other Irish UNIFIL soldiers were seized on Thursday by
armed residents of Tibnin in retaliation for the kidnapping.
   But they were released an hour later when Amal promised villagers
that the U.N. force would seek to locate Kasfi and bring him back.
   The afternoon clashes at Sidon were touched off when two
Palestinians were killed by a rocket-propelled grenade fired by Amal
gunners near the Ein el-Hilweh Palestinian refugee camp, police said.
   The battles with mortars, grenades and machine guns raged after
nightfall on Sidon's southern outskirts, triggering fears of a major
confrontation that would negate a 20-month-old Syrian-brokered truce.
   Amal fought a two-year war with the Palestinians before the truce
took hold. More than 1,500 people were killed and 3,500 wounded in
the fighting, in which Syrian-backed Amal tried to prevent PLO
chairman Yasser Arafat from rebuilding the Lebanon power base he
lost in Israel's 1982 invasion.
</TEXT>
