<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-Hughes     12-16 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Hughes,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Drops Out Of Collusive Pricing Suit Against Hughes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has decided to withdraw from a
lawsuit alleging that Hughes Helicopter Co. engaged in collusive
pricing on parts used to produce the Army's Apache helicopter, the
Justice Department announced Friday.
   The department said there was insufficient evidence to
demonstrate that the government was damaged in connection with
allegations of collusive pricing on parts provided by Parker
Hannifin Corp.'s Bertea Controls Division of Los Angeles for use in
the Apache.
   The allegations were contained in a private lawsuit filed by a
former Hughes employee, Roderick Stillwell.
   The suit also alleged that Hughes submitted false requests for
reimbursement of tooling charges incurred on the Parker subcontract.
   The government joined the suit, which was filed in March 1987 in
U.S. District Court in Los Angeles, but it withdrew after conducting
an extensive investigation, Assistant Attorney General John Bolton
said in a statement.
   The investigation included the informal discovery and audit of
thousands of documents provided by Parker Hannifin and by McDonnell
Douglas Corp., which owns Hughes Aircraft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
