<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 2058EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Laws     12-16 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Laws,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Penal Code Revisions Lists Capital Crimes, Allows Holding In
Isolation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed revision of the Soviet penal code says
convicts may be executed for crimes ranging from treason to rape and
allows authorities to hold people under arrest in isolation,
official media said Friday.
   The two-page draft revision, the first result of a long-promised
change in the criminal laws, appeared in the government newspaper
Izvestia.
   The draft apparently does not deal with the two sections of the
penal code most criticized by Western human rights activists. The
code now allows authorities to imprison people on charges of
anti-Soviet slander and anti-Soviet agitation.
   The proposed revision has been submitted to the two houses of the
Supreme Soviet, or parliament, for discussion. The deputies were
asked to submit their conclusions to the Presidium, or chief
executive body of parliament, by March 15, the official news agency
Tass said.
   One new section would permit authorities to keep people under
arrest in isolation for one to three months, with the exception of
women who are pregnant or have children under the age of eight.
   A series of crimes which are not included in the current code and
which would be punishable by death ``under extraordinary
circumstances'' are listed in the draft. The draft does not say what
the circumstances would be.
   Betrayal of the state, spying, terrorist acts, sabotage,
premeditated murder under aggravating cirumstances, and rape of
minors could be punishable by death.
   Under the provisions of the draft, the death sentence could not
be applied to people under the age of 18 and over the age of 60.
   Although the revised code is more severe concerning arrest and
capital punishment, certain punishments have been dropped.
   Exile and deportation, two measures that prohibit a person from
living in certain cities, are not included in the draft. Under
current law, the two measures are listed under ``types of
punishment.''
   In the past, dissidents often were exiled or deported as part of
their sentence, helping to fragment the dissident movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
