<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     12-16 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Eastern Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 leftist guerrillas on
Friday attacked an eastern army battalion in an operation that
included sabotage of power lines and gasoline stations, officials
said.
   At least four guerrillas were killed. The army said one soldier
and three civilians were wounded.
   Guerrillas coordinated the mortar and rifle attack on the
headquarters of the Atonal army battalion in Usulutan, 70 miles east
of San Salvador, with sabotage in central El Salvador that left most
of the capital without electricity for much of Friday.
   Capt. Mario Miranda, spokesman for the 6th army brigade based in
Usulutan, told said in a telephone interview that the fighting began
about midnight and lasted for two hours.
   Miranda said at least two guerrilla groups, of 60 and 40
combatants, fired mortars and rifles at the Atonal base in a
``harassment'' action. No rebel mortars fell inside the compound, he
said.
   Troops from the 6th brigade and the Atonal battalion and national
and treasury Police repelled the attackers, he said.
   The guerrillas also used explosives to partially destroy two
gasoline stations and blow up five utility transmission poles,
Miranda said.
   The sabotage left the entire province of Usulutan and parts of
San Miguel and La Union provinces without electricty for several
hours.
   Officers permitted reporters to photograph the four slain rebels
but refused to permit access to the battalion base to survey
possible damage.
</TEXT>
