<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 2100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Quake     12-16 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Quake,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Allocates Money for Reconstruction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARS, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has allocated $50,000 to house
hundreds of families left homeless in an eastern province from the
earthquake that devastated nearby Soviet Armenia, the provincial
governor said Friday.
   Four people were killed in the region in the Dec. 7 quake.
   Gov. Hasan Pakir of Kars province said 560 families were left
homeless in Akyaka and Arpacay townships on the border with the
Soviet Union. He did not give an exact number of people.
   New houses for those families will be finished by the end of
1989, Pakir said in an interview. The families will spend the winter
in makeshift homes they built for themselves using logs provided by
the state, he said.
   The area affected by the quake is dotted with mountain villages
in which many people live in homes of mud brick.
   Relief workers have set up 1,909 tents, issued 3,000 blankets and
distributed three tons of food to the victims, Pakir added.
   The governor said financial aid will be made available to those
whose houses were slightly damaged in the quake.
   Most of eastern Turkey lies on the Anatolian fault and the area
has been hit often by temblors.
   Last week's quake killed an estimated 55,000 people in Soviet
Armenia.
   An earthquake in 1983 killed 3,000 people in the Turkish
provinces of Kars and Erzurum. Another quake killed 30,000 in the
eastern province of Erzincan in 1939.
</TEXT>
