<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-Tents     12-16 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Tents,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Tape Delays Effort To Send Temporary Housing To Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of 17 volunteers ran into
complications obtaining an airplane Friday to take them to Soviet
Armenia, where they had planned to provide plastic tents for about
3,000 earthquake victims.
   ``This is frustrating,'' said Anthony Seraphin, president of a
Springfield-based company that came up with the idea for
quick-to-build, durable plastic shelters. ``There's 17 of us here
waiting to go and we've just heard a news report about people
literally freezing to death'' at the earthquake site.
   The Air National Guard had agreed to provide a C-141 transport
plane, but needed the approval of Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
before the civilians could board, Seraphin said.
   A Defense Department spokeswoman, Maj. Shelley Rogers, said
Friday night that the department received the request and ``it will
be forwarded to the State Department Monday.''
   ``It's got to get the proper approval,'' she said.
   She did not say how long the approval process could take.
   Soviet officials say the Dec. 7 quake claimed 55,000 lives and
left 500,000 of the 700,000 people in the area homeless.
   ``It's just so insane,'' Seraphin said. ``We're here ready to go
and we can't get through.''
   Seraphin said the group, whose mission was being coordinated with
the Armenian Relief Society, had hoped to leave by Saturday.
   Union Carbide Corp. of Danbury, Conn., which makes the resin from
which the film is manufactured, will pay the estimated $100,000 cost
of the effort.
   The team wants to take material for 100 opaque blue,
576-square-foot tents that will provide shelter for 30 people each,
said Union Carbide spokesman John P. Yimoyines.
   The tents will be warmed by the sun during the day, but will lose
much of their heat at night.
   ``They'll be good wind protection and weather protection,'' said
Lou Agnello, another Union Carbide spokesman. He said the film could
withstand temperatures as low as 50 degrees below zero without
cracking.
   Seraphin said the group is also looking elsewhere for a plane.
</TEXT>
