<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-WorldHealth     12-16 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-World Health,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WHO Chief: Sex Discrimination, Youth Alienation Threaten World
Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes for a healthy world by the turn of the
century are threatened by discrimination against women and
alienation of youth from their parents, the head of the World Health
Organization said Friday.
   ``If you fail to give education to women, how can you give the
message of AIDS prevention ... of spacing childbirths'' and of
elementary sanitation and simple treatment of such child-killers as
diarrhea, asked Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima.
   The new WHO director-general departed from a prepared speech to
declare ``the gap between men and women'' an obstacle to achieving
WHO's goal of ``Health for all by the Year 2000.''
   In the fight against AIDS, ``since there is yet neither vaccine,
treatment nor cure, our only weapon against this lethal disease is
health education and information,'' he said in an address to the
National Council for International Health and the Council of
Washington Representatives on the United Nations.
   ``Yet if you look at reality, in many developing nations ... the
gap between men and women still depends on the economic climate. In
many developing countries ... only the men are going to school,'' he
said.
   Nakajima said WHO is leading not only a worldwide scientific
search for a vaccine against AIDS but also, with two other U.N.
agencies, is attacking the problem of providing basic knowledge to
women and mothers unable to read.
   The other agencies are the U.N. Children's Fund and UNESCO, the
U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
   Nakajima, a Japanese physician elected earlier this year as WHO's
fourth director-general, said there is an urgent need for parents
``to re-establish dialogue with our children.'' Answering a
question, he said young people especially in advanced countries seem
``completely isolated'' from their elders, experimenting with
narcotics and unsafe sex to the detriment of health.
   ``If we continue this kind of mistrust between generations, there
will be further deterioration'' of health, especially in the spread
of AIDS, he said.
   AIDS or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system and renders it
powerless against other illnesses.
   Nakajima said the long battle to eradicate tuberculosis was a
near-success until recently, when ``in just a few months the
situation changed in Africa, most probably due to the spread of AIDS
infection which decreased immunity _ and even some parts of the
United States like in New York City reported increased
tuberculosis...''
   He praised President Reagan's message to the recent world
conference on AIDS as a ``very powerful'' contribution to the fight
against ``the most serious disease of this century.'' Reagan upheld
the individual human rights of those infected while declaring them
responsible to ensure that the virus is not transmitted to others,
Nakajima noted.
   Surgeon General Dr. C. Everett Koop has provided strong support
to WHO in its campaigns against both AIDS and smoking, Nakajima
said, asserting that tobacco causes 2.5 million premature deaths a
year, and 90 percent of lung cancer cases.
   He voiced hope that the United States will quickly pay $7.5
million in overdue U.N. assessments earmarked for the health
organization now that WHO has undertaken financial and personnel
reforms demanded by Congress.
</TEXT>
