<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CostaRica-Panama     12-16 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Panama,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rica Protests Incidents on Border With Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government protested Friday to
Panama about violations of Costa Rica's southern border, saying such
incidents encourage suspicion among the two peoples.
   Foreign Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto issued the protest in a
letter to Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter which was
delivered to Panamanian Ambassador Dario Arosemena Gonzalez.
   The letter referred to border intrusions that reportedly occurred
last week but said such incidents have been happening regularly
since November 1987. Costa Rica shares all its southern border with
Panama.
   ``A situation has developed along the border that in no way
should continue,'' Madrigal said in his letter.
   The Costa Rican government is concerned ``not only because the
acts violate the territorial integrity of Costa Rica,'' but also
because they foment insecurity and suspicion between the people of
both nations, the letter said.
   It said the Panamanian National Guard, aided by soldiers and
intelligence officials, held eight Costa Rican citizens for five
hours last week after contraband coffee was found in a Panamanian
vehicle in Costa Rica.
   It also said Costa Rican Planning Minister Jorge Monge, touring
the border area Oct. 11, surprised a Panamanian military patrol of
eight men in two vehicles.
   When Monge asked if the soldiers knew they were in Costa Rica,
they explained they knowingly drove in Costa Rica territory as a way
to avoid poorly-maintained Panamanian border roads.
   Hernan Garron, the Costa Rican minister of public security, has
said border residents repeatedly complain about Panama violating
Costa Rican sovereignty.
</TEXT>
