<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg     12-16 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steinberg Defense Abandons Formal Insanity Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for a man accused of beating his
6-year-old adopted daughter to death said Friday they have decided
not to file a formal insanity plea to avoid taking action ``that
would poison the jury's mind.''
   Defense attorney Ira London said such a defense would require him
to call psychiatric experts to prove that Joel Steinberg was insane.
It would also require that prosecution psychiatrists be allowed to
examine Steinberg.
   ``We felt in view of the vast amount of investigation the DA has
done in this case, in view of all the reports they have obtained _
whether verified or unverified _ it would poison the jury's mind as
to Joel,'' London said.
   ``It would open the door to (questioning about) any rumor,
anything they had about Joel coming into this case,'' he said, ``so
we made a determination we didn't want that.''
   London was referring in part to reports of Steinberg's heavy drug
use, his often bizarre behavior, his reported belief in cults that
hypnotized people and used them sexually and his alleged violence
against others.
   London said he had not decided whether to continue pursuit of an
insanity defense in which he lets the jury infer from testimony _
without defense attorneys saying explicitly _ that Steinberg was
crazy the night Lisa was fatally injured.
   Steinberg, 47, is a disbarred lawyer charged with second-degree
murder in the fatal beating of Lisa, a child he illegally adopted
shortly after her birth.
   The first-grader was removed unconscious from the Greenwich
Village apartment Steinberg shared with his longtime companion,
Hedda Nussbaum, 13 months ago. The child died in the hospital three
days later.
   Lisa's death in an affluent, well-educated household shocked many
New Yorkers and led to a re-examination of the duty and ability of
neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   Steinberg denies that he hit the girl, but Ms. Nussbaum, the
prosecution's chief witness, said he told her the night Lisa was
fatally injured that he had ``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want
to get up.''
   The defense team's decision to abandon the formal insanity
defense was announced just after state Supreme Court Justice Harold
Rothwax excused the jury for the day without any trial proceedings
because an alternate juror was ill.
   London's co-counsel, Adrian DiLuzio, said the defense does not
have to call witnesses to testify about Steinberg's state of mind.
   ``The evidence (of mental disease or defect) can emerge from any
source,'' DiLuzio said. ``If the evidence emerged from the
prosecution's witness _ as I would submit to you it may have _ then
that may be considered by the jury as meeting our burden of going
forward on the affirmative defense.''
   An example of what DiLuzio was talking about is found in London's
five-day cross-examination of Ms. Nussbaum, in which she testified
that Steinberg said and did bizarre things before Lisa's death.
   But if London and DiLuzio try for an insanity defense without
saying so, prosecutors on summation will almost certainly call the
jury's attention to it and argue that no psychiatric experts have
been presented to support it.
   And Rothwax indicated he would instruct the jurors that an
insanity defense was being offered _ whether the defense called it
that or not _ and he would say it was up to them to decide whether
Steinberg was criminally responsible for Lisa's death.
   The trial was to resume Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
