<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TeacherShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0676 12-16 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0676,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Killed, Another Wounded When Student Opens Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to clarify in lede that student fired on third
classroom but gun jammed before anyone was hit, UPDATES with ID of
dead teacher, second teacher in serious condition with gunshot wound
to chest, charges against student. SUBS grafs 10-11 to CORRECT
deputy's name to Terry sted Perry and school trustee to Boelens sted
Bolens. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student shot two teachers, killing
one and seriously wounding another, then began firing on a classroom
full of students Friday, police said.
   The student's gun jammed before anyone was hit and he was
disarmed by the students and teachers in the classroom at the
Atlantic Shores Christian School, said police spokesman Lewis
Thurston.
   The two teachers were shot about 10:30 a.m. in separate
classrooms in which there were no students, Thurston said. The
student, a sophomore at the school, then allegedly entered the third
classroom and opened fire with a Mac-10 9mm pistol, similar to a
small Uzi, before the weapon was wrestled away, Thurston said.
   He identified the teacher who was killed as Karen Farley, in her
late 30s or early 40s. Teacher Sam Marino, 37, was in serious
condition with a gunshot wound to the chest, said Anne Adler,
spokeswoman at Sentara Norfolk General Hospital.
   The shootings occurred in the junior and senior sections of the
school, in a complex of four trailers outside the main building.
   School officials did not know the two teachers had been shot
until they realized they had not seen one of them since the
shooting, and her body was not found until about 90 minutes after
the incident, Thurston said.
   The suspect, whom police declined to identify because he is a
juvenile, was charged with one count of first-degree murder, one
count of malicious assault and four counts of attempted murder. He
also was charged with using a firearm in a felony and discharging a
firearm in an occupied building.
   Thurston said the youth is either 15 or 16 and a sophomore at the
school.
   He said police have no motive for the shooting. Police found
homemade explosives in a locker in the school, but he had no further
information on where they came from, Thurston said.
   David Terry, a city deputy sheriff who was at the scene, said he
had been told that a third teacher was the gunman's intended target.
   The school, which is affiliated with the fundamentalist Atlantic
Shores Baptist Church, has 500 students in kindergarten through 12th
grade. Students were sent home following the shooting and school
trustee Martin Boelens said students were receiving counseling.
   Church officials would not allow reporters in the school and a
parent said she had been advised not to speak to reporters.

</TEXT>
