<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Africa     12-16 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Africa,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Says France To Withdraw Some Troops From Chad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois Mitterrand
said Friday that his country plans to withdraw some of its soldiers
from Chad now that Libyan troops have been driven out of the central
African country.
   Speaking at a news conference at the close of the 39-nation
Franco-African summit, Mitterrand did not specify how many of the
1,700 troops in Operation Sparrowhawk will leave Chad, or when.
   ``Now that peace is approaching and Chad has achieved its unity
and reestablished its sovereignty, the military need is not the
same,'' Mitterrand said.
   Presidential aides said Mitterrand discussed the issue privately
with President Hissene Habre of Chad and agreed on terms for the
pullout.
   Under Operation Sparrowhawk, which began in February 1986 at
Habre's request, the French guaranteed the security of roughly half
of Chad's territory _ the portion south of the 16th parallel.
   Chadian troops drove the Libyans out of northern Chad in a series
of attacks between December 1986 and August 1987. France said its
troops were not directly involved, although both France and the
United States supplied military aid to the Chadians.
   French troops were sent to Chad in 1983, then withdrawn in 1984
as part of an agreement with Col. Moammar Gadhafi for a simultaneous
departure of Libyan troops. The Libyans, however, did not live up to
their part of the bargain.
   Of the 39 countries at the 15th Franco-African summit, 22 were
represented by their armed forces chiefs of staff.
   In a statement issued at the conclusion, the countries said they
were pleased at the prospects of settlements in Angola and the
Western Sahara, but expressed concern at falling commodities prices
which ``paralyze all development in Africa and make the debt burden
unbearable.''
</TEXT>
