<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-GrandJury     12-16 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Grand Jury,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: No More Indictments in PTL Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors will not seek any more
indictments against the targets of a 16-month grand jury
investigation into Jim Bakker's leadership of the PTL ministries.
   ``We do not expect to ask the grand jury to return any additional
indictments against anyone,'' said James Knapp, a deputy assistant
attorney general who oversees the Justice Department's criminal tax
investigations.
   The grand jury indicted Bakker and three former associates on
Dec. 5, charging that they misused millions of dollars of PTL money.
   Bakker and Richard Dortch, Bakker's former top deputy, are
charged with mail fraud, wire fraud and conspiracy. David Taggart,
Bakker's former personal secretary, and James Taggart, PTL's former
interior decorator, are charged with tax evasion and conspiracy.
   Prosecutors and Justice Department officials considered seeking
tax charges against Bakker and Dortch. But Assistant U.S. Attorney
Jerry Miller said Thursday Bakker and Dortch would not be charged
with any more crimes.
   Bakker, Dortch, the Taggart brothers and Roe Messner, PTL's chief
builder under Bakker, had been identified as targets of the
investigation.
   Messner was not named in the indictment.
   Bakker, 48, resigned in 1987 amid revelations he had a sexual
encounter with former church secretary Jessica Hahn and paid her
hush money. Three months later, amid reports of financial
wrongdoing, PTL filed for bankruptcy.
   On Tuesday, Canadian real estate magnate Stephen Mernick, an
Orthodox Jew, bought PTL's assets, including its Christian theme
park, hotel and broadcast studios in Fort Mill, S.C., for $65
million in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   The fate of the PTL's religious operations, which were spun off
by the court into the non-profit Heritage Ministries, remained
unclear. Heritage Ministries uses facilities at the theme park.
</TEXT>
