<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HouseFiresRdp     12-16 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Fires Rdp,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blazes in Three States Leave Eight Dead, 200 Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Ohio poet and two members of his family were killed
Friday when fire broke out in their home, and four children and an
adult died in an Alabama blaze believed started by matches.
   In New York City, about 200 people were left homeless when a fire
raged through a Staten Island apartment complex, but there were no
serious injuries, firefighters said.
   In Beachwood, Ohio, a suburb of Cleveland, poet James Kilgore,
58, his daughter Sheila, 24, and her 19-month-old son, Julius, died
in the fire, authorities said. Kilgore's wife, Alberta, and son,
Steven, were treated for smoke inhalation.
   Kilgore was the author of nine volumes of poetry and a teacher
for 22 years at Cuyahoga Community College, said college spokeswoman
Marcia Ballinger. He won the Ohio Poetry Association's Ohio Poet of
the Year award in 1982 with his last volume of poetry, ``African
Violet: Poem for a Black Woman.''
   Beachwood Fire Chief William Kaselak said the fire was under
investigation.
   In York, Ala., the blaze that killed five early Friday apparently
began when youngsters in the home played with matches. Survivors had
to go two blocks to find a phone to call firefighters.
   Sumter County Coroner James Campbell said firefighters had no
chance of saving anyone in the wood-frame house, which was reported
ablaze about midnight.
   ``It was burned about 75 percent when we got there, and it was
about 90 percent by the time they got it extinguished,'' he said.
   Two families shared the home, said Fire Chief Wayne Simmers. He
identified the dead as brothers Harold Wayne and Michael Evans, both
3, their 9-year-old sister, Shameka, the childrens' uncle, Nathaniel
Evans, 21, and his 3-year-old son, Tony Chapman.
   Campbell said three other children escaped and told investigators
they had been playing with matches.
   The nearest occupied house was about a half-block away, the
coroner said, but the children had to go two blocks before finding a
home with a telephone to summon firefighters.
   Some 30 familes were left homeless by the five-alarm fire in the
Staten Island apartment complex. The blaze, apparently an accidental
electrical fire, began in a fourth-floor apartment late Thursday and
spread to the roof of the seven-story brick structure, causing the
roof to partially collapse, said Fire Department spokesman John
Mulligan.
   Mulligan said the blaze was well-advanced by time firefighters
arrived and was not under control until early Friday. ``We were
hampered by wind, cold and ice,'' he said.
   About 100 people were staying with relatives or friends and the
rest were put up in motels, said Mike Azzara, executive assistant to
Borough President Ralph Lamberti.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
