<1ST_LINE>a i PM-FallofRome Adv21   12-16 1062</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fall of Rome, Adv 21,1089</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Dec. 21 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Eternal City Losing War against Modern-Day Ravages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When an Italian historian recently called Rome a
corrupt, vulgar and violent city that shouldn't be the nation's
capital, Romans rose up in anger.
   But many also conceded that the Eternal City that has survived
sackings, sieges and the fall of an empire appears helpless against
the onslaughts of the 1980s _ not to mention what lies ahead in
1990, when Italy serves as host to the World Cup soccer tournament.
Rome has virtually no major projects under way to prepare for an
event comparable to the Olympics.
   Chaotic traffic, air and noise pollution, crumbling monuments and
inadequate public transportation are some of the symptoms of modern
Rome's problems.
   ``The central government has never really had any interest in
governing Rome,'' says Francesco D'Onofrio, a former Christian
Democrat senator who is one of many who favor moving government
offices out of the historic center.
   There is a proposal, though still far from being realized, to
build a government and business center on 1,600 acres on the eastern
edge of the city.
   ``Rome isn't really a capital, it's a work of art and works of
art ought not to be capitals,'' said the American author Gore Vidal,
who has kept an apartment in central Rome for 26 years.
   While Italy has experienced great economic strides in recent
years and claims to have surpassed Britain as the world's fifth
largest industrial power, the capital has continued to suffer from
what many here describe as second-rate services.
   Romans themselves have long complained about the deterioration of
their city, but it took a verbal broadside by a Parliament member
and historian from Turin to push the issue to the forefront of
national attention.
   Explaining why he spearheaded the defeat of a bill in
Parliament's Chamber of Deputies that would have allocated $156
million for restoration of Rome monuments, Luigi Firpo declared:
``Rome is rotten, asphyxiated by car fumes. It would be useless to
undertake major restorations. It would be better to choose another
capital for the country.''
   Rome's woes are probably best exemplified by its traffic
nightmare, an enemy that even Julius Caesar failed to defeat when he
tried to ban wagons and chariots from the city center in 45 B.C.
   Today, 1.8 million cars and 200,000 motorcycle and motorscooters
fight for space in ancient, narrow streets. With only one municipal
parking garage and no metered spaces to choose from, every day some
200,000 cars end up illegally parked, many on sidewalks.
   Despite the Italians' reputation for fast driving, cars in Rome
travel at an average speed of 6 mph, compared to 15 mph in most
other European capitals.
   The cacophony of roaring traffic, honking horns and screaming
sirens average 76.4 decibels, 11 above the level considered
unhealthy for humans.
   The gridlock never lets up since Rome actually has four rush
hours. In addition to the morning and evening crush, there is the
mad dash home for lunch and, following a siesta, the trip back to
the office.
   In the most drastic step taken so far, the city early this year
started banning private vehicles from entering the center from 7
a.m. to 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. Monday-through-Saturday.
   But the ban has only worsened the traffic on the outskirts and
barely dented the congestion downtown because thousands of special
permits are given to Parliament members, government officials,
journalists, doctors, judges and others.
   ``The Roman public eagerly wants the traffic problem to be
resolved ... but each of us rejects even the idea of leaving the car
in the garage for two or three days a week,'' columnist Miriam Mafai
wrote in La Repubblica, Italy's largest daily newspaper.
   Those who choose public transporation aren't muh better off.
Buses are so crowded that passengers shove and scream for a space to
breathe, while pickpockets have a field day.
   Rome's Metropolitana (subway) has only two lines and 15.5 miles
of track and transports only 400,000 passengers a day, one-fourth
the total of Paris' subway, the Metro. Officials say they can't dig
further because of all the archaelogical treasures lying beneath the
city.
   The lack of public transportation is one reason why 63 percent of
Romans drive to work each day. The resulting exhaust fumes make Rome
one of the most polluted cities in Europe, prompting some bicyclists
and traffic cops to don surgical masks and leading Italy's Greens
Party to propose that the entire city be put under curfew once smog
reaches a certain level.
   The smog also eats away at the city's ancient monuments, leaving
arches, columns and buildings concealed behind green cloth and
scaffolding for painstaking restorations that last years and deny
tourists a look at some of the symbols of imperial Rome.
   In the last quarter century, Rome has absorbed some 2 million
immigrants from other parts of Italy. But very few urban development
projects have been carried out since Rome hosted the 1960 Olympics.
   Plans for an archaelogical park extending from the Colosseum to
the Old Appian Way, a railroad ring around the city and an
underground tunnel have once again been put on hold.
   ``It will be a pity if Rome is unable to capitalize on this huge
opportunity,'' said Luca Di Montezemolo, head of the Italian
organizing committee. ``Two years ago I thought Rome could have
benefited the way it did from the 1960 Olympics, but it looks too
late now.''
   As public services, including electrical and telephone, have
broken down so have the patience, tempers and manners of many
Romans. Just watch them pushing and cursing each other as they try
to beat the line at a bank or post office.
   Sociologists have noted a rise in violence and racial
intolerance, including an incident in which an African woman was
chased off a bus by passengers shouting, ``Leave the seats to the
whites.''
   For all its detractors, Rome still has its eternal supporters.
   Said novelist Alberto Moravia:
   ``Rome is what the Italians want it to be. All types of Italians
live and work in Rome. Rome is a cross-section of Italy.
   ``Rome has always gone to ruin, but at the same time it has
always been very much alive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Dec. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
