<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Collins ADV20   12-16 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Collins, ADV 20,1013</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Dec 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Mine Field for Rock Stars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock superstar Phil Collins wanted a supporting
role when he did his first movie, and he didn't want to sing in it
because he wanted to be taken seriously as an actor.
   Instead he's playing the title role in ``Buster,'' the story of
Buster Edwards, one of the men who pulled off Britain's ``great
train robbery'' in 1963. He also talked himself into singing two
songs: ``Two Hearts,'' which plays over the ``Buster'' credits, and
``Groovy Kind of Love,'' a hit single.
   ``I'd have been happy going in at the shallow end rather than the
deep end,'' he says. ``It's a mine field _ rock stars acting.''
Critics have praised Collins' performance though they were lukewarm
to the movie itself.
   Collins also didn't intend to put himself in danger in his movie
acting debut. However, for an early scene establishing Buster as a
small-time thief, Collins said he'd bash in a store window himself,
using a metal garbage can.
   ``A stuntman said the dustbin could bounce back and hit me in the
face. He told me to hold it up in front of my face and make sure no
huge splinters fell down and cut my head off.''
   Collins had beginner's luck. ``When I break the huge plate-glass
window, go in, get the dummy and come out, that was one take,'' he
says.
   Director David Green got the idea of casting Collins as Buster
after seeing the rocker in his first acting role, as the host of a
rigged game show on a ``Miami Vice'' episode.
   Collins described Buster as ``a bit different from most
villains.''
   ``A professional thief is what he was. He came out of prison and
went straight back inside for shoplifting. For 13 years he has been
on the straight. He's got a flower shop outside Waterloo Station.
He's become a bit of a tourist attraction.''
   Collins met Buster Edwards. ``We've become very good pals,'' he
says. ``In personality I don't think we're that far away. He's a
very friendly bloke; I think I am, too. Our backgrounds are
different and we come from different parts of London. Since I was 5
or 6 I just wanted to be involved with music; he obviously didn't
have that kind of dream. When kids were going around causing trouble
I was home practicing the drums.''
   Collins became a drummer in the hit British group Genesis. He
revived the group's career in 1976 by stepping forward as vocalist
and then he became a major rock soloist.
   The movie takes a certain amount of poetic license, Collins said.
Buster's wife, June (Julie Walters), returns to England from Mexico,
where they'd fled. Buster followed because of his love for her. In
reality, the rocker says, ``June didn't like Mexico and they went
back to England together. He walked into a police station and gave
himself up. In the early '60s if you're working class you never
traveled far. You didn't eat spicy food or have a suntan.''
   When shooting began, the director kept Collins away from the
rushes, fearing he'd see things he'd want to do over. Then Collins
happened to walk in while rushes were being shown one day.
   ``I saw a scene I didn't think I was very good in, where I come
home from the robbery and have a confrontation with June's mother.''
He liked it, which gave him confidence.
   Collins' sister, Carole, plays a nosy neighbor in the film. ``She
auditioned for the part and got it. She doesn't do it for a living,
just the odd thing. She has her own talent agency, for adults. She
was a professional ice skater for many years,'' he said.
   ``My mother is an agent for kids. My brother is a cartoonist. My
father had the normal job in the family. He was in insurance in the
City of London for 40 years.''
   Collins said he wouldn't do the music and put the production
company in touch with Lamont Dozier. But he wound up being involved
afterall.
   ``He came up with a couple of songs that needed words. I thought
I should write the words. Because I was so involved with the film
and the part, I felt I could summarize the feelings in the lyrics.''
   Collins got involved in helping choose other music in the film,
too, such as ``I Got You Babe'' by Sonny and Cher, and ``Sweets for
My Sweet'' by the Searchers, which was No. 1 the week of the robbery.
   ``A Groovy Kind of Love'' was an uptempo hit for the Mindbenders
in the '60s. ``I thought it would be nice to have a slow version in
the radio for background, somewhere. I did a little demo at home and
the director liked it so much he used it at the end, over the
arrest, when I get taken away,'' Collins said.
   ``We looked at a list of songs we could use in the film, 10
seconds of some of them,'' he said. ``They're all just on the radio;
they give an indication of the period.
   ``The only song that's loud is the Four Tops' `Goin' Loco Down in
Acapulco,' when they first get to Mexico. Lamont and I wrote it.''
   But lawyers wouldn't allow them to use any songs by the Beatles.
``I found that very frustrating. I rang all the surviving Beatles.
They said, `yes,' but the lawyers wouldn't let us. I couldn't work
out why.''
   Collins would like to do another film, playing a different type
of character. He has an idea for a remake of ``Goldilocks and the
Three Bears,'' starring himself and three other actors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Dec. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
