<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Czechoslovakia Adv19   12-16 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Czechoslovakia, Adv 19,0827</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Reminder About Czechoslovakia in PBS Documentary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the midst of the enthusing over Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the remarkable reforms he has launched in
the Soviet Union, a PBS special Wednesday reminds that all is not
rosy on the other side of the Iron Curtain.
   The title of the documentary, ``Czechoslovakia: The Long Wait for
Spring,'' refers to the ``Prague spring'' of 1968, when reforms
introduced by Premier Alexander Dubcek raised hopes for new freedom
after 20 years of hard-line communism.
   A few months later, those hopes were crushed under the treads of
invading Soviet tanks. Today, little evidence remains in
Czechoslovakia of the ``Prague spring,'' which, ironically, Soviet
citizens seem to be enjoying under Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost.''
   The documentary crams a lot of historical, economic and
socio-political information into one hour, but also gives the
country a human face.
   Viewers are taken on a whirlwind tour of the country, from
Prague, just as modern and beautiful as many other European cities,
at least on the surface, to the grimy iron-smelting plants that seem
to have been lifted from another era.
   Indeed, the factories represent Czechoslovakia's biggest problem
_ economic dependence on the Soviet Union to support an outdated
heavy manufacturing industry. Czechoslovakia has little access to
other markets, except for its pilsner beer, Urquell, which is
exported to the West.
   In addition, Czechoslovakia is one of the most polluted countries
in Europe with its reliance on cheap brown coal for heating and
manufacturing.
   There are interviews with dissidents who hold little hope of soon
seeing the kind of reforms that Gorbachev has introduced in the
Soviet Union.
   ``You have to have a Gorbachev, and in Czechoslovakia so far no
one like that has appeared,'' says Zdenek Mlynar, a member of the
Dubcek government who was interviewed in Vienna where he lives in
exile. Forty years of hard-line communism and an economy hog-tied by
entrenched Stalinism will be hard to erase, he says. ``Now the word
is `go your own way,' but we have been crippled.''
   Other dissidents _ who took a chance just by being interviewed _
are part of a writers' group that was subjected to a government
crackdown after calling for recognition of human rights. One of
them, we are told, had been arrested five times before the interview
and again at least once since.
   Even more depressing than their own oppression is the dissidents'
despair over a spiritless new generation that has turned to drugs
and cares little for anything other than obtaining material
possessions.
   ``There is no aim of life, and everywhere you look you see the
result of this crisis,'' says Ivan Klima, an author who has been
published in the West. ``I think the young generation is rather
unpolitical and rather apathetic. They don't see any sense to fight
for any value.''
   The filmmakers also interview Communist Party members who seem to
live well under the system and enthusiastically support the
government. But the filmmakers are careful to stress that these
citizens were selected for interview by the authorities.
   Despite the problems lurking around the bend, Czechoslovakia
currently has the highest standard of living of any communist
country. ``The government's agreement with the people,'' says the
narration, ``is, we'll keep your stomachs full if you keep your
mouths shut.''
   Nevertheless, there are tiny signs of change. Czech filmmakers
are allowed to tackle such subjects as drug abuse, ``hooliganism''
and the black market in foreign currency. And the lack of
spirituality in the society has sparked a new interest in religion,
especially among young people.
   The film, a production of WTTW in Chicago, was produced by George
Vicas, a veteran television journalist who started out with the
``CBS Reports'' unit headed by Edward R. Murrow. He went on to work
for NBC and produce other documentaries for PBS, as well as the
National Geographic series.
   The principal writer of the film is journalist Sanford Ungar,
dean of the school of communications at American University in
Washington, D.C., whose father was born in Czechoslovakia.
   The documentary is a pilot for a possible new series on Eastern
bloc countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BRINKLEY ONE-ON-ONE WITH REAGAN _ ABC News' David Brinkley has
landed a one-hour, one-on-one interview with President Reagan to be
taped Wednesday and air Thursday at 10 p.m. EST. ABC News publicity
says confidently that Reagan ``will reflect on the last eight
years,'' and Brinkley has done his share of interviewing presidents
_ Truman, Eisenhower, Nixon, Kennedy, Carter and Reagan. ...
   INDUSTRY TIDBIT DU JOUR _ According to A.C. Nielsen, 62 percent
of the 90.4 million U.S. homes with televisions have no children in
them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Dec. 19</NOTE>
