<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-AnotherLook:Schmoke-Drugs Adv19   12-16 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Schmoke-Drugs, Adv 19,0951</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday PMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Response Negative Since Baltimore Mayor Launched Drug Legalization
Debate</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baltimore Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke, who
launched a national debate on legalizing drugs earlier this year,
jokes that he's often introduced lately as a man who once had a
bright future.
   Schmoke, a former federal and state prosecutor, acknowledges his
views on decriminalizing drugs are not popular among politicians and
says he would have dodged the issue if someone had raised it during
his race for the mayor's office in 1987.
   And yet he doubts America can prosecute its way out of the drug
problem and insists something more must be tried.
   Schmoke, 38, was Baltimore state's attorney about three years ago
when an undercover officer, wired with a bugging device, was gunned
down.
   ``I listened to him die,'' Schmoke said in an interview before
speaking in Westminster, about 40 miles north of Baltimore. ``One of
the drug dealers shot him just because this officer was in the way
of a major profit-making operation.
   ``I've prosecuted thousands of drug offenders. I'm not soft on
crime. But as a mayor and citizen, I feel I have an obligation to
call for an alternative to the bloodletting in the streets and to
the shameful seduction of our children into the role of drug
pushers.''
   Thousands of calls and letters poured into Schmoke's office after
he went public with his belief that the war on drugs should be led
by the ``surgeon general, not the attorney general.''
   ``Early on I had a lot of mail very strongly negative to the
whole idea,'' Schmoke said. ``The way my mail is running now, people
generally feel that I'm wrong in my conclusion, but that I was right
to raise the issue and that the debate is healthy.''
   Schmoke, a Harvard-educated Rhodes Scholar and first black
elected mayor of Baltimore, grabbed national attention in April when
he addressed the U.S. Conference of Mayors in Washington.
   ``I was asked to give a speech about urban crime problems. I had
the speech written and then over the weekend, I decided `I'm
changing the speech,''' Schmoke said. ``I didn't tell anyone on my
staff. I just rewrote it, called a person in to type it and gave it
to my staff on my way into the meeting.''
   In revising it, he added the suggestion: ``Let's at least have a
national debate about decriminalizing drugs.''
   He explained, ``I thought that either I would be dismissed as a
kook, or the issue would catch hold and cause a major debate.''
   Five months later, he testified before the House Select Committee
on Narcotics, where his ideas got a chilly reception from some
politicians.
   For nearly two hours, Schmoke told committee members that
expecting the criminal justice system to solve the drug problem was
unrealistic.
   He suggested eliminating criminal penalties for possession of
marijuana, providing addicts with methadone maintenance and
increasing emphasis on treatment, prevention and education. Schmoke
also called for a high-level commission to study the potential
impact of decriminalization.
   ``The biggest misconception is that people think I favor people
using drugs, which is not true at all,'' Schmoke said. ``Alcohol is
legal, but we don't favor kids drinking scotch.
   ``What I am saying is that the drug issue is twofold. It's the
problem of abuse and the problem of crime associated with drug
trafficking. The criminal justice system might be good dealing with
one, but it's sure not good dealing with the abuse problem.
   ``If addicts had access to drugs through the public health system
and not through criminals, they would not have to steal and break
into houses and shoot people in order to get to the substance.''
   Schmoke says he's encouraged that his comments have prompted a
debate.
   Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the narcotics
committee, is emphatically against any form of legalization.
   ``He says, `It's a dangerous idea. I feel that we must not
surrender in the war on drugs before we've even fought it,''' said
Robert Weiner, spokesman for Rangel. ``He asks `What do we do about
all the international treaties we signed to stop the flow of drugs?
He asks what kind of message legalization would send to young
people, and wouldn't it counter our anti-drug education programs?' ''
   Some athletes who had been taking anti-drug messages to Baltimore
area schools resigned from the education program after Schmoke
testified in Washington, Weiner noted. ``They said `Why should we do
that if the mayor is talking about legalizing drugs for addicts?'''
   However, Rep. James H. Scheuer, D-N.Y., another committee member,
praised Schmoke's testimony, and said he too believes it's time to
set up a bipartisan commission.
   ``Such a commission could avoid some of the political posturing
about drug issues that emerges as sure as the sun rises in the East
during every election year,'' said Scheuer, who believes America is
spending too much money on interdiction and enforcement and not
enough on treatment, education and prevention.
   Minneapolis Police Chief Tony Bouza agrees with Schmoke's call
for developing a national stategy to attack the drug problem.
   ``In 1966, President Johnson created the president's commission
on crime, which in 1967 gave us a blueprint for the future, gave us
a national strategy. We now need to replicate that effort,'' Bouza
said.
   ``Schmoke has really helped a lot by basically calling for `Stop
the music and let's bring a little thought to the process.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Dec. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
