<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv19   12-16 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 19 ,0687</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday, Dec. 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Commercial Real Estate; Boom and Bust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few things reflect investment fads and the
get-rich-quick mentality better than the commercial real estate
market.
   There is something about this market that seems ripe for
exploitation. And, since so many investors spy the opportunities
simultaneously they tend to knock each other off. Boom becomes bust.
   Some of the biggest institutions in America have played the game
and lost.
   Within the past 15 years, for instance, large commercial banks
tried to manage commercial properties and found the task required a
lot more talent than the mere understanding of an income statement.
   Much of the multibillion-dollar financial debacle of the nation's
savings and loan associations can be traced to a lust for real
estate profits and a departure from common sense. They guessed wrong
on their real estate ventures.
   Real estate partnerships sold millions of people on the idea of
cashing in on the big tax deductions of real estate. What a game;
the enterprise didn't even have to make a pretax profit. Tax
deductions would be the profit.
   Then Congress removed the tax deductions, suddenly causing the
real estate market to be one of many sellers and few buyers, a
situation that brings prices back to reality with a thud.
   Builders, themselves, are among the worst players of the game. So
true is this that it has become almost axiomatic that a sound way to
make money in real estate is to wait until the builder gets into
trouble and then lowball him.
   Decade after decade a very few investors with great foresight
ride the real estate cycle to the top and get off, leaving the vast
majority of investors to ride it back down. Hot markets cool
quickly; big losses replace big hopes.
   So much overbuilding has occurred during the past few years that
rents in some areas have actually fallen. In those areas, says
George Puskar, an authority, ``real estate has actually been
subsidizing corporate America.''
   Puskar, chairman of Equitable Real Estate Investment Management,
observes that rents are the second biggest expense for companies _
after payroll and benefits _ and rents have been flat or falling
because of the oversupply.
   Strangely, while commercial real estate attracts innovative,
daring and often highly successful entrepreneurs, as well as the
biggest institutional investors, it often has been run by the seat
of the pants.
   In the past, losses meant nothing to some of these entrepreneurs,
developers and promoters because they believed tax deductions,
inflation and divine intervention would bail them out.
   The tax deductions were eliminated, inflation calmed down in the
1980s and the divine interveners became occupied elsewhere. Only
then did some investors learn that real estate is a business.
   It isn't, after all, like stocks and bonds, which have liquid
markets. Hot real estate markets seem to be made up of all buyers,
but in a flash they become markets of all sellers. The Sun Belt
experience illustrates.
   Puskar states the newer, businesslike approach:
   ``You want to position investments in properties that will have
strong, steady cash flows over time and not be subject to boom-bust
cycles. You can't be successful looking to buy in on a surge and
sell quickly before a drop ...''
   Still, if the past remains a criterion, something new will be
introduced into markets in 1989 that will resurrect the same old
bullish enthusiams that lead to disaster.
   What will it be? Hard to say. However, there is growing concern
among important corporations owning first-class real estate that
they keep on the books at only a fraction of its market value.
   That's a dangerous practice these days because it might invite
raiders. The raiders might not want the company and its products
nearly so much as that undervalued real estate. They think they
might make a killing on that.
   It could be the start of something big.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon., Dec. 19.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Spotlight-Dominican Adv25   12-16 1120</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Spotlight-Dominican, Adv25,1152</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP SPOTLIGHT: Dominican Republic _ Columbus Anniversary Building</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spree
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDS:, the main story of a package of three</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Its roots go back to 1492, when it became a
landfall for Christopher Columbus, but today the Dominican Republic
has economic problems so severe that it has boat people fleeing to
Puerto Rico and the United States. Its links with Columbus, however,
have given the government of the Caribbean-island nation new hope as
the 1992 Columbus discovery celebrations approach.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This oldest capital in
the Western Hemisphere is filled with the roar of bulldozers and
clatter of jackhammers in preparation for the 500th anniversary of
Columbus' discovery of America.
   Hospitals, museums, libraries, schools, bridges and monuments are
springing up everywhere as part of a $500 million nationwide
public-works project President Joaquin Balaguer set in motion in
1987.
   It is the government's job-creating answer to an economic crisis
that has led to wage strikes, food riots and a flight of its people
in hazardous boat journeys across the Caribbean.
   Critics say the project geared to the Columbus celebrations is a
giant boondoggle that is fueling inflation while failing to tackle
the needs of the nation's 6.6 million people, half of whom are
involved in agriculture.
   They accuse the 81-year-old Balaguer, who is nearly blind with
glaucoma, of acting like an Egyptian pharaoh building pyramids.
   ``Balaguer is remodeling the city to the memory of Columbus,''
said Francisco Pena Gomes, a former Santo Domingo mayor and
political opponent of Balaguer. ``But these are unproductive works
because the agriculture sector has most of the work force, whereas
construction only employs 5 percent.''
   Much, though not all, of the construction is timed for the
anniversary in 1992 of Columbus' first voyage to the New World.
   Dating back to 1492 and the place where Columbus' remains are
said to be buried, Santo Domingo is hoping to attract thousands of
tourists for the 500th anniversary.
   The project's showcase is a 777-foot Columbus Lighthouse, with
beams forming a cross, rising above a rundown neighborhood near the
airport at a cost of $30 million. It is the butt of ridicule.
   `These days lighthouses aren't used by boats or planes,'' said
Juan Bosch, a former president and Balaguer opponent. ``So tell me,
what is the reason for this?''
   Government officials contend the works project has created
210,000 jobs and is underpinning an economy in transition from
reliance on the sugar industry, its mainstay for 400 years.
   ``I know my policy of construction has received a lot of
criticism,'' Balaguer said in an interview. ``But it has been
necessary to revitalize a stagnated economy and to produce jobs.''
   ``Everyone criticized the Versaille Palace, too,'' said chief
economic planner Guillermo Caram. ``And look at all the treaties
that were signed there. Who knows? Maybe in 1992, there will be an
armistice signed at the lighthouse between the world's debtors and
creditors.''
   By comparison with impoverished Haiti, with which it shares the
island of Hispaniola, the Dominican Republic is well-off and
politically stable.
   But economic growth nosedived in 1988 to 2.8 percent, from 8
percent in 1987, according to government figures. One of every three
workers is unemployed and inflation is officially pegged at 30
percent and estimated by private economists at twice that rate.
   The country's $3.5 billion foreign debt equals 68 percent of its
gross national product. The government has paid $780 million in
interest and servicing on the debt this year, but Balaguer says
relief will be sought with creditors because ``the national reality
is that we are not in a condition to pay.''
   From the daily ``apagones'' _ electrical blackouts that often
last hours _ to the proliferation of street hawkers, evidence of
economic distress abounds.
   At the U.S. Consulate, hundreds of Dominicans line up daily
hoping for a chance to go the United States, easily exhausting the
country's yearly quota of 20,000 immigrant visas. U.S. officials say
1 million Dominicans are in the United States _ more than half
illegally.
   Boat people cross the dangerous 90-mile Mona Passage separating
the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico. They sell refrigerators,
ovens and televisions for the $500 to $3,000 passage in flimsy
``yola'' motor fishing boats.
   Puerto Rican authorities say some 3,000 Dominicans have been
arrested since April. Countless others make it across.
   The government has recently been hit by a wave of wage strikes
that many fear will fuel protests similar to ones in February and
March, when price hikes in gasoline, milk and rice caused street
clashes that left six people dead and dozens injured.
   In Santo Domingo, with 2 million inhabitants, an estimated
500,000 people are living in unsanitary, crowded shacks as they wait
for new housing projects because the government bulldozed their
homes to make way for a beltway.
   ``I've been waiting four months for a new home,'' said
61-year-old Juana Sofia Lubierez, whose family of 11 is sharing a
one-room house built by the government as temporary shelter after
her eight-room house was flattened.
   ``And look at us,'' she said. ``We're living like pigs. There's
no water, no lights, no bathroom.''
   Many blame the country's problems on the depressed sugar
industry, which has been battered by U.S. import quotas, low world
prices and increased competition from beet and corn sweeteners.
   From 1975 to 1981, the Dominican Republic exported an average
815,000 tons of sugar a year to the United States. The U.S. quota
for imports of Dominican sugar in 1988 was 176,710 tons. The cuts
forced up to 60,000 out of work in the last two years and reduced
foreign exchange earnings by $80 million.
   There are efforts to diversify the economy away from its heavy
dependence on sugar. But the only sector showing significant
improvement is tourism, which has provided $676 million in foreign
exchange this year. The country's nine duty-free zones accounted for
an additional $400 million in exports to the United States.
   To brake the falling value of the Dominican peso, the government
closed foreign-exchange centers and cracked down on a lucrative
black market when the peso fell from 33 U.S. cents to 12 in March,
1987. It has since stabilized and is valued at about 15 cents.
   Meanwhile, building for the future goes on.
   ``Balaguer's vision of the Dominican Republic is different from
others, and there's a lot of criticism that he thinks the country
will be another Egypt,'' said a foreign diplomat. ``But is he right
or is he wrong? The economy is suffering, but who knows if in the
long term he isn't right?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
