<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Dominican-Populists Adv25   12-16 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dominican-Populists, Adv25,0597</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Dominican Republic _ Two Aging Populists Prevail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With b0516. One of a package of three stories.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly half this
century, two charismatic intellectuals with opposing ideologies have
dominated politics in the Dominican Republic.
   Joaquin Balaguer, the conservative incumbent president, and Juan
Bosch, his socialist foe, belong to an old breed of Latin American
leader _ a ``caudillo.''
   ``The caudillo is a social, political phenomenom of Latin
America, a product of our underdeveloped society,'' said Victor
Gomes Berges, a former foreign minister under Balaguer. ``Balaguer
and Bosch are the residues of this phenomenom.''
   Balaguer is 81 years old and nearly blind from glaucoma, but
otherwise in apparently good health.
   Bosch is 79 and equally robust. Both attribute their health to
hard work, strict diet and no alcohol. Neither shows signs of
slowing down.
   ``It may not be logical that a man who can't see can be
president, but I've done it,'' said Balaguer in an interview.
   Both Bosch and Balaguer are fiction writers, poets and
historians. Each has more than 20 books to his credit. Both are
savvy; both have mass appeal. But they approach politics from
opposing poles.
   Balaguer rose to power under the repressive dictatorship of Gen.
Rafael Trujillo, becoming his president. Trujillo was assassinated
in 1961, and Balaguer fled into exile a year later to New Orleans,
where he remained until 1965.
   He defeated Bosch in the presidential election in 1966 and has
been elected president three other times, most recently in 1986. His
four-year term expires in May 1990.
   Asked if he plans to run against Bosch, his declared opponent,
Balaguer said: ``At my age, I don't make definite plans.''
   But Dominicans expect a Balaguer-Bosch rematch.
   Educated in philosophy and law, Balaguer published this year a
witty, introspective book, ``Memories of a Courtesan in the Era of
Trujillo.''
   In it, he says he attempts to explain his role in the Trujillo
government, which despite brutal human-rights violation left
Balaguer's reputation largely untainted.
   ``Is there a valid morality for actions in political life and
another very different one for private life?'' Balaguer writes. ``I
don't know. But what is certain is that politics puts blinders on
men and converts them into docile instruments of causes which we
intimately reject.''
   Bosch went into exile in Europe during Trujillo's rule and
returned when Trujillo was assassinated. Two years later, in 1963,
he was elected president. It was the country's freest election in 38
years.
   But seven months into his term, Bosch's Marxist-inspired politics
resulted in a military coup. In 1965, a popular uprising called
Bosch back. Instead, President Lyndon B. Johnson ordered an invasion
by U.S. military forces.
   ``Johnson had even come to my inauguration,'' Bosch said in a
recent interview. ``Afterwards, he said I was a communist and sent
in the Marines. If I was a communist, I'd be secretary of the
Communist Party.''
   A high school dropout, Bosch is a self-educated man whose
intellect has earned him literary recognition and the nickname
``Professor Bosch.''
   He leads the leftist Dominican Liberation Party, which he founded.
   Bosch says he's not a Marxist ``except in the sense I follow
Marx's economic theories; but politically, I am not a communist.''
   He said he believes Franklin D. Roosevelt was ``the last great
statesman, a social democrat.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
