<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Dominican-Glance Adv25   12-16 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dominican-Glance, Adv25,0317</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Dominican Republic _ Facts and Figures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With b0516, b0517. One of a package of three stories</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on the Dominican Republic:
   THE LAND _ The Dominican Republic makes up the eastern two-thirds
of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola, which it shares with Haiti.
Its area of 18,700 square miles is roughly size of Vermont and New
Hampshire combined. The terraian ranges from fertile plains to
mountains and deserts. Pico Duarte, at 10,206 feet, is the highest
mountain in Caribbean. The climate is sub-tropical with an average
temperature of 77 degrees. Its main agricultural products are sugar,
cocoa, coffee, tobacco and rice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ The island was discovered by Columbus in 1492 on his
first voyage to New World and was was ceded by Spain to France in
1697. Haiti held the entire island from 1822 until 1844, when the
independent Dominican Republic was established. The republic was
annexed to Spain from 1861 to 1865, when independence was restored.
Unrest brought an invasion by U.S. Marines in 1916 and a military
government was in place until 1924. Gen. Rafael L. Trujillo took
power in 1930 and established a repressive dictatorship that ended
with his assassination in 1961.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ The population of about 6.6 million is
Spanish-speaking. Seventy-five percent are of mixed race, 15 percent
white and 10 percent black. Ninety-eight percent are Roman Catholic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GOVERNMENT _ Executive power is vested under the 1966
constitution in a president, elected by popular vote every four
years. Its bicameral Congress consists of a 27-member Senate,
representing 26 provinces and district of Santo Domingo, and a 92
member Chamber of Deputies. The nine-member Supreme Court is chosen
by the Senate.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
