<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv17-18-1stAdd   12-16 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 17-18-1st Add,0521</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 17-18</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: the 1990s.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other business news this past week:
   _The Federal Reserve's open market committee met to consider
tightening credit, but by week's end there was no announcement of
changes in the central bank's discount rate.
   _The Commerce Department said the U.S. merchandise trade deficit
for October narrowed slightly to $10.35 billion, but financial
markets were unimpressed by the news. The department also said the
deficit in the broadest measure of U.S. trade, the current account,
shrank to $30.89 billion from July through September, the smallest
imbalance in three years.
   _The government reported retail sales in November jumped 1.1
percent. In another economic report, it said U.S. industry operated
at 84.2 percent of capacity in November, the highest rate in nine
years.
   _The government reported that wholesale prices edged up 0.3
percent in November, for an annual rate of less than 4 percent.
Separately, the government said housing construction last month
reached its highest level in seven months.
   _Pillsbury Co. rejected Grand Metropolitan PLC's sweetened $5.5
billion hostile tender offer. The $63-a-share cash offer for the
food and restaurant company was a $3-a-share increase over Grand
Met's earlier tender offer.
   _Farley Inc. asked West Point-Pepperell Inc. to call a special
shareholder meeting to consider Farley's $1.4 billion takeover bid.
Pepperell said it would review a shareholder vote calling for the
meeting.
   _Pennwalt Corp. received a $760 million takeover offer from
Centaur Partners, a New York investor group. Pennwalt did not
comment on the offer.
   _Shamrock Holdings Inc. amended its $2.6 billion bid for Polaroid
Corp. to meet a federal court order that was blocking the offer.
Analysts did not expect the development to substantially change the
bid.
   _Financier Carl C. Icahn said he had raised his stake in Texaco
Inc. to 15.8 percent. Securities analysts said the move evidently
reflected his impatience at the pace of the company's
post-bankruptcy restructuring.
   _The Occupational Health and Safety Administration proposed
fining a Pepperidge Farm Inc. plant nearly $1.4 million for exposing
workers to dangerous working conditions. The company said it would
contest the alleged violations.
   _Barry Minkow, the teen-age entrepreneur behind the carpet
cleaning company ZZZZ Best, was convicted of fraud for swindling
investors in a phony restoration business.
   _CBS Inc. won network rights to broadcast major league baseball
by agreeing to pay $1 billion over four years.
   _Platinum prices tumbled in major world markets Ford Motor Co.
announced a program to eliminate the precious metal from the
pollution control devices used in many cars.
   _Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. said it laid off about 120
employees, largely in its municipal and equities departments.
Meanwhile, another large brokerage firm, Kleinwort Benson Group PLC
said in London it cut 35 jobs from its British equity trading
department.
   _Grumman Corp., in response to a Pentagon decision to cancel a
major bomber project, said it would eliminate 3,100 jobs, 2,500 of
them at its Long Island operations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 17-18</NOTE>
