<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-16 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0528</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum prices tumbled in major world markets one
day after Ford Motor Co. announced a pilot program to eliminate the
precious metal from the pollution control devices used in many cars.
   Ford revealed no details of the device but said it would result
in a significant cost reduction. Spokesman Bill Peacock would not
say whether any savings would be passed along to car buyers.
   Spot platinum on the spot market closed Thursday at $531.90 a
troy ounce at the New York Mercantile Exchange, down $34.10 an ounce
from Wednesday's close.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The agency regulating nationally chartered
banks ordered its examiners to look for banks that have taken too
big a chunk of the risky, but lucrative, business of financing
leveraged buyouts.
   The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, which regulates
about 4,400 of the nation's 14,000 commercial banks, issued a set of
guidelines Thursday for banks and government examiners to determine
whether a bank's safety is endangered by involvement in the buyouts,
commonly known as LBOs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of U.S. business failures fell by 6.3
percent during the first three quarters of this year, the best
performance in nearly a decade, according to a private survey.
   The number of business failures fell to 44,793 from 47,794 in the
first nine months of 1987, the report by Dun & Bradstreet Corp. said
Thursday.
   The decline was attributed largely to ``decreases in the levels
of failures in the oil and agricultural states.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorimar Telepictures Inc. has agreed to sell its
Puerto Rican television broadcast interests, removing an obstacle to
the entertainment company's proposed sale to Warner Communications
Inc.
   Lorimar's interest in the two stations as well as its ownership
of a third station in Pittsburgh has prevented the Culver City,
Calif.,-based company from moving ahead on its agreement to be
acquired by Warner in an exchange of stock and debt that has been
valued at about $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four former chiefs of the Federal Highway
Administration say they oppose proposals to raise the tax on
gasoline to reduce the budget deficit.
   Such a change, they said Thursday, would fall unfairly on the
poor, worsen inflation, deprive the states of a revenue source and
further delay improvement of the nation's deteriorating highways and
bridges.
   They spoke at a news conference sponsored by The Road Information
Program, an advocacy group financed by energy, insurance, automobile
and highway-construction companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.
decided to extend a 1984 antitrust settlement that requires the
computer giant to give certain technical information to competitors
in Europe.
   The U.S. company and the European Economic Community said in a
statement Thursday that the accord ``has come to serve as an
effective vehicle'' for resolving questions on how competing
machines can be hooked up to IBM equipment.
   The 1984 settlement suspended a 4-year antitrust case brought by
the 12-nation trading bloc against IBM.
</TEXT>
