<HEAD>Oil Prices Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking has helped drive down energy
futures prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The January contract for wholesale heating oil lost 0.19 cent
Thursday to settle at 50.94 cents a gallon on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, after jumping 1.86 cents Wednesday. Strong
gains also were made earlier in the week after the arrival of
sub-freezing temperatures in the Northeast.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Thursday, January unleaded gasoline, which rose 0.42 cent on
Wednesday, lost 0.07 cent to settle at 43.65 cents a gallon.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $16.35 a barrel, down 2 cents
from Wednesday, when it rose 37 cents.
   Bud de Gorgue, an energy analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., attributed Thursday's decline mainly to profit-taking
following Wednesday's rally. The strong performance had been fueled
by market optimism that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries would stick to a recent production-cutting agreement.
   But de Gorgue said, ``Many traders felt the market was overbought.
   ``You really can't put a lot of faith in the type of rally we've
seen because of the lack of volume. December is typically a slow
month,'' he said.
</TEXT>
