<DOCNO> AP881216-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Lorimar Bjt   12-16 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lorimar, Bjt,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorimar Agrees to Sell Two TV Stations, Could Clear Way For Warner
Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorimar Telepictures Inc. says its agreement to
sell its Puerto Rican television broadcast interests has cleared the
way for the entertainment company's long-stalled sale to Warner
Communications Inc.
   Lorimar's interest in the two stations as well as its ownership
of a third station in Pittsburgh had been a stumbling block for
Warner's proposed acquisitions of the Culver City, Calif.-based
company in an exchange of stock and debt that has been valued at
about $1.2 billion.
   Lorimar has previously announced plans to sell the Pittsburgh
station, WPGH, in a deal that is expected to be completed in January.
   On Thursday, it said it expects to complete the sale of its
interest in the two Puerto Rican stations, WSUR-TV and WLII-TV,
before the end of the year.
   The buyer was identified as an investor group led by Timothy
Brumlik of Orlando, Fla., who was said to have other television
interests serving the Hispanic market in central Florida. Terms of
the sale were not disclosed.
   As a result of both deals, Lorimar said that its merger with
Warner ``is expected to be consummated in January 1989.''
   Lorimar is a leading supplier of television programming including
such popular shows as ``Dallas,'' ``Knots Landing'' and ``Alf.''
   Warner, a records, film and publishing company based in New York,
proposed in May to acquire Lorimar, which has lost millions of
dollars in recent quarters, in an exchange of stock.
   But Warner's biggest shareholder, Chris-Craft Industries Inc.,
objected to the deal, saying it would violate a 1984 agreement it
signed with Warner when the two companies bought stakes in each
other.
   Chris-Craft, a New York-based media company, bought its stake in
Warner and gave Warner in return a 42.5 percent in its BHC Inc.
subsidiary, which operates a half-dozen television stations.
   Under the terms of the agreement, however, Warner was prevented
from owning other television stations as long as it owns 25 percent
or more of BHC.
   Chris-Craft sued Warner over the Lorimar deal last summer in New
York State Supreme Court.
   Warner proposed putting the Lorimar television stations in a
trust until they could be sold, but the court blocked the merger
until either Warner reduced its stake in BHC below 25 percent or
Lorimar sold the stations.
   Warner appealed the decision, but the lower court's ruling was
affirmed by the Appellate Division of the New York State Supreme
Court earlier this week.
   In a statement, Chris-Craft said, ``Hopefully, today's
announcement signals that Warner has finally decided to live up to
its agreement with us.''
   Lorimar announced in August that it had agreed to sell the
Pittsburgh station to Renaissance Communications. The sale is being
reviewed by the Federal Communications Commission, and Lorimar
expects approval by mid-January.
   But a Lorimar spokeswoman, speaking on condition that she not be
identified by name, said the sale of Lorimar's interests in the
Puerto Rican stations is different because Lorimar placed its
interest in the stations in a trust and is selling that rather than
the stations themselves.
   As a result, she said, Lorimar can shed its interest in those
stations without waiting for FCC approval.
   In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, Warner was
unchanged at $35.37{ a share. Lorimar rose 12{ cents a share to $12
in trading on the American Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
