<DOCNO> AP881216-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankerIndicted Bjt   12-16 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banker Indicted, Bjt,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-NY Fed Reserve Director Pleads Innocent To Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert A. Rough, who has long denied leaking
confidential interest rate data while on the New York Federal
Reserve Bank's board, has formally entered an innocent plea to
insider trading charges.
   Rough was arraigned Thursday before U.S. District Judge Dickinson
R. Debevoise one week after his indictment by a federal grand jury
in Newark.
   Rough is accused of disclosing information on the discount rate
set by the Federal Reserve Bank in Washington to principals at
Bevill, Bresler & Schulman Inc., a brokerage firm based in
Livingston, N.J., that later suffered a $144 million collapse.
   The government said Bevill, Bresler made millions of dollars and
avoided millions in losses because of the information, which Rough
allegedly exchanged for $47,000 in interest-free loans.
   Rough's attorney, Michael Himmel, said he would need time to
review thousands of transactions by the firm, which collapsed in
April 1985.
   Debevoise on Thursday set Rough's bail at a $150,000 personal
recognizance bond and limited his travel to New York, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Michigan, Florida and Washington, D.C.
   A hearing on pre-trial motions was set for Feb. 14, and trial was
scheduled for Feb. 21.
   After the hearing, Himmel and the affable-looking Rough declined
to comment.
   The indictment said that while Rough was president of the
National Bank of Sussex County in Branchville, N.J., and sat on the
New York Fed's board from 1982 to 1984, he regularly leaked advance
word on the local federal reserve's discount rate recommendation to
the national Fed, as well as the Fed's final determination on the
rate.
   The discount rate has a powerful effect on the securities market,
and has been called by Fed officials one of their most closely
guarded secrets. The rate is the interest the Fed charges on loans
to financial institutions and is regarded as an indicator of the
direction in which the Fed is seeking to push interest rates, which
affect the prices of bonds.
   After the Fed learned of the allegations against Rough, which
were first mentioned in April 1987 during testimony at a criminal
trial stemming from the Bevill, Bresler collapse, the bank tightened
procedures for the rate. Rough publicly denied the charges at the
time of the trial, repeating denials to investigators in private
interviews.
   Rough, a former chairman of the New Jersey Bankers Association,
was formally charged with conspiracy to commit wire and securities
fraud, two counts of bank fraud, one count each of wire fraud and
securities fraud and two counts of making false statements to banks.
   Authorities have called it the first case of insider trading
involving government securities and the federal reserve system.
   Rough resigned from Sussex National earlier this year,
prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0147EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-Converter Bjt   12-16 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Converter, Bjt,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Converter Announcement Knocks Platinum Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum prices should continue dropping sharply
for the next few days in the wake of Ford Motor Co.'s announcement
of a program to equip some cars with pollution controls that don't
use the precious metal, an analyst says.
   Platinum prices plunged on the New York Mercantile Exchange
Thursday, a day after Ford Chairman Donald Petersen announced in
Pittsburgh a pilot program using catalytic converters without
platinum.
   Ford has released few details of the new converter, which is to
be used in 1989 Ford Thunderbird and Mercury Cougar cars sold in
California, a state with the toughest air quality standards in the
nation.
   More than 75 percent of the platinum used in the United States is
in converters, which remove some pollutants from automobile exhaust
gases. Petersen made the announcement Wednesday night and that sent
Thursday's platinum prices tumbling.
   Platinum futures contracts for current delivery closed Thursday
at $579.60 a troy ounce at the New York exchange, down $24.90 an
ounce from Wednesday's $604.50 close. The heavily traded contract
for January delivery dropped the daily limit of $25.
   Earlier Thursday, the spot contract price, which is not subject
to the $25 limit, fell more than $60 an ounce before rebounding
prior to the close of trading.
   ``This is actually a collapse,'' precious metals analyst James
Steel of Refco Inc. in New York said. He said the decline came
solely because of Ford's announcement.
   ``In fact, it took everybody by surprise,'' he said. ``If you
asked any analyst, fundamentally they were bullish on platinum. It
looks like the futures are going to lock in at limit-down (the $25
maximum loss) for the next few days at least.''
   Metals analyst Bette Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. agreed.
   ``It is a very bearish indicator for platinum,'' she said.
``There may be other issues as we go on. It's also brought downside
pressure on the other precious metals.''
   Steel said the waves should be felt in Europe, too, where
platinum futures were being bought on expectations of increased used
of catalytic converters there.
   ``It's double-bearish now because we had put in our forecast for
`89 that we were relying on the Europeans to buy more platinum,'' he
said.
   Ford spokesman Bill Peacock declined comment on the reaction of
the commodity market to the company's announcement and declined to
detail any of the specifications of the new converter.
   He and Petersen said the device could save the company a
substantial amount of money. But Peacock did not say if any of the
savings would be passed on to consumers if the device proves
successful.
   He said the device would be installed in 40,000 to 50,000
Thunderbirds and Cougars, both made at a Ford plant in Lorain, Ohio.
   Bill Sessa, a spokesman for the California Air Resources Board,
confirmed that the cars have been certified to be sold in the state.
   Auto industry analyst Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of
San Francisco said current catalytic converters use about $10 worth
of platinum each, leading him to suggest that cost savings must come
from other areas, such as the cost of applying the platinum in the
converter.
   A catalytic converter is attached to the exhaust system of an
engine. Exhaust gases pass through it and react with a catalyst _
platinum in the current device _ to remove pollutants and produce
harmless materials.
   Peacock said the new device creates no materials other than the
water and carbon dioxide produced by today's converters.
   He declined to speculate on when the new converter could be put
into Ford's full manufacturing process if the pilot program is
successful. He said, however, it would not be during the current
1989 model year, which ends next Sept. 30.
   ``We don't want to be pinned down on a timetable,'' he said. ``It
is a very attractive opportunity because it yields quality and cost
advantages.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
