<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstInterstate     12-16 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First Interstate,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Interstate Cancels Spin-off of Bad Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp has decided to sell
off hundreds of millions of dollars in bad loans and unprofitable
real estate rather than spin them off into a separate ``bad bank.''
   First Interstate had planned to form a separate company _ the
``bad bank'' _ to handle $400 million in bad loans and unprofitable
real estate.
   But the company said Thursday it had changed its mind, based on a
re-assessment that put the value of the non-performing assets at
$225 million to $250 million rather than the original $400 million.
   The smaller pool of bad loans and real estate would be better
disposed of through sale, the company said. Additionally, because
the amount to be spun off was smaller than originally expected, tax
benefits of the deal weren't as great as planned, it said.
   The original plan would have given First Interstate shareholders
stock in two companies, a bigger, more profitable ``good bank''
shorn of under-performing assets, and the smaller ``bad bank.''
   The change in plan means the bad assets won't be shed by the end
of the first quarter of 1989, as originally thought.
   The asset sales will leave First Interstate with $150 million
more in common equity than would have been the case under the
spinoff, the bank said.
   The plan was part of a restructuring scheme announced in October
1987 to get out of lines of business outside those where the bank
has done best, mainly consumer and middle-market banking in the West.
   First Interstate, which has more than 1,000 banks in 21 states,
is the nation's ninth-largest bank holding company.
</TEXT>
