<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0748EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-16 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher today against the
Japanese yen, while share prices finished lower due to strong
speculation of an impending hike in the U.S. discount rate.
   The dollar closed at 124.10 yen, up 1.13 yen from Thursday's
close of 122.97 yen. After opening at 123.90 yen, the American
currency moved in a wide range of 123.73-124.75 yen.
   Dealers said the dollar strengthened in Tokyo after gains in New
York following an interest rate hike in West Germany, fanning
speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve Board may increase its discount
rate, the rate charged on loans to commercial banks.
   ``On a short-term basis, the dollar will remain on a firm note,
aside from the issue of pending U.S. fiscal and trade deficits,''
said Shinichiro Maruyama of the Industrial Bank of Japan's
International Treasury Department.
   Maruyama said Emperor Hirohito's ailing health also contributed
to ``triggering yen-selling.''
   The 87-year-old Hirohito has been bedridden since September,
suffering from internal bleeding.
   On Thursday, the West German Bundesbank raised its Lombard
lending rate from 5 percent to 5.5 percent. The figure is applied to
very short-term borrowings from the bank using securities as
collateral. The West German discount rate remained unchanged at 3.5
percent.
   A higher U.S. discount rate would tend to push up the dollar's
value and make dollar-denominated holdings worth more.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 48.98-point loser Thursday, shed 169.04 points,
or 0.56 percent, closing the week at 29,536.71. Volume trade on the
major first section was 800 million shares, the same amount traded
Thursday.
   Share prices moved up slightly at the start of trading, but fell
a sharp 413.54 points before the afternoon session, which saw a
moderate recovery.
   The market's main index failed to regain its earlier losses on
profit-taking, centering on large-capital issues, in reaction to the
growing concern of higher U.S. interest rates, dealers said.
   ``There's a 50 percent chance whether the Fed will announce a
raise in its official discount rate today,'' said Masahiro Umemori
of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0751EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-16 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher But Off Best Levels, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was higher in European trading late
this morning but was off its best levels after the West German
central bank reportedly started selling dollars in an attempt to
bring the currency down.
   Gold prices were lower.
   The dollar strengthened in Tokyo and Europe after gains in New
York following an interest rate hike in West Germany, which fanned
speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve Board may increase its discount
rate, the rate charged on loans to commercial banks.
   But the Bundesbank, the West German central bank, began selling
dollars at midmorning, driving the dollar down, traders said. The
amounts were small, they said.
   The Bundesbank wouldn't comment on the reports.
   Dealers in Milan were divided on when, or whether, the Federal
Reserve would increase the discount rate.
   ``I don't see the (U.S.) discount rate rising this year. At the
earliest a hike will come in January,'' said one trader with a major
Italian commercial bank.
   Another trader said she thought the Fed would hold off any hike
until 1989 and might try to avoid one altogether. ``I see the Fed
braving it out until January and then seeing what sort of shape the
dollar is in,'' she said.
   One dealer at a major West German bank said that barring massive
interventions, the dollar seemed poised to rise until the end of the
year on commercial demand that had been held back over the past few
months.
   ``Some people had expected new lows, and now they have to move
fast to cover their positions before the end of the year,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.13 yen to a closing 124.10 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 124.18 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7527 West German marks, up from 1.7485; 1.4765
Swiss francs, up from 1.4725; 5.9885 French francs, up from 5.9745;
1.9726 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9665; 1,292.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,288.00; 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2054.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8215, compared with
$1.8280 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $413.30 a troy ounce,
down from $416.45 bid late Thursday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of
$412.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $412, down from $416 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $7.81 to close at a bid $415.24.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.07 a troy ounce,
down from Thursday's $6.11.
</TEXT>
