<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-InterestRate     12-16 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Interest Rate,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgium Raising All Banking Rates Second Time In Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium's central bank announced on
Friday that it was raising the country's key interest rates for the
second time in less than a week.
   The Belgian National Bank said the discount and lombard rates
would be increased by 0.25 of a percentage point each to respective
rates of 7.75 percent and 8 percent.
   The bank also announced that it was increasing the three-month
Treasury bill rate by a quarter point to 7.65 percent. The
three-month rate is considered to be the most important in Belgian
banking.
   In addition, the bank is raising the one-month Treasury bill rate
to 7.5 percent from 7.35 percent and the two-month rate to 7.5
percent from 7.4 percent.
   The increase in the treasury bill rates takes effect immediately,
while the hike in the discount and lombard rates takes effect on
Monday. The lombard rate is that charged for short-term borrowings
from the central bank using securities as collateral, and the
discount rate is the interest charged commercial banks for loans.
   The Belgian move follows the half point increase in West
Germany's Lombard rate to 5.5 percent, announced on Thursday.
   This is the second time this week that Belgium has increased key
interest rates amid signs of a general rise in interest rates
worldwide.
   On Wednesday the bank announced that it was increasing the
discount and lombard rates by a quarter point each and raised the
three-month rate by a similar margin.
</TEXT>
