<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     12-16 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Inflation,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain's Annual Inflation Rate Holds Steady at 6.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual inflation rate held steady at 6.4
percent in November, the government said Friday, in the latest in a
series of economic reports which have somewhat eased concerns about
resurgent inflation.
   However retail prices rose 0.5 percent in November from the
previous month, the Department of Employment said, and Employment
Secretary Norman Fowler said, ``There can be no grounds for
complacency.''
   Fighting inflation ``remains a clear priority,'' the secretary
said.
   The government has pushed up interest rates to 13 percent from a
decade low of 7.5 percent in June to discourage consumer spending
and choke off inflation, which has increased from a 3.3 percent
annual rate in January.
   In October, the retail price index rose 1 percent from the
previous month and was up 6.4 percent from a year earlier.
   Market expectations had been for an annual inflation rate of
between 6.3 percent and 6.5 percent in November.
   The department said that the rise between October and November
mainly reflects increases in mortgage interest rates, as well as
higher prices for some foods, clothing and footwear. Excluding
mortgage interest payments, retail prices rose by 5.1 percent on
average in the year to November, the department said.
   The index, which uses a January 1987 base of 100, stood at 110.0
in November, up from 109.5 in October, and from in 103.4 November
1987.
   Fowler noted Thursday's news that the underlying annual rate of
increase in earnings fell to 9 percent in October from 9.25 percent
in September, but said the growth of earnings still remains too high.
   ``Moderation in pay settlements remains essential for the economy
and for jobs,'' he said.
   On Monday, the government reported that retail sales fell 0.5
percent in November.
</TEXT>
