<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv19   12-16 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 19,0636</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Dec. 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Earnings Play Catch-Up With Stock Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The past year has provided plenty of support for
those pundits who argue that corporate earnings don't matter much to
the stock market.
   When all the results are in, Standard & Poor's Corp. estimates,
corporate earnings for 1988 will be up as much as 40 percent from
last year, on top of a 21 percent increase in 1987.
   Yet S&P's 500-stock composite index showed a gain for the year of
only about 11.5 percent as of mid-December.
   The numbers also reflect badly on the image of the market as a
mechanism that anticipates _ or ``discounts,'' in Wall Street
parlance _ trends in corporate earnings six months to a year in the
future.
   The market's crash in 1987, and the meager increase it posted for
the year as a whole, hardly appear to have been accurate foretokens
of where earnings were headed in 1988.
   And these days, of course, the market seems to swoon every time
it is confronted with evidence that the economy remains strong and
is supporting continued growth in profits.
   Will all that, however, some analysts say the sharp increases in
earnings this year have done the market a lot of good.
   When the price-earnings ratio of the S&P 500 soared over 20 to 1
in the summer of 1987, they say, it reached dangerously overvalued
levels and had to come down one way or another.
   The first part of that reduction, to about 15 to 1, was achieved
by a drastic drop in stock prices in the fall of last year.
   Since then, by contrast, the market PE has been lowered further
in a far more constructive way through earnings increases, rather
than reductions in stock prices.
   The S&P 500 lately has traded at just under 12 times the last 12
months' earnings reported by the stocks that make up the index.
   Analysts at the firm's weekly publication The Outlook say the
multiple is barely more than 10 if you calculate it on the basis of
their earnings projections for 1989. It hasn't been that low since
1984.
   There is nothing to prevent the market PE from falling even
further. Indeed, it spent more than five years below 10 in the late
1970s and early 1980s.
   However, many market-watchers argue, at its current levels the PE
indicates that stocks aren't puffed up by overly optimistic
expectations.
   ``Last year's crash was triggered by fundamental overvaluation of
stocks,'' says Norman Fosback in the Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based
investment advisory letter Market Logic.
   ``Although price levels are the same now as they were in early
1987, underlying fundamentals have improved substantially.
   ``Earnings and dividends have grown, and continue to grow, and at
current levels will readily support substantially higher prices than
prevail today.
   ``Given the present reasonable valuation levels, moderate
monetary policies and modest economic growth, there is no reason why
the stock market cannot continue to advance, not only over the
course of 1989, but into the 1990s.''
   S&P's analysts aren't so sanguine about the market's 1989
prospects. They predict a ``bumpy'' market that may end the year 5
percent to 10 percent below its recent levels.
   But, looking at PE ratios, they also observe, ``stock valuations
are generally reasonable. Thus, long-term investors shouldn't
hesitate to accumulate stocks of companies with good earnings
visibility and strong balance sheets.''
   Maybe it's hard to see any year-by-year correlation between
trends in stock prices and earnings, analysts like these contend,
but over the long haul rising earnings count for a lot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon., Dec. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
