<HEAD>Airline Wants Recount</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir has appealed to the National Mediation
Board for a recount of an election in which the Teamsters narrowly
claimed victory to represent 3,700 fleet service workers in 100 U.S.
cities.
   The airline also asked the board to reconsider an earlier
decision that prevented voting by a number of other employees,
presumed to support management against the union.
   The two-member mediation board was to receive the airline's
request today in Washington, D.C., but might not act immediately,
said board spokesman Charles Barnes.
   The mediation board credited the union with 1,867 votes, four
more than the majority it needed to win.
   William Genoese, director of the Teamsters' airline division,
called the recount request a ``frivolous and desperate attempt to
cloud the issues and block certification.''
   Had the union lost, it would have been forced to withdraw as
bargaining agent for 2,000 fleet service workers it had been
representing in Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Buffalo and Boston.
   ``We were expecting more, but a win is a win is a win,'' said
Vince Hickman, business representative for Teamsters Local 732 at
Greater Pittsburgh International Airport.
   Contract talks have been stalled for more than a year.
   ``We're very up,'' Genoese said. ``We're ready to sit down and
negotiate.''
</TEXT>
