<2ND_LINE>BC-Northwest-Pilots,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest, Pilots To Begin Talks Jan. 4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mediated contract talks between Northwest
Airlines and the union representing the carrier's 4,800 pilots will
begin in earnest Jan. 4, a company spokesman said Friday.
   Northwest officials and leaders of the Air Line Pilots
Association met in separate and joint meetings this week with
federal mediator Robert Brown, said Alan Muncaster, a spokesman for
Northwest.
   The meetings were designed to provide Brown with background on
the labor dispute, Muncaster said.
   The parties agreed Thursday to adjourn and begin a full round of
joint talks Jan. 4, Muncaster said.
   The pilots and the airline were millions of dollars apart when
Northwest requested mediation in mid-November. The call for
mediation temporarily ended the union's strike threat. The pilots
voted overwhelmingly to walk off their jobs, but said they would
abide by laws that make a strike illegal during mediation.
   One of the sticking points in the negotiations is how to merge
the seniority rights of pilots in the aftermath of the 1986
acquisition of Republic Airlines. Pilots from the two carriers had
been working under separate contracts until they expired.
</TEXT>
