<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Bilzerian     12-16 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bilzerian,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Bilzerian Targeted for Two Felony Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Manhattan federal grand jury investigating
takeover investor and Singer Co. chairman Paul Bilzerian is expected
to indict him on two securities fraud charges, the Wall Street
Journal reported Friday.
   Quoting unidentified people it said were familiar with the
investigation, the newspaper said the charges could come as early as
next week and will focus on at least two takeover situations in
which Bilzerian was involved concerning H.H. Robertson Co. and
Hammermill Paper Co.
   The Journal said one of the impending charges evidently stems
from disclosures by Boyd L. Jefferies, a Los Angeles broker who
turned state's evidence in March 1987 after he was implicated in
securities violations by Ivan F. Boesky, the infamous insider trader
now serving a three-year prison term.
   The other charge was said to concern allegedly false disclosures
Bilzerian made to the Securities and Exchange Commission regarding a
source of money to be used to buy securities.
   Bilzerian, a one-time real estate investor with residences in
Florida and California, has been one of the most active investors in
takeover targets. He won control of Singer Co. for $1.06 billion
after a lengthy fight with the defense contractor's management and
is currently chairman of that company.
   Bruce Baird, the Manhattan assistant U.S. attorney for securities
and commodities fraud, declined to comment on the Journal story.
   Neither Bilzerian nor his lawyer, Arthur F. Mathews, returned
telephone calls for comment, and Jefferies' lawyer Kevin T. Rover
declined to comment.
   Bilzerian reportedly has been under investigation for months
regarding questionable trading activities. The Journal quoted people
familiar with the probe as saying the indictments expected against
Bilzerian represent only a portion of matters involving him and more
charges may be sought.
   The investor made an unsuccessful run at Hammermill Paper two
years ago but ultimately walked away with a big profit by pushing
the Erie, Pa.-based concern into a friendly merger with
International Paper Co. In 1985 he made a failed bid for
Pittsburgh-based H.H. Robertson, a construction materials concern.
</TEXT>
