<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UniversalFoods     12-16 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Universal Foods,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suitor Raises Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts company seeking to purchase
Universal Foods Corp. has increased its cash tender offer to more
than $600 million just one week after its initial takeover bid was
rejected.
   Amanda Acquisition Corp., a subsidiary of High Voltage
Engineering Corp., of Burlington, Mass., had offered $30.50 in cash
for all of the outstanding shares of Universal Foods.
   Universal Foods' board of directors last week voted unanimously
against the bid, and said it ``reaffirmed its commitment to remain
an independent company.''
   But Amanda on Thursday increased its offer to $35 a share.
Clifford Press, deputy chairman of High Voltage, said the deal would
amount to $615.6 million for the 17.1 million outstanding shares.
   ``It seems to us that you should be interested in exploring, and
Universal's shareholders are certainly entitled to decide for
themselves, whether the premium price that we are offering is fair
and adequate in view of the company's past performance and future
prospects,'' Press said in a letter to Universal's board.
   Paula C. Norton, Universal's director of corporate
communications, confirmed receipt of the new offer late Thursday.
   ``We did receive the increased offer,'' Norton said. ``Management
will take this offer to the board of directors, which will meet in
due course.''
   Amanda began its acquisition bid Dec. 2 and its tender offer is
scheduled to expire at midnight Dec. 30 unless otherwise extended.
   ``We continue to believe that our acquisition can be achieved and
we intend to consumate it,'' Press said. ``We are also mindful that
it is to everyone's advantage that the acquisition be accomplished
speedily, without causing otherwide unavoidable disruptions and
uncertainties to the company's business.''
   Press said he hoped to encourage the board not to exercise a
recently adopted ``poison pill'' provision aimed at blocking
unwanted takeovers.
   The poison bill gives the company's board and shareholders power
to increase the price of a takeover by issuing a large amount of
stock.
   The price of Universal stock rose 12{ cents to $34.125 per share
at the close of trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
Universal Foods makes and markets specialized food ingredients as
well as retail food items.
</TEXT>
