<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Japan-Platinum     12-16 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Platinum,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures Plunge In Tokyo On News Of New Catalytic Converter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures fell sharply Friday in Tokyo,
following the previous day's plunges in other major markets on news
that Ford Motor Co. had developed a catalytic converter that doesn't
use the metal.
   The near platinum future contract opened sharply lower and fell
further during the day, while all other contracts opened and closed
at their daily lower limits on the Tokyo Commodity Exchange for
Industry.
   Catalytic converters account for about a third of the annual
consumption of the world's newly mined platinum.
   Ford announced Thursday it would test the newly developed
catalytic converters in a limited pilot program but didn't say what
material the device used in place of platinum.
   The near December platinum futures on the exchange tumbled by 9.6
percent from Thursday's close to finish at 2,089 yen per gram, the
equivalent of about $679 a troy ounce.
   All other contracts opened at their lower daily price limit and
stayed there throughout the day.
   The January 1988 contract closed at 2,108 yen per gram, about
$685 a troy ounce at current exchange rates, down about 8.7 percent
from Thursday's close.
   The price limit on the Tokyo commodities exchange, as is the case
on the New York Mercantile Exchange, doesn't apply to the near
contract.
</TEXT>
