<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower,
then turned narrowly mixed in early trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Buying interest surfaced in the corn market on talk that the
Soviet Union would need to buy more corn for near-term delivery than
had previously been expected, analysts said.
   Rumors abounded on Thursday that the Soviets were in the market
for 2 million metric tons of U.S. corn. Today, traders were saying
the Soviet Union may need to buy 5 million metric tons of corn for
near-term delivery.
   ``That would put them over the market's most optimistic
projections,'' said Steve Freed, a grain-market analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Soybeans opened lower, then steadied on reduced chances for
weekend rain in the South American soybean belt, analysts said.
   Wheat prices were little changed.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.28 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent lower with December at $2.68 a bushel; oats were
\ cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at $2.24} a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 2 cents higher with January at $7.73 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent higher with December at
73.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
to .53 cent higher with December at 43.40 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .28 cent to .50 cent higher with February at 44.37
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures
finished mostly lower.
