<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AsbestosVerdict     12-16 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asbestos Verdict,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $7 Million To Families Of Asbestos Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix coding, slugline</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has awarded more than $7 million
in damages to the families of two men who were exposed to asbestos
while working at the Brooklyn Navy Yard.
   One of the men died in 1987 of a lung disease called asbestosis
and the other man is ill with the same ailment.
   The judgments Thursday were brought against three companies which
manufactured insulation containing asbestos: Owens-Illinois Inc. of
Toledo, Ohio; Raymark Industries Inc. of Trumbull, Conn.; and
Celotex Corp. of Tampa, Fla.
   The families' product liability suits, brought in federal court,
were consolidated because they involved the same companies and the
same workplace.
   A six-member civil jury awarded $4 million in compensatory and
punitive damages to Gertrude Higgins of Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., whose
husband, John, died last year at age 72.
   Higgins worked at the Brooklyn Navy Yard from 1945 to 1965 as a
``chipper and caulker,'' checking to make sure compartments on ships
were welded correctly and watertight, said the family's attorney,
Steven Phillips.
   He was diagnosed as having asbestosis, a lung disease contracted
by exposure to asbestos, in 1980.
   The jury awarded $3.15 million to John and Ann Marie Johnson of
Baldwin, N.Y.
   Phillips, who also represented the Johnsons, said Higgins worked
as an electrician at the Navy Yard during World War II. He is now in
the beginning stages of asbestosis, which takes years to develop.
   Both men were exposed to insulation containing asbestos, which
was wrapped around pipes and machinery on the ships, Phillips said.
   The jury found there was ``clear and convincing'' evidence that
the companies were ``wanton and reckless'' in marketing the
asbestos-tainted insulation.
   Phillips said he presented numerous medical studies about the
dangers of asbestos and internal company memos as evidence at the
five-week trial before U.S. District Judge Charles Sifton.
   John Hoff, a spokesman for Owens-Illinois, declined comment on
the jury verdict. Messages left for comment with the other two
companies were not returned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
