<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TigerIntl 1stLd-Writethru f0087 12-16 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tiger Intl, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0087,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Express Buying Tiger International</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 new grafs to UPDATE with earnings, further background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Express Corp. plans to purchase
Tiger International Inc., parent of the Flying Tigers air shipping
service, for $851.7 million, officials from both companies said
today.
   If completed, the buyout will combine Federal, the nation's
biggest package shipper with a company that has undergone major
restructurings in recent years to cope with financial problems.
   Los Angeles-based Tiger International will become a wholly-owned
subsidiary of Federal Express, officials said.
   Under the agreement approved by the boards of directors of both
companies, Federal Express will make a $20.87{ a share cash tender
offer for all Tiger International's 40.8 million common shares and
equivalents.
   Tiger International stock jumped $2.50 to $19.37{ a share in
early trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Federal Express dipped
50 cents to $46.75 on the American Stock Exchange.
   The offer is conditioned on at least 50.1 percent of the Flying
Tigers stock being tendered.
   The merger is subject to the approval of U.S. Department of
Transportation and the Department of Justice.
   In connection with the merger, Flying Tigers granted Federal the
option to purchase for $20.87{ a share authorized and unissued
shares of Tigers common stock amounting to 22 percent of the
outstanding fully diluted shares.
   Such an option commonly is known as a ``lockup'' and generally is
used to discourage competing suitors.
   Federal Express was granted the option to purchase Tiger shares
owned by Reliance Group Holdings Inc., amounting to 14.8 percent of
outstanding fully diluted shares, at the same price being offered to
all other shareholders.
   Federal Express has a fleet of 221 aircraft and 63,000 employees
worldwide. Flying Tigers has 38 aircraft and 6,300 employees
worldwide.
   Frederick Smith, chief executive officer for Federal Express,
said: ``The combination of Flying Tiger's international route
authorities, highly efficient cargo fleet and strategically located
airport facilities will enable Federal Express to accelerate the
development of its global distribution network.''
   ``While our two businesses have to date served different markets,
we believe the merger will result in significant operating
efficiencies which will benefit our respective customers,'' he said.
   Saul P. Steinberg, chairman of Flying Tigers International Inc.,
and chairman and chief executive officer of Reliance Group Holdings
Inc., said the agreement provides all Tiger shareholders with
excellent value for their investment.
   ``We have been a long-term investor in Tiger and have supported
the company through a highly successful turnaround,'' he said. ``Its
merger with Federal Express will open up new avenues for growth for
the combined companies.''
   Federal Express posted a profit of $118.8 million, or $2.28 per
share, on revenue of $2.2 billion for the first six months of its
fiscal year.
   Tiger International posted a profit of $56.6 million, or $1.52 a
share, in the first nine months of its fiscal year, up from $45.2
million, or $1.22 a share, in the same period a year earlier.
Revenue rose to $986.7 million from $878.7 million.
   The company disclosed earlier this week that it had been
approached by a possible suitor. Earlier this month, The company
said Steinberg, who also heads Reliance Group, was considering
making a proposal to acquire the Tiger International stock Reliance
did not already own.
   At the time, some analysts speculated Steinberg may have made the
overture in order to attract other potential bidders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BP-Kuwait     12-16 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-BP-Kuwait,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government Gives Kuwait Three Years to Sell BP Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday it would allow Kuwait up
to three years to reduce its holding in British Petroleum Co. PLC to
9.9 percent from 21.68 percent.
   The period represents a compromise between the five years sought
by the Kuwait Investment Office, which is the London-based
investment arm of the Kuwaiti government, and the one year
originally recommended by the British Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young in October ordered Kuwait to reduce
its BP holding to 9.9 percent after the monopolies commission said a
larger holding by Kuwait ``might be expected to operate against the
public interest.''
   The commission cited Kuwait's role as a member of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The Kuwaiti office was satisfied with the three-year divestment
period, said John Jeffrey of Stephenson Harwod, the office's law
firm. The time span gives the office sufficient leeway to minimize
its losses, Jeffrey said.
   In recommending a one-year divestment period, the monopolies
commission had said the timing of the sale should be subject to some
flexibility in light of current stock market conditions.
   The Kuwait Investment Office built up its BP holding, amounting
to 1.316 billion shares, by purchasing partly-paid BP stock in the
months following the British government's $13.2 billion public
offering of BP shares in October 1987, which coincided with the
stock market crash.
   The offering, which was far undersubscribed, included the
government's remaining 31.5 percent stake in BP, plus $2.7 billion
worth of new BP shares.
   Kuwait must sell around 700 million shares to reduce its holding
to the required level.
   Analysts recently have speculated that BP might be planning to
buy back the Kuwaiti-held shares.
   The speculation was prompted by BP's confirmation this week that
it is negotiating to sell most of its mineral assets to RTZ Corp.
Analysts say the sale could be raise about $3.5 billion.
   Once the Kuwaiti office has made the final payment on the partly
paid shares next April, the 700 million shares to be disposed of
will be worth around $3.3 billion.
   BP refused to comment on the timetable, or on speculation about a
share buyback.
   BP shares closed up 2 pence, about 4 cents, at 259 pence, or
$4.74, Friday on the London Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
