<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     12-16 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Friday against major currencies in
Europe as traders hedged their positions amid speculation of an
imminent rise in U.S. interest rates.
   Gold prices fell in nervous trading triggered by a slump in
platinum prices.
   The dollar ended the week higher against all key currencies
compared with last Friday's late levels.
   Dealers said the dollar moved up sharply in late trading partly
because trading volume was relatively light.
   The dollar began rising Thursday following interest rate hikes in
West Germany and Austria, which fanned speculation that the U.S.
Federal Reserve might increase its discount rate, the rate charged
on loans to commercial banks.
   But some analysts said the Fed's 6.5 percent discount rate would
remain unchanged at least until the end of the year because of fears
that an increase could disrupt stock markets in thin pre-Christmas
trading.
   Traders said the Bundesbank, the West German central bank, sold a
small amount of dollars in morning trading but said the intervention
had little impact on the dollar's rise.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.13 Japanese yen to a closing 124.10
yen, and edged up later in London to 124.22 yen. The dollar closed
last Friday in London at 122.43 yen in London.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8150 from $1.8280 late
Thursday and $1.8490 late last Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7635 West German marks, up from 1.7485; 1.4895
Swiss francs, up from 1.4725; 5.9950 French francs, up from 5.9745;
1.9805 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9665; 1,296.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,288.00; and 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2054.
   Gold prices fell about $4 a troy ounce in nervous European
trading. The market has been unsetled by a $70 dollar-an-ounce slump
in platinum prices since Ford Motor Co. announced Thursday that it
had developed a platinum-free auto exhaust system.
   Catalytic converters account for about a third of the world
consumption of newly mined platinum.
   Gold fell in both London and Zurich to a late bid of $412.25 a
troy ounce, down from $416.45 bid in London and $416 bid in Zurich
late Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $7.81 to close at a bid of
$415.24.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $6.12 a troy ounce
from $6.11 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
