<HEAD>Tyson Extends Holly Farms Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. said Friday it had
extended its $1.1 billion hostile tender offer for rival poultry
processer Holly Farms Corp. for a week to await court rulings
stemming from the battle.
   The $54 a share offer, which was to expire at 5 p.m. EST Friday,
was extended through 5 p.m. EST Dec. 23.
   James B. Blair, an attorney for Tyson, said that by the close of
business Thursday about 1.9 million of Holly Farms' 20 million
outstanding common shares had been tendered under its offer.
   Holly Farms, based in Memphis, Tenn., has rejected two takeover
offers from Tyson and says it will merge with ConAgra, based in
Omaha, Neb., in a $1 billion transaction. Tyson is the nation's
biggest producer of processed chicken and the three companies handle
about 30 percent of the ready-to-cook chicken market.
   Tyson is challenging the Holly Farms-ConAgra merger in court.
   Blair said the share offer had been extended in the hope that the
Delaware Chancery Court would rule next week on Tyson's challenge.
Tyson is seeking a preliminary injunction to block the ConAgra
agreement on grounds it was reached unfairly and was not in
shareholders' best interests.
</TEXT>
