<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st ld - Writethru, f0025,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher On Positive Sentiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished higher on the London Stock
Exchange on Friday, fluctuating slightly in daylong quiet trading.
   Dealers attributed the gains to positive sentiment inspired by a
growing belief that British interest rates might not have to rise
further to quell inflationary pressures in the British economy.
   The government reported Friday that Britain's annual inflation
rate held steady at 6.4 percent in November.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished up
10.7 points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,773.9.
   Dealers said the market gradually has been shaking off its
previous concerns about the effects of high interest rates on
British corporate profitability.
   Until recently, many analysts thought the government would have
to push base lending rates above the current 13 percent to slow down
the British economy and choke off inflation.
   But recent economic reports, especially average earnings figures
released Thursday and retail sales figures published Monday, have
suggested the economy already is responding to the higher interest
rates.
   Volume was a moderate 468.4 million shares, up from Thursday's
396.2 million shares.
</TEXT>
