<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a late rally triggered by
rumors that the Soviet Union had bought large amounts of U.S. corn
and soybean meal.
   Rumors of Soviet buying supported grain and soybean prices all
week despite the lack of official confirmation.
   Large grain companies such as Cargill Inc. and Continental Grain
Co. kicked off the buying Friday and ``suddenly it began to feed on
itself,'' said Pat O'Connell, a grain-market analyst with Refco
Inc., a Chicago-based commodities brokerage house.
   The rally accelerated through a number of buy stops, or levels at
which new buy orders are triggered, he said.
   Corn prices rose high enough to encourage a fair amount of farmer
selling, but the market will have to reach better price levels to
encourage further such selling, O'Connell said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 7{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.36 a bushel; corn was 2\
cents to 6\ cents higher with December at $2.74{ a bushel; oats were
1} cents to 6 cents higher with December at $2.20 a bushel; soybeans
were 6{ cents to 14} cents higher with January at $7.85 a bushel.
</TEXT>
