<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FederalExpress     12-16 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federal Express,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Package Delivery Firm Had Humble Beginnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tiger International Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick W. Smith was 27 years old in 1973
when he created Federal Express Corp., a company designed to
speedily fly checks and documents between Federal Reserve banks.
   Since then, Federal Express has grown into the nation's biggest
express package carrier and a dominant force in the overnight
delivery business.
   The Memphis-based company _ known to many Americans by its
offbeat television commercials and fleets of purple-and-white jets
and delivery vans _ reached another milestone Friday when it
announced an agreement to acquire Tiger International Inc. for about
$880 million.
   Tiger is the nation's biggest scheduled cargo transport company
and has substantial foreign routes.
   The buyout will greatly expand Federal's present fleet of 221
aircraft and workforce of 63,000 employees worldwide. Tiger flies 20
Boeing 747s, six DC-8s, and 11 Boeing 727s. It also has two Boeing
747 passenger planes used for military contract flights.
   Federal Express provides international service to more than 100
countries, either through subsidiaries, licensees or by using
independent contractors.
   Although for many people Federal Express' name is synonymous with
overnight delivery, that business actually began in 1929 when United
Parcel Service of America began flying Ford Tri-Motors along the
West Coast.
   But Federal Express did launch modern overnight express services
with its founding in 1973. Adopting elements from the ground system
of companies such as UPS, Federal Express invented an organizational
system used by most overnight companies today, known as ``spoke and
hub.''
   But even Federal didn't take off right away. The government's
cargo regulations limited the company to small planes, and it wasn't
until air cargo deregulation in 1977 that independent haulers were
allowed to fly planes larger than DC-3s.
   In the late 1970s, Federal virtually was alone in the market,
allowing it to establish its delivery and communications systems
without the pressure of competition. Other companies gradually
followed.
   The results have made Federal one of the nation's biggest
transportation-related concerns, with about $3.2 billion in
operating revenue last year. It still trails Greenwich, Conn.-based
United Parcel Service, which had about $9.7 billion in operating
revenue last year.
   Federal Express posted a profit of $118.8 million on sales of
$2.2 billion in the first six months of the current fiscal year. Its
revenue rose to $2.2 billion from $1.85 billion a year earlier.
   In June, Federal Express began package deliveries to Japan,
marking its first venture into the Far East, and recently bought a
100-acre sorting facility in Indianapolis with an eye to making it a
hub in the 1990s. Existing hubs are Memphis and Brussels.
   There have been setbacks. In 1986, the company shut down its
ZapMail electronic document delivery service after two years of
operation and operating losses of $317 million.
   In June, a federal judge in Nashville dismissed a lawsuit in June
by Federal Express challenging the state Public Service Commission's
attempt to regulate its truck delivery of packages between Tennessee
cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881216-0279 </DOCNO>
