<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Rescue,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FSLIC Aiding Ford in Michigan S&L Acquisitions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Friday they were
providing $118.3 million in assistance to a subsidiary of Ford Motor
Co. to rescue two Michigan savings institutions.
   The two _ First Dearborn and Bloomfield Savings and Loan
Association _ are being acquired by First Nationwide Bank, which is
based in San Francisco but is owned by Ford Motor Co. It has 400
branches in 15 states and $23.6 billion in assets.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which guarantees
S&L deposits up to $100,000, is providing First Nationwide with a
10-year promissory note with a face value of $174 million.
   First Nationwide is paying a premium of $39 million and is
turning over 80 percent of the tax benefits of the deal to the
FSLIC, bank board spokesman Paul Olhkovsky said.
   The two acquired institutions have 28 branches in the Detroit
area. They will open on Monday as branches of First Nationwide.
   The rescue of First Dearborn and Bloomfield bring the total of
thrift rescues and closing for the year to 155, a post-Depression
record. Last year, the cases of 48 failed S&Ls were resolved.
   Critics, including the congressional General Accounting Office,
say the bank board should be given the money to close failed
institutions and should end its strategy of keeping S&Ls alive with
promissory notes.
</TEXT>
