<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Slightly Higher in New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar's value rose Friday, strengthened by
intensified speculation about higher U.S. interest rates and
increased yearend demand for the currency by multinational companies.
   Gold prices rose in late U.S. trading after falling abroad, in
markets still jittery following Thursday's selloff in platinum. By 4
p.m. EST, gold fetched $413.50 a troy ounce at Republic National
Bank of New York, up 50 cents from a day earlier.
   Currency strategists said foreign exchange was influenced by
fresh rumors that the Federal Reserve was preparing to raise the
discount rate, which by late Friday remained at 6.5 percent.
   The discount rate is the Fed's interest on loans to U.S.
financial institutions and is a strong influence over other interest
rates. A rise would tend to bolster the value of dollar-denominated
investments.
   Some foreign exchange dealers said the dollar also moved higher
because of orders for the currency by U.S.-based multinationals
preparing to repatriate profits from overseas operations.
   Many companies evidently had been waiting to change currencies
until late in the year, hoping the dollar would fall as it has done
for six out of the past eight years, thereby making a conversion
more attractive.
   ``They figured they'd play that game again to the bitter end, but
this year it doesn't seem to be working,'' said Robert Hatcher, a
senior dealer at the New York branch of Britain's Barclays Bank PLC.
``So they figure they'd bite the bullet and buy dollars now. There's
definitely an underlying demand for dollars here.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.13 Japanese yen to 124.10 yen, and
traded later in London at 124.22 yen. By the time trading ended in
New York the dollar fetched 124.13 yen, up from 123.86 yen late
Thursday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8150 from $1.8280 late
Thursday. In New York, the pound remained unchanged from late
Thursday at $1.8193.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Thursday, included: 1.7583 West German marks, up from 1.7557; 1.4820
Swiss francs, up from 1.4783; 1.2034 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2054; 6.0090 French francs, up from 6.0075; and 1,296.50 Italian
lire, unchanged.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.7635 marks, up from 1.7485; 1.4895 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4725; 5.9950 French francs, up from 5.9745; 1.9805
Dutch guilders, up from 1.9665; 1,296.50 Italian lire, up from
1,288.00; and 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2054.
   Gold prices steadied in New York as the platinum selloff
subsided, after further depressing gold overseas. The run on
platinum Thursday was blamed on Ford Motor Co.'s announcement of a
platinum-free catalytic converter exhaust system. Catalytic
converters account for about a third of newly mined platinum
consumption.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
rose $1.10 a troy ounce to $414. In London, gold fell $4.20 an ounce
to $412.25; in Zurich it fell $3.75 to $412.25, and in Hong Kong it
fell $7.81 to $415.24 a troy ounce.
   Silver bullion for current delivery rose 2.1 cents a troy ounce
on the New York Comex to $6.082. In London, silver rose 1 cent to
$6.12.
</TEXT>
