<2ND_LINE>BC-Anheuser-Busch Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru,f0119,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Anheuser-Busch Executives, Ad Execs Get Prison For Fraud
Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final graf Orloff still...to DELETE erroneous reference
to Orloff still facing charges.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former executives of Anheuser-Busch Inc. and
two advertising executives charged with attempting to defraud the
company and the government were sentenced to prison terms and fined
Friday in federal court.
   The two former executives, Michael A. Orloff and Joseph E.
Martino, each were sentenced to a total of nine years in prison on
counts of mail fraud, conspiracy and filing a false tax return. Both
each were fined $10,000.
   Mark L. Shyres, one of the advertising executives, was sentenced
to a total of 14 years in prison on counts of mail fraud, conspiracy
and two counts of tax evasion. Shyres also was fined $10,000.
   U.S. District Judge William L. Hungate also ordered the three to
make a total of $30,000 in restitution to the brewery.
   Lawyers for all three, who were convicted Oct. 31, said the
planned to appeal.
   Marvin L. Cotlar, who pleaded guilty to conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service and cooperated with the government in its
case, was sentenced to four years in prison and fined $10,000.
   The judge stayed execution of the sentences until after the
holidays.
   Orloff, 38, is a former vice president of Anheuser-Busch
wholesale operations. Martino, 36, is a former vice president of
sales. They were fired in March 1987 following a year-long internal
investigation.
   Shyres, 44, was president of the now-defunct Bingham Group, one
of two promotions firms accused of paying Martino and Orloff more
than $52,000 in kickbacks.
   Martino had been on paid leave from his job as vice president of
marketing at Miller Brewing Co., the nation's second-largest maker
of beer. Miller spokesman Al Easton said after the sentences were
announced that Martino had been dismissed.
   The jury found the defendants had agreed that Martino and Orloff
would give Anheuser-Busch sales promotions business to the Bingham
Group in return for a portion of the amount of Bingham invoices that
they approved.
   Cotlar, 50, was president of the Hanley Group, a marketing
company closely affiliated with the Bingham Group.
   Hanley and Bingham paid the kickbacks with cash, gifts, club
memberships, airline tickets and payment of personal bills for
Martino and Orloff, according to court records.
   The jury found Hanley and Bingham recovered some of the costs of
the kickbacks by sending false or padded invoices to Anheuser-Busch.
   Orloff had faced a maximum sentence of 13 years in prison and a
fine of $16,000. Martino faced the same maximum penalty and Shyres
faced a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and fines of up to
$121,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
