<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   12-16 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0780</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Platinum Futures Plunge Again But Cash Market Steadies
^By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices plunged the permitted limit of $25 an
ounce for the second straight day Friday but cash prices steadied as
players reassessed the likely market impact of Ford Motor Co.'s
platinum-free catalytic converter.
   On other markets, coffee futures roared to a six-month high and
prices of palladium, gold, silver, grain, soybean, energy, cattle,
pork and stock-index futures all rose.
   Platinum for January delivery on the New York Mercantile Exchange
settled at $554.50 a troy ounce as traders attempted to bring the
price of the near-month futures contract into line with the spot
price for platinum.
   Spot platinum had tumbled from around $600 to about $532 an ounce
Thursday on news that Ford planned to test an automobile catalytic
converter that did not use the rare and costly metal.
   The use of platinum as a catalyst in the pollution-control
devices accounts for more than one-third of world platinum
consumption.
   Spot platinum settled $7.10 lower Friday on the New York Merc at
$524.80 an ounce after trading as low as $517. But analysts, citing
tight supplies and strong near-term demand for the metal, said the
markets had overreacted to Ford's announcement.
   ``It's going to take some time before the shift to the new
technology takes place at Ford and before other automakers use the
technology and before it gets to Europe,'' said Jack Barbanel,
director of futures trading with Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   ``Meanwhile,'' he said, ``everyone has to accumulate platinum to
put in their converters.''
   Richard Levine, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York,
said he was more bullish on platinum now than when the metal was
trading above $600 earlier this month.
   ``I would consider this a very good buying opportunity,'' he said.
   Ford has not specified which element will replace platinum in its
new converter, but many experts have speculated that it would be
palladium, a metal similar to, but much cheaper than platinum and
which is already used in conjunction with platinum in most
converters.
   Prices of palladium futures, which also are traded on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, soared the daily trading limit of $6 an
ounce Friday with the active March contract settling at $136.25.
   Gold and silver futures gained slightly on New York's Commodity
Exchange after falling sharply in the previous session in sympathy
with platinum.
   Gold was $1 to $1.10 higher with February at $417.60 an ounce;
silver was 2 cents to 2.3 cents higher with March at $6.205 a troy
ounce.
   Coffee futures rocketed to their highest levels since June 10 in
a storm of buying linked to bullish fundamentals, including late
harvests in Central America and Colombia, and a drought and
dockworkers' strike in Brazil.
   Coffee settled 5.64 cents to 8.37 cents higher with March at
$1.4035 a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures moved sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade in a late rally triggered by rumors that the Soviet
Union had bought large amounts of U.S. corn and soybean meal,
analysts said.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 7{ cents higher with December at $4.36 a
bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 6 cents higher with December at $2.74\
a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 7{ cents higher with December at
$2.21{ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 14\ cents higher with
January at $7.86{ a bushel.
   Strong cash markets boosted pork futures on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while cattle futures finished mostly higher
ahead of the Agriculture Department's monthly cattle-on-feed report.
   Live cattle settled .08 cent to .48 cent higher with December at
73.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .20 cent higher
with January at 84.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent to .82
cent higher with December at 43.82 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .95 cent to 1.20 cents higher with February at 45.07
cents a pound.
   In energy futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 23 cents to 37 cents
higher with January at $16.72 a barrel; heating oil was .48 cent to
1.08 cents higher with January at 52.02 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .71 cent to 1.51 cents higher with January at 45.13
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 1.15 points higher at 278.85. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
