<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished little changed in quiet
trading Friday as market watchers said there were indications the
Federal Reserve had tightened credit conditions.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond finished unchanged from late Thursday
while its yield held at 9.05 percent.
   Shorter-term governments posted some slight gains and tax-exempt
issues were higher, but corporate prices slipped.
   Credit-market watchers said evidence was mounting that the
Federal Reserve had decided to tighten credit conditions, possibly
in response to recent indications of rapid economic growth that
could fuel higher inflation.
   Federal Reserve policymakers met in private this week, but
normally don't report or comment on what steps they may have taken
for about six weeks.
   In the absence of a clear statement from the Fed, market watchers
look for other signals that may indicate what it has decided to do.
   Several analysts noted the central bank failed to take
significant steps for the second day in a row to relieve upward
pressure on the federal funds rate, the interest that banks charge
each other for short-term overnight loans.
   The federal funds rate was quoted at 8~ percent late Friday,
unchanged from late Thursday. The rate had been fluctuating near 8{
percent in the past few weeks before Thursday.
   William Sullivan Jr., director of money market research for Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said the Fed's failure to buy securities and
increase the money available to the banking system indicated the
central bank had tightened.
   He said he expects the Fed soon will raise the discount rate, its
charge on loans to financial institutions, which now is 6{ percent.
   ``I'm surprised they haven't moved on the discount rate
already,'' he said.
   Sullivan also said expects banks to soon boost their prime rate,
which is at 10{ percent and is used as a benchmark for bank interest
on a variety of business and consumer loans.
   Sullivan said the bond market showed little reaction to a new
report that producer prices rose 0.3 percent in November. The rise
was widely expected.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments rose 1-32 point, intermediate issues were up [ point and
20-year issues were steady, the Telerate Inc. financial-information
service said.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, edged up 0.60 to 1,130.38.
   Corporate bond prices slipped. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate
Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds
with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.03 to 292.92.
   In the tax-exempt market, prices rose 5-32 point, according to
the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively-traded municipal issues.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.42 percent as the
discount slipped 2 basis points to 8.15 percent. Yields on six-month
bills held at 8.68 percent as the discount was unchanged at 8.22
percent. Yields on 1-year bills fell to 9.12 percent as the discount
fell 5 basis points to 8.43 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
