<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Head Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures have ended a week of volatile
trading with sharply higher prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
unleaded gasoline settled at 45.13 cents a gallon Friday, up 1.48
cents from the close Thursday, when it lost 0.07 cent. Other
contract months also showed big gains.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Friday, wholesale home heating oil jumped 1.08 cents to 52.02 cents
a gallon, after falling 0.19 cent Thursday.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $16.72 a barrel, up 37 cents
from Thursday. It fell 2 cents in the previous session.
   Analysts attributed Friday's increase largely to optimism that
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would stick to its
production-cutting pact reached last month in Vienna. The 13-nation
cartel agreed to keep daily output levels at 18.5 million barrels to
push up sagging worldwide oil prices.
   Marketwide optimism about OPEC brought oil prices sharply higher
throughout the week, but subsequent profit-taking pushed down those
gains.
   Although the OPEC pact doesn't go into effect until Jan. 1, there
are reports that some OPEC members already have started to slash
output, said Robert Murphy, a vice president at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   He said the heating oil market was helped by the continued cold
weather in the Northeast.
</TEXT>
